Commentary.Commentary: We are back for New Zealand's reply! The umpires are back out in the middle and the English players take their position on the field. It will be Devon Conway and Tom Latham to open the innings for New Zealand. James Anderson has the brand-new pink cherry in hand and is raring to go. Let's play...
... SECOND INNINGS ...

Right then, 325 isn't the biggest score on this deck but one can understand Ben Stokes' decision to declare here. If England are able to make use of the proper ball, then they would be firmly in the driver's seat. The New Zealand openers however will look to ride the early storm from the likes of James Anderson and Stuart Broad and remain unscathed. We shall find out how things unfold as the Kiwi reply is coming up shortly.

New Zealand will be happy to have restricted England after the Dinner break but won't be that pleased as they now have to face the new ball under lights which could prove to be decisive. Neil Wagner was all over the place with the new ball but showed his class with the old ball and bounced out the English lower order to end with four wickets. Scott Kuggeleijn too bowled well from the other end after the interval and the pair of them ran through the lower order.

Oh, well Ben Stokes has decided to declare! England finish up with 325/9 and Ben Stokes and co want to bowl late on Day 1 under lights and make the most use of the new ball. They went into the break being 279/5 but it all went downhill after the break as the Kiwi bowlers bowled aggressive lengths. Harry Brook fell 11 short of what would have been a fourth hundred in as many Test matches as well. The pair of Brook and Ben Foakes put on 89 runs for the 6th wicket which took the visitors over the 300-run mark.

OUT! CAUGHT! Another one bites the dust! Neil Wagner goes short again and at the batter, Jack Leach goes for the pull but gets cramped for room. Ends up chipping this one to Tom Latham at short leg who completes the catch on the second attempt. With the fall of this wicket, England have declared their innings!
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Latham b Neil Wagner

Commentary.Commentary: Slower and fuller on leg by Neil Wagner, Jack Leach backs away but cannot get this one away on the leg side.
Switches to 'round the wicket and bowls it short on leg, Ollie Robinson turns this one towards behind square on the leg side but fails to get it past leg slip.
FOUR! Pace on this time and back of a length on leg, Ollie Robinson moves to the leg side and slaps it back over the bowler's head for a boundary.
Bowls this one slower and on a length on middle and leg, Ollie Robinson backs away and keeps this one out.
Banged in short and aimed at the batter, Ollie Robinson ducks under it once again and leaves it alone.
Short of a length but angling down the leg side, Ollie Robinson ducks under it and lets it go through to the keeper.
Back of a length around off by Scott Kuggeleijn, Ollie Robinson clears his front leg and slaps this one straight to mid off.
Neil Wagner follows the batter and bowls it short at him, Jack Leach steers this one on the bounce towards gully.
Goes short and around middle, Ollie Robinson helps this one towards fine leg for a single.
Short of a length on leg, Jack Leach turns this one towards square leg and gets off the mark with a single.

Another bumper at the batter, Jack Leach stays on the back foot and tries to fend off this one. Gets into an awkward positon and the ball hits him on the gloves. Luckily for him, the ball trickles past the off stump.
Jack Leach walks out to bat now.

OUT! IN THE AIR AND GONE! Neil Wagner has the last laugh! Keeps it short and bowls this one outside off, Ben Foakes moves to the leg side and looks to go through the off side. Does not get a proper connection and spoons a simple catch towards mid off. Kane Williamson there back tracks and takes a good catch. England slip further in their quest to go for boundaries.
Commentary.Howout: c Kane Williamson b Neil Wagner

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Runs continue to flow for England! Neil Wagner bowls this one short of a length on middle and leg, Ben Foakes backs away and drills this one towards the vacant mid on region for a boundary.
FOUR MORE! Persists with the short length, Ollie Robinson makes room by moving to the leg side, uses the pace of the delivery and ramps it over the slip cordon for yet another boundary.
FOUR! Clubbed away by Ollie Robinson! Scott Kuggeleijn goes short again at the batter, Ollie Robinson moves away and frees his arms. Flat bats this one towards the mid-wicket fence for a boundary.
Shortish delivery outside off, Ollie Robinson hangs back and pulls this one through mid-wicket. Opens his account with a couple of runs.
Another bumper aimed at the batter, Ollie Robinson ducks under it and lets it go.
Ollie Robinson is the new man in.

OUT! CAUGHT! The short ball ploy to Stuart Broad reaps the reward for New Zealand! Banged in short and on middle by Scott Kuggeleijn, Stuart Broad clears his front leg and moves to the leg side. Pulls this one but gets it from the bottom part of the bat and holes out to Devon Conway at deep square leg who makes no mistake. Scott Kuggeleijn gets his second wicket as England lose their 7th wicket.
Commentary.Howout: c Devon Conway b Scott Kuggeleijn

Commentary.Commentary: Back of a length at the batter, Ben Foakes tucks this one off his hips towards deep square leg for a single.
Fuller and at the stumps, Broad steps out yet again and mistimes it toward mid-wicket.

Excellent effort in the deep from Blair Tickner. Banged in short and Stuart Broad steps out, pulling it away flat and toward deep backward square leg. Tickner at deep square leg runs around to his left and pulls it back in with his left hand. They get a couple of runs.
Fuller and angling in from around middle, Broad hits it straight to mid on.
Good length on off, Broad pushes it back to the bowler.

FOUR LEG BYES! An aggressive charge down the wicket first up from Stuart Broad. Wagner sees him coming and bowls it full on the legs, Broad misses the flick and the ball deflects off the pads before running away into the fine leg fence.
Stuart Broad comes out to bat.

OUT! DRAGGED ON! Neil Wagner gets his man and Harry Brook too falls short of his hundred. Wagner rattled Brook last over with a peach and again digs it in short and keeps the line very close to the off pole. Brook backs away and looks to drag the pull shot but is through his shot a bit early. The ball takes the bottom edge and just goes through his legs and hits the top of the stumps. Brook is disappointed but he played a fine knock.
Commentary.Howout: b Neil Wagner

Commentary.Commentary: Dug in short and a bit outside off, Foakes slaps it straight to cover.
Back of a length around off, dabbed down onto the off side.
Beaten! Scott Kuggeleijn pitches this one up around the fifth stump line and Ben Foakes is drawn forward. Foakes has a little feel for it before the ball zips past the outside edge.
On a hard length and angling into the body, Harry Brook stays leg side of the ball and flicks it down to fine leg for one more.
A tad shorter and on the pads again, Foakes tucks it away to deep mid-wicket for a run.
Good length on the pads, Foakes works it away to the left of the man at fine leg for a couple of runs.
A length ball around off, Brook blocks it out.
Slight halt! Harry Brook has been hit on the helmet and he will now undergo the concussion protocol. He puts his helmet back on and the play will resume now.

Ouch, that must have hurt! Neil Wagner gets on right on the money as he digs it in short over middle and leg. The ball comes quickly off the deck and at a difficult height. Harry Brook is taken aback and gets a blow to the side of the helmet. Hope he is fine.

Risky single and if that had hit, Harry Brook was a goner! Full and wide again, Ben Foakes pushes it to the right of the man at short cover and sets off for the single. Michael Bracewell there makes a sharp stop and whilst imbalanced has a shy at the batter's end but misses.
Nice and full outside off and slanting across, Foakes leaves it alone.
Goes a bit fuller now and angles it well across the off stump, Foakes taps it out toward cover.
Short one around the rib cage, Brook tucks it neatly to deep backward square leg and picks up a single.
Shorter and on the body, this is worked away down to fine leg for one.
Back of a length around off, Brook hops on the back foot and just knocks it down fine of the fielder at third man for a couple of runs.
Another bumper, over middle and angling in a bit, Harry Brook ducks under it.
Good length around the top of off, Brook blocks it back onto the deck.
Around the top of off and middle, Brook nudges it leg side.
WIDE! Bangs it in halfway down the pitch and the ball just sails over Brook's head. Wide called.
FOUR! Nicely done! Good length around off, Harry Brook stays back and lets the ball come to him before just dabbing it down in between wide slip and gully for a boundary.
Pitches it a bit further up and bowls it well outside off, Foakes doesn't play at it.
Good length, close to the off stump and angling across, Foakes makes a good leave.
Fractionally short and around off, Harry Brook jabs it along the ground to deep mid-wicket for a single.
Short again and around off, Brook leaves it alone this time.
A good bumper, just around the leg stump and coming in at a difficult height. Harry Brook goes after it but fails to make a connection.

Leg bye! Optimistic appeal for lbw but it is turned down. Good length around leg and angling across the right-hander. Ben Foakes gets pushed on the back foot and looks to flick. The ball pings him on the pads and goes toward backward square leg. They get a leg bye.
Hard length around off, Brook solidly blocks it out.
Good delivery! Back of a length and close to the off stump, Harry Brook hangs back and looks to have a dab at it but the ball zips past the outside edge.
WIDE! Scott Kuggeleijn puts in the extra effort and bowls a bumper over the stumps, this one just flies over Brook's head and a wide is called.

Spooned in the air but lands safely! This is dug in around off but doesn't rise up much. Ben Foakes gets caught on the crease and he tries to pull. The ball gets sliced up in the air off the toe end and lands safely around the short square leg region.
Good length around the top of off, blocked out.
A slower bumper, around off stump and getting it in at a good height. Ben Foakes looks to take it on but gets a bottom edge down to the keeper.
Starts off with a loosener down the leg side and Foakes misses the flick.
It will be Scott Kuggeleijn to bowl from the other end.
Bowls it back of a length and over off stump, Harry Brook gets behind the line of the ball and makes the block.
A tad shorter and on leg stump, tucked away off the hips to deep backward square leg for a single.
Goes full now and bowls it around off, Foakes pushes it straight back.
Good length, around off and angling across, Foakes stays back and taps it toward point.
Pitches it up now in that channel around off, Foakes leaves it alone.
On a good length around off, Ben Foakes solidly keeps it out.

We are back for the post-dinner session. As the players make their way out in the middle, there is some lightning in the distance. Let's hope that the rain stays away. It will be Neil Wagner to get the proceedings underway with the ball in the third session. Let's play...
... DAY 1, SESSION 3 ...

Managing to bowl the first maiden of the Test in the 47th over of the game sums up New Zealand's story with the ball so far. Having failed to make a mark in the first session, the hosts needed to strike early in the second session and they did just that dismissing Joe Root and Ollie Pope in quick succession. They switched to bowling short stuff and that brought about success for them as Ben Stokes pulled one straight to Tom Latham off Scott Kuggeleijn's bowling. Having reduced England to 209-5, New Zealand failed to capitalize and let it slip from thereon. Tim Southee has truly led from the front with two wickets and he will require support from other bowlers in the post-dinner session. Do join us back at 11.30 am IST (6.00 am GMT) for the third and final session on Day 1.

Session Summary - 25 overs, 145 runs and 3 wickets. Another entertaining session comes to an end and it will be England who will be the happier side going into the break. Joe Root and Ollie Pope resumed their innings after tea and were positive in their approach. However, the same approach brought about their downfall with both batters departing one after the other. Ben Stokes joined Harry Brook in the middle and played the second fiddle in the partnership. He got off to a start but could not carry on and his dismissal put England in a spot of bother with 5 wickets down. Ben Foakes took his time initially but once set forged a solid recovery with Harry Brook. The duo have stitched an unbeaten 70-run stand to put England in a commanding position.
Tossed up again around off and turning in, Harry Brook solidly keeps it out off the front foot. And, that will be the end of the second session on Day 1!
Tosses it up now outside off, Ben Foakes uses his feet and works it through wide mid on for one more.
Slower and turning onto the pads, Harry Brook waits for it and turns it through square leg for a single.
Drifted onto middle and leg, Brook flicks it away in front of short leg.
Flatter one, around off and turning in sharply, Brook goes deep in his crease to keep it out.
This is bowled full and around off, Brook mistimes the push back to the bowler.
New Zealand have done it, they have finally bowled a maiden over in this game. Pitched up in the channel around off and left alone by Ben Foakes.
Hard length around off and just seaming away a touch, Foakes eases it toward cover.
A touch fuller, angling into the off pole, Foakes leans forward and pushes it to mid on.
Good length again, on a tighter line around the off stump, Foakes blocks it from inside his crease.
Pitches it a bit further up and keeps it outside off, Ben Foakes lets it through to the keeper.
Good length around the fifth stump line, Foakes goes back and across to defend.
Shortens the length and gets it to turn in a bit, Harry Brook blocks it out.
Tossed up around middle, this is pushed away to mid on for a single.
Flighted delivery on a length and around off, Foakes nudges it onto the leg side.
Drifts one onto the legs, Brook stays back and works it 'round the corner for a single.
Quicker and shorter around off, punched away through the cover region without much timing for one.
FOUR! Classy shot! Tossed up outside off, Ben Foakes comes down the pitch and wrists it away in between mid on and mid-wicket and the ball trickles away into the fence.
Michael Bracewell is back into the attack.

Direct hit but Ben Foakes is well in! Good length around the top of off, worked away to wide mid on for a quick run. Blair Tickner there picks it up and throws it onto the stumps at the bowler's end but to no avail.
FOUR! Ben Foakes is holding back either and New Zealand continue to bleed runs. Fractionally short but outside off, Foakes just taps it wide of the man at gully and the ball races away to the fence.
Goes full now and bowls it outside off, Foakes jams it out toward mid off.
Good length on middle and leg, nudged away in front of mid-wicket for a single.
SIX! Wow, Harry Brook is playing a blinder of a knock here. Length ball around off stump, Brook lifts it effortlessly over mid off and the ball travels the distance.
FOUR! Crunched! Pitched up around off, Harry Brook advances and thumps it to the right of a diving Kane Williamson at mid off for a boundary. New Zealand just cannot stop the flow of runs here.
FOUR! Up and over! Short of a length around off, Ben Foakes stays there and pulls it well in front of square and over mid-wicket for yet another boundary.
Too full and too straight, flicked away down to fine leg for one. The 250 is now up for England.
FOUR! More width and more runs for Harry Brook behind square on the off side. Short and wide, Brook slaps it away past backward point for a boundary.
Banged in short at 140 clicks and around off. Ben Foakes gets on top of the bounce and pulls it down to deep backward square leg for a single.
Goes a bit wider of the crease and angles in a fuller delivery at the stumps, Foakes blocks it off the front foot.
Good length over the top of off stump, Ben Foakes keeps it down on the deck.

A stifled appeal but turned down! Fuller and outside off by Tim Southee, Harry Brook gets forward to defend but gets hit on the front pad first. New Zealand players went up in appeal but the impact was outside off.

FOUR! Streaky but Harry Brook will take it! Keeps it on that good length around off, the ball comes back into the batter, Harry Brook takes a stride forward to defend but gets an inside edge that goes past the keeper for a boundary.
FOUR! Good-length delivery shaping away outside off, Harry Brook slashes hard at the delivery and gets a thickish outside edge that goes wide of gully for a boundary.
On a length on off, Harry Brook defends this one on the off side.
Back of a length outside off by Tim Southee, Ben Foakes stays on the back foot and punches this one through covers. The batters run three.
Length delivery outside off, Harry Brook guides this one towards deep backward point for a single.
Shortish delivery on off, Ben Foakes pushes this one to cover for a dot.
WIDE! Short and aimed at the batter, Ben Foakes ducks under it as the ball sails over his head. It is signalled as a wide by the square leg umpire.
FOUR! Nicely played! Back of a length on off by Scott Kuggeleijn, Ben Foakes gets on his toes and gets on top of the bounce. Punches it past extra cover and collects his first boundary.
Bowls it on a good length around off, the ball nips back in after pitching and catches Ben Foakes high on the back leg as he tried to defend.
Short of a length at the batter, Harry Brook swivels in his crease and pulls it down to fine leg for a single.
A bumper outside off, Ben Foakes gets on top of the bounce and works it down to fine leg for a single.
Back of a length on off by Scott Kuggeleijn, Ben Foakes looks to whip this one on the leg side but fails to get it past Tom Latham at short leg.
Banged in short and on off, Ben Foakes rolls his wrists and keeps his pull shot along the ground. Collects a single towards deep square leg for a single.
Length delivery outside off, Ben Foakes stays back to defend but gets it from the outer part of the bat towards backward point.
Another delivery in the channel outside off, Ben Foakes gets behind the line and blocks this one out on the leg side.
Keeps it back of a length outside off, Ben Foakes defends this one towards cover for a dot.
Back of a length outside off, Ben Foakes hangs back and punches it nicely but fails to get it past cover.
On a length outside off, Ben Foakes pushes this one off the back foot to backward point.
Good-length delivery around off, Harry Brook goes on the back foot and solidly defends this one on the off side.
Banged in short and just outside off, Harry Brook sways away and lets it go.
Goes fraction short but on leg, Ben Foakes gets inside the line and helps it towards fine leg for a single.
Short of a length but way down the leg side, Ben Foakes lets it go through to the keeper.
On a length and angling at the pads, Harry Brook works this one to fine leg and takes a single.

FOUR! FIFTY for Harry Brook! Scott Kuggeleijn bowls this one short and at the batter, Harry Brook expects the short ball and moves to the leg side early. Ramps this one over the keeper's head for a boundary. Brings up his fifty off just 43 balls.
Back of a length on middle, Harry Brook eases this one off the back foot to mid-wicket and retains the strike with a single.
Back of a length around off, Harry Brook dabs this one to backward point.
Short and aimed at the batter, Harry Brook stays leg side of the ball and tries to ramp this one over the keeper's head but does not connect.

FOUR! Back-to-back boundaries by Harry Brook! Keeps it short again and on off, Harry Brook hangs back and thrashes this one through covers. This time he gets it to the right of Neil Wagner at deep point for yet another boundary.
FOUR! Cut away! Blair Tickner bowls it short and outside off, Harry Brook picks the length early and stays on the back foot. Cuts this one fiercely towards deep backward point for a boundary.
On a length on off, Harry Brook pushes this one to cover.

A loud appeal but turned down! Short of a length on leg, Ben Foakes gets inside the line of the delivery and tries to help it fine but fails to connect. New Zealand go up in appeal thinking Ben Foakes had edged it but they decide not to go upstairs.
Ben Foakes is the next man in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Scott Kuggeleijn has his first Test wicket and it's the big wicket of Ben Stokes! Kuggeleijn persists with short stuff and bowls it on middle, Ben Stokes clears his front leg and tries to flat bat this one on the leg side. Gets himself into an awkward position and ends up hitting it straight to mid-wicket. Tom Latham stationed there takes a sharp catch. England have lost their half their side now.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Latham b Scott Kuggeleijn

Commentary.Commentary: Banged in short at the batter, Ben Stokes ducks under it and lets it go.
FOUR! A fraction short on off, Ben Stokes hangs back and punches this one along the ground on the off side. Gets it well wide of deep point for a boundary.
Back of a length around off, Harry Brook dabs this one towards gully and takes a single.
Full but angling down the leg side, Harry Brook goes for the clip but misses.
FOUR! Short of a length outside off, Ben Stokes shimmies down the track and slashes hard at the delivery. Gets a thickish outside edge that goes over the slip cordon for yet another boundary.
Fuller in length on off, Harry Brook drives it along the ground to deep point for a single.

FOUR! Edgy! Short of a length on off by Blair Tickner, Harry Brook looks to leave the ball alone but keeps his bat hanging. The ball catches the top edge of his bat and it flies over the slip cordon for a boundary.
Good-length delivery around off, Harry Brook defends this one on the off side.
Banged in short and on middle, Harry Brook ducks under it and leaves the ball alone.
Back of a length on middle by Blair Tickner, Harry Brook gets behind the line of the delivery and blocks this one out.

Back of a length shaping away outside off, Ben Stokes looks to steer this one with soft hands but gets it from the outer part of the bat. Luckily for him, the edge does not carry to Daryl Mitchell at second slip.
Another bumper at the batter by Scott Kuggeleijn, Ben Stokes ducks under the delivery and lets it go.
Length delivery at the stumps, Harry Brook nudges this one from the crease to deep square leg for a single.
WIDE! Goes short again but this time it goes way over the head of the batter. Harry Brook ducks under it and lets it go through to the keeper. It is signalled as a wide by the square leg umpire.
Fuller and around off by Scott Kuggeleijn, Ben Stokes steps out and pushes it to the left of Kane Williamson at mid off for a single.
Beaten! On a good length and angling away outside off, Ben Stokes uses his feet and tries to dab this one on the off side but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Banged in short and at the batter, the ball does not rise and that allows Ben Stokes to defend while getting on top of the bounce.

Drinks break! The first hour after Tea has been an exciting one as the Kiwi pacers were able to get their team back in the game with a couple of wickets in quick succession. Ollie Pope who looked good got out and then Joe Root also fell in uncharacteristic fashion. Since then though, Harry Brook has done well to put the pressure back on the hosts and England seem to have got their rhythm back. Also, Scott Kuggeleijn (3-0-20-0) is back into the attack.
Full and at the stumps, Harry Brook drives this one on the up but fails to get it past mid on.

FOUR! Short and punished by Harry Brook! Blair Tickner shortens his length and goes wide outside off, Harry Brook needs no second invitation as he pounces on the delivery with a cut shot. Gets it well wide of backward point and the fast outfield does the rest.
On a good length on off, Harry Brook blocks this one out on the off side.
FOUR! Fuller and outside off by Blair Tickner, Harry Brook gets the width he needs and throws his hands at it. Carves this one past backward point for a boundary.
Back of a length in the channel outside off, Harry Brook hangs back to defend but gets it from the inner part of the bat. The ball rolls behind the wicket for a dot.
Bowls it full and around off, Harry Brook gets on the front foot and defends this one back to the bowler.
Back of a length and outside off, Harry Brook frees his arms and cuts it along the carpet to deep point for a single.
On a length angling at the pads, Ben Stokes rolls his wrists and turns it towards backward square leg for a single.
Short of a length on off, Harry Brook swivels in the crease and pulls it to deep square leg for a single.
Good stop! Goes full and at the stumps, Ben Stokes uses his feet and drives it wide of mid on. Tim Southee there dives to his left and keeps it to one.
Shorter in length and on off, Harry Brook cuts this along the ground to deep point for a single.

FOUR! Just over! Neil Wagner bowls it touch fuller and outside off, Harry Brook steps out and looks to go back over the bowler's head. The bat turns in his hands and the ball catches the outer part of the bat. Gets it just over mid off and collects a boundary.
Fuller and on off by Blair Tickner, Ben Stokes blocks this one out on the off side.
Good-length and around off, the ball nips back in after pitching, Ben Stokes shuffles across to defend but gets an inside edge back onto his pads.
Goes full and outside off, Ben Stokes shoulders arms and lets it go through to the keeper.

FOUR! Nicely played! Back of a length in the channel outside off, Ben Stokes allows the ball to come to him and uses the pace of the delivery. Opens the bat face and steers it through gully for a boundary.
Length delivery around off by Blair Tickner, Ben Stokes advances and dabs it towards backward point for a dot.
Full and angling in on off from 'round the wicket, Ben Stokes leans forward and defends it towards cover.
Blair Tickner (8-0-41-1) is back on.

FOUR! Dispatched by Harry Brook! Neil Wagner bowls this one full and outside off, Harry Brook gets into the position early and uses the bottom hand. Drills this one to the right of mid off and collects a boundary.
Full and in the channel outside off, Harry Brook gets on the front foot and solidly blocks this one out on the off side.
Good-length delivery outside off, Harry Brook covers the stumps and lets it go.
Fuller and outside off, Harry Brook takes a big stride forward and drives it straight to Tom Latham at extra cover.
On a good length and angling away outside off, Harry Brook does not reach out to the delivery and leaves it alone.
Full and on middle and leg by Neil Wagner, Harry Brook drives it a bit uppishly towards Kane Williamson at mid on.
Full and slanting in on off by Tim Southee, Ben Stokes drives it firmly back to the bowler. Tim Southee in his follow through makes a good stop.
Southee sees the batter advance and bowls it full and wide outside off, Ben Stokes shoulders arms and lets it go through to the keeper.
Straying on the pads and fuller in length, Harry Brook flicks this one down to fine leg for a single.
Full and angling in at the stumps, Harry Brook gets behind the line and drives it firmly to mid on.
Goes full this time around off, Ben Stokes presents a straight bat and drives it to the left of mid off for a quick single.
Bowls this one back of a length outside off from 'round the wicket, Ben Stokes steps out and leaves the ball alone.
Good length outside off, Brook hammers it away toward cover.
FOUR! Edged away! Fractionally short and wide of the off stump, Harry Brook stays on the back foot and throws his hands at it. Brook ends up slashing it over the gully region for a boundary.
Almost a half-volley around off, Brook latches onto it and drives it firmly but it is well stopped by the fielder at short cover.
Pitched up again, on the fifth stump line and going across the right-hander. Brook leaves it alone.
A touch fuller and well outside the off stump, around the tramline. Harry Brook doesn't play at it.
Pitched-up delivery in and around the off stump, Harry Brook defends it out.
On a length and outside off, Stokes steps out again and just taps it onto the off side.
Pitches up close to the off stump, Stokes looks to block but ends up edging it down through the backward point region for a couple of runs.
Fuller in length and bowled well outside off, Ben Stokes steps out and drives it firmly toward cover.
Goes a bit wider of the crease now and tries to angle one in full and into the off stump but Stokes manages to keep it out.
Good length, in that channel around off and just angling in a bit, Stokes lets it through to the keeper.
Southee comes from around the wicket and angles in a fullish delivery into the off stump. Ben Stokes stays solid in defense.
FOUR! In the air but it's in the gap this time around. Pitches up outside off, Harry Brook throws his hands at it and drives it a touch uppishly to the left of the man at cover for a boundary.
Length ball, well outside the off stump and angling away, Harry Brook leaves it alone.
Full and outside off, this is driven to the left of mid off.
Pitches up, Ben Stokes pushes it gently off the front foot straight back past the bowler for a single.
England skipper Ben Stokes walks out to bat with his side suddenly in a spot of bother.

OUT! CAUGHT! What a ripper of a catch from Daryl Mitchell! Neil Wagner goes full and wide now as he sees Joe Root setting up for the reverse sweep. Root pre-meditates and does go for the reverse lap but has to stretch for it a bit. The ball takes the under edge and flies low to the right of the second slip where Daryl Mitchell springs to his right and pouches it with both hands. New Zealand get the double-strike not too long after the break and England are all of a sudden four down with two new batters at the crease.
Commentary.Howout: c Daryl Mitchell b Neil Wagner

Commentary.Commentary: Hits the length hard and bowls it outside off, Joe Root gets on the front foot and blocks it back onto the deck.

Tim Southee looks for the magic ball, trying to swing it away from leg stump but it goes straight on. Harry Brook tickles it away fine and Neil Wagner makes a good stop to his right at fine leg to keep it down to a brace.
Harry Brook is the next man in.

OUT! CAUGHT! The skipper has done the job for his side! Tim Southee bowls this one on a perfect length but pushes it wider of the off stump. Ollie Pope looks to pounce on it and drive it through covers but plays a loose shot away from his body. The outside edge is taken and Tom Latham at second slip takes an excellent catch going down to his right. Pope who looked so comfotable out there is gone and New Zealand have their third wicket.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Latham b Tim Southee

Commentary.Commentary: Fullish length on the fifth stump line, driven square of the wicket but straight to cover-point.
This is pitched up on off stump, Pope solidly keeps it out off the front foot.
Back of a length around off, Pope gets on the back foot and keeps it down on the off side.

FOUR! Banged in short and down leg, Ollie Pope pulls it very fine and gets it into the fine leg fence. There are just way too many loose deliveries from the Kiwis and England aren't missing out on any of them.
Good length around off, tucked away neatly in front of square leg for a single.
Wagner switches to around the wicket and angles it in from outside off, Pope pushes it out.
FOUR! Aggressive intent from Ollie Pope! Pitched up around off, Pope comes down the wicket and heaves it using the bottom hand through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Very full and around off, Pope drives it straight back and finds the man at mid off.
On a length around off, Pope shuffles across and hits it straight to mid on. Neil Wagner has overstepped yet again and a no ball is called.
Goes full and again and angles it well across the off stump, Joe Root uses his feet and drives it firmly to deepish extra cover for a quick single.
Way too full and way too straight by Wagner, Pope clips it away behind square on the leg side for a single.
A single to end and there's still not a single maiden over bowled by New Zealand thus far. This is full and on the pads, flicked away to deep square leg for one.
Full and outside off, Ollie Pope steps out and drives it to the left of the man at cover-point but fails to beat him.
Bowls it a bit fuller now and floats it around the off stump, Ollie Pope defends it under his eyeline.
Good length again, around middle and off, Pope stays watchful in defense.
Good length in that channel around off stump, Pope defends it out on the off side.
A length ball around off, Ollie Pope uses his feet and pushes it toward cover.
Tim Southee will operate from the other end.
A half-volley well outside the off stump, Joe Root drives it square but misses out on the boundary as he hits it straight to cover-point.
Pitched it up now around off, Root blocks it solidly off the front foot.
Good length angling down the leg side.
FOUR! Joe Root with a skillful shot! Fullish length angling across the off stump, Root shuffles across and plays the reverse ramp over short third man and into the fence.
Bowls it full and wide outside off, Joe Root extends his arms and drives it toward cover.
Slight halt! Joe Root has got something in his left eye and the physio comes out to have a look. He looks okay to resume now.
Starts off with a length ball angling across off, Ollie Pope tucks it away neatly through mid-wicket for a single.

We are back for the post-tea session. New Zealand players make their way out in the middle followed by Joe Root and Ollie Pope. Neil Wagner will get the proceedings underway with the ball in this session. Here we go...
... DAY 1, SESSION 2 ...

After Tim Southee called it right and opted to bowl first, he found his mojo straightaway dismissing Zak Crawley in his second over. However, other bowlers failed to back their skipper up from the other end. They kept bowling loose deliveries which allowed the opposition batters to release the pressure. Tim Southee persisted with Blair Tickner and that paid dividends for New Zealand as the debutant provided them with a much-needed breakthrough making Ben Duckett his maiden Test victim. New Zealand have their task cut out against this fearless English batting attack in the second session. Grab a coffee and do join us back at 8.50 am IST (3.20 am GMT) for what promises to be another entertaining session of cricket.

Session Summary - 23 overs, 134 runs and 2 wickets. As the first session comes to an end, it will be safe to say that 'Bazball' has arrived in New Zealand and how. After being asked to bat first, England did lose an early wicket but Ben Duckett took charge and unleashed himself on the Kiwi attack. He did not shy away from pouncing on any loose delivery and stroked his way to a 36-ball fifty. He, along with Ollie Pope stitched a 99-run stand before falling 16 runs short of his hundred. Joe Root has looked solid since his arrival and will look to press on the advantage in the post-tea session.
Tossed up a bit fuller and on off stump, Joe Root defends it off the front foot. And, that will be the end of the first session on Day 1 as well.
Short again and around off, eased away off the back foot past point for another brace.
Shortens the length now and turns it onto middle and off, Joe Root goes on the back foot and pushes it out on the off side.
Fired in a bit, full and outside off, Joe Root steers it away through the cover region for a couple of runs.
Drifted onto middle and leg, Root blocks it in front of short leg.
Starts off with a fullish delivery around off stump. Joe Root gets on the back foot and keeps it out.
Spin for the first time in this Test as Michael Bracewell is introduced into the attack.
An attempted bumper on leg stump but this is dragged well down the leg side.
Perfect length around off and angling across, Ollie Pope plays it late and defends it out with soft hands. Neil Wagner is down on the ground yet again.
NO BALL! Fullish length on the pads, tickled down to fine leg for a single. Also, a no ball is called as Neil Wagner has overstepped.
Length ball around leg stump, Root nudges it onto the leg side.
Full on middle and leg, driven straight to mid on.
FOUR! Joe Root gets off the mark with a lovely shot. A touch fuller and around off, Root gets on the front foot and just caresses it through the cover region for a boundary.
Good length around the top of off, Joe Root defends it out with soft hands.

EDGED AND FOUR! This is on a length and around off, Ollie Pope comes forward and looks to flick it through mid-wicket but gets a leading edge that flies in between the slip cordon and backward point for a boundary.
A length ball around off, Ollie Pope punches it off the front foot but straight to mid off.

Well bowled! Fuller in length and in that channel around off. The ball angles in but straightens at the last moment and Ollie Pope makes a good leave as well. Blair Tickner seems to have found some rhythm here.
A tad shorter and well outside off, Pope reaches out and taps it straight to backward point.
And again! Nice and full on off stump, a bit of movement on offer. Ollie Pope looks to flick but gets a bit of a leading edge toward cover.
Fullish length, trying to skid one through on off stump, Ollie Pope punches it toward mid on.
Sweetly time but for no run. This is pitched up outside off, Joe Root drives it off the middle of the bat but the fielder at wide mid off dives to hie left and makes a good stop.
Bowls it a bit wider of the off stump and its a bit too drive to invite the cover drive.
Nicely bowled! Pitched up in that channel around off and angling it away. The ball just holds its line and Joe Root makes a leave.
Good running! This is pitched up around off, Pope works it to the right of mid on and sets off for the single straightaway.
Wagner bowls it fuller and outside off, angling it well across the right-hander. Ollie Pope leaves it alone.
Misfield! Good length around off, punched away on the up by Pope toward a deepish extra cover where Tim Southee fumbles and allows the batters to pick up a brace.
Joe Root comes in at number 4 for England.

OUT! TAKEN! Straight to the man and Ben Duckett is gutted! Blair Tickner pitches this one up around the off stump and invites the drive. Duckett obliges and doesn't quite followthrough with the bat and ends up just punching it away. Duckett does so a bit uppishly and hits it straight to Michael Bracewell at short cover who makes no mistake. Tickner gets his maiden Test wicket and Duckett departs after a superb knock.
Commentary.Howout: c Michael Bracewell b Blair Tickner

Commentary.Commentary: Fullish length around off and angling across, Duckett pushes it straight to mid off.
Now Blair Tickner falls over as well. Tickner puts in a bit of extra effort and bangs it in over off stump, Ollie Pope pulls it down to deep square leg for a run.
Good length, close to the off stump, Ollie Pope defends it from inside his crease.
Good length around leg stump, Duckett nudges it down with soft hands in front of mid-wicket for a quick run.
Full and on off stump, hit away to the right of the man at mid off.
This is bowled wide of the off stump, Duckett plays it with an angled bat down to third man for a single.

Pitched up on off stump, Ollie Pope gently pushes it on the up and there's a bit of hesitation for the single. The fielder from mid off dives to his right and misses the ball and the batters do eventually get an easy single.
Length and on the pads, tucked away to deep square leg for one and Neil Wagner falls over on the followthrough. He is fine though.
Two more! Full on middle and leg, Ben Duckett leans forward and just pushes it well in front of mid-wicket for a couple of runs.
Good running! Good length on the pads, Duckett tickles it down to fine leg and hustles back for the second.
Pitches it up around middle, looking to swing it away from the left-hander, Duckett presents the full face of the bat and defends it out.
Neil Wagner (2-0-19-0) comes back into the attack.
Four dots to end the over, much better from Blair Tickner. On a hard length outside off and just seaming away a touch, Pope looks to come forward and play at it but leaves it alone.
Pitched up around the fifth stump line, Ollie Pope shoulders arms at it.
Fullish length in that channel around off, Pope plays it with soft hands toward cover.
A length ball around off, Pope comes forward and mistimes the drive toward mid on.
Keeps the length full and tries to slide one across the leg stump, Duckett turns it 'round the corner for one.
Fullish length, angling it into leg stump, Pope flicks it away through the gap at mid-wicket for a single.
FOUR! And again, this time a lot squarer though. Short of a length over middle and off, Duckett rolls his wrists over the ball and pulls it into the deep mid-wicket fence.
FOUR! Short but not short enough and the 100 is up for England inside 16 overs. This is bowled outside off, Ben Duckett pulls it firmly and well in front of square on the leg side for a boundary.
Nagging length around leg stump and sliding across, Ben Duckett looks to play at it but misses and gets thudded on the pads.
Back of a length around off, Pope walks across and works it off his hips down to fine leg for an easy single.
On a hard length and on the fifth stump line, Ollie Pope looks to come forward but lets it through to the keeper in the end.
A bit uppish but in the gap. Short of a length around off stump, Duckett pulls it through mid-wicket without much timing but picks up a run.
Short again and Duckett just drags the pull shot through mid-wicket for one more.
Leg bye! Good length, over off stump, Pope looks to walk across and work it away but misses. The ball deflects off the pads toward backward square leg and they pick up a leg bye.
This is banged in halfway down the track and over middle and leg, Ben Duckett gets on top of the bounce and pulls it in front of mid-wicket for a run.
Pitches it up now on off stump, Duckett blocks it off the front foot.
FOUR! Quick hands from Duckett! Good length outside off, Duckett stays back and just slaps it away to the right of the man at deep point for a boundary.
This is bowled full and around off, Ben Duckett eases it toward mid off.
Four singles in a row to close out the over. Good length on leg stump, Duckett works it away in front of square leg for one.
Another short ball, this time over middle and this is pulled away to deep mid-wicket for yet another single.
Scott Kuggeleijn bends his back a bit and bangs it in around the leg stump. Ben Duckett muscles it away toward deep square leg for one more.
Dugs it in a bit, Pope walks towards the ball and plays a controlled pull shot down to fine leg for a single.
Good length around the top of off, Pope blocks it out.
FOUR! Driven and driven well! This is pitched up on middle, Ollie Pope punches it to the left of mid on and picks up a boundary.
Fuller and outside off by Blair Tickner, Ben Duckett drives it firmly towards extra cover where Michael Bracewell makes a good stop to his left and parries it towards mid off.
Fuller in length and outside off, Ben Duckett gets forward and defends this one on the off side.
Leg bye! Back of a length on middle, Ollie Pope shuffles across to tuck this one fine on the leg side but fails to get any bat on it. The ball rolls off his pads towards fine leg for a single.
Short of a length outside off, Ben Duckett hangs back and drags this one from outside off towards deep square leg for a single.
On a length outside off, Ben Duckett dabs this one along the ground to gully.
Starts with a full toss outside off, Ben Duckett frees his arms and goes for the drive but fails to get it past extra cover. That should have been put away by Ben Duckett.
Blair Tickner (3-0-26-0) returns to the attack.
Goes full and outside off, Ollie Pope steps out and drives it crisply back to the bowler. Scott Kuggeleijn bends down in his follow through and makes a good stop.
Banged in short and outside off, Ollie Pope sways away and lets the ball go through to the keeper.
Shorter on middle by Scott Kuggeleijn, Ben Duckett controls the pull shot well and takes a single to deep square leg.
Length delivery outside off, Ben Duckett guides this one along the ground towards gully.
On a good length around off from over the wicket, Ben Duckett gets behind the line and blocks this one out back to the bowler.

Ollie Pope has been hit on the helmet and out comes the physio for the concussion check. That will also be Drinks! This has been a great start by England after being sent into bat first. They did lose Zak Crawley early but Ben Duckett has been brilliant so far pouncing on any loose deliveries. On the other hand, New Zealand have missed their lines and lengths consistently which has allowed the visitors to get off to such a start. They need to assess during this break and come up with a better game plan.
Starts with a short delivery at the batter, Ollie Pope goes for the pull but gets hit on the helmet. The ball rolls towards fine leg and batters cross for a single.
Scott Kuggeleijn comes on to bowl, replacing Blair Tickner.
Touch fuller on middle and leg, Ben Duckett clips this one straight to mid-wicket.
On a good length outside off, Ben Duckett gets forward and defends it on the off side.

FOUR! Tim Southee goes searching for the swing and bowls it full at the stumps, Ben Duckett needs no second invitation as he presents a full face of the bat to the delivery. Gets it wide of mid on for yet another boundary.

FOUR! FIFTY for Ben Duckett! Full and at the pads by Tim Southee, Ben Duckett rolls his wrists and clips this one past square leg for a boundary. This has been an entertaining innings here from the stylish left-handed batter.
Beaten! Full and angling away outside off, Ben Duckett looks to drive this one on the up but plays it away from his body. Luckily for him, he does not get an outside edge.
Full and outside off, Ben Duckett gets behind the line and blocks this one out on the leg side.
Switches to over the wicket and bowls it at the pads, Ben Duckett turns this one towards deep square leg and retains the strike with a single.

FOUR! Make that three in a row! Blair Tickner changes his length and goes full and outside off, Ben Duckett punches on the full delivery and punches this one through the covers for a boundary. Ben Duckett is putting on a show here.
FOUR! On a length outside off by Blair Tickner, Ben Duckett allows the ball to come to him and opens the bat face. Steers it through backward point and collects the third boundary of the over.

FOUR! Ben Duckett is looking in fine nick here! Blair Tickner goes full and outside off, Ben Duckett does not miss out as he leans into the drive and drives it through extra cover for yet another boundary.
On a good length outside off, Ben Duckett defends this one from the crease on the off side.
FOUR! Beautiful timing! Full and angling in at the stumps from 'round the wicket, Ben Duckett presents a full face of the bat and drives it to the right of mid on for a boundary.
Goes full and swinging away outside off, Ollie Pope uses his feet and drives it back past the bowler. Gets it to the left of mid on for a couple of runs.
Good-length delivery outside off, Ollie Pope lets it go through to the keeper.
Fuller in the channel outside off, Ollie Pope takes a stride forward and leaves the ball alone.
On a good length and shaping away outside off, Ollie Pope does not reach out to the delivery and watchfully lets it go.
Shorter and at the batter by Tim Southee, Ben Duckett swivels and helps this one to fin leg for a single.
On a length and angling away outside off, Ben Duckett dabs this one wide of backward point and collects a couple of runs.
Length delivery and going away outside off, Ollie Pope shoulders arms and leaves the ball alone.
Short again and around off, Ben Duckett pulls it along the ground towards deep square leg for a single.
FOUR! Shorter in length and on off, Ben Duckett hangs back and gets on top of the bounce. Pulls it through mid-wicket for his fourth boundary of the innings.
Back of a length on leg by Blair Tickner, Ben Duckett gets inside the line of the delivery to tuck this one fine but fails to connect and gets hit on the thigh pad.
On a length but down the leg side, Ben Duckett tries to flick this one but misses.
NO BALL! Back of a length and into the batter, Ben Duckett gets cramped for room as he goes for the pull and gets hit high on the pads. Blair Tickner has overstepped again.
Full and angling in on middle, Ben Duckett looks to turn this one on the leg side but closes the bat face early. Gets a leading edge that goes a bit uppishly but to the right of Blair Tickner.

FOUR! Glorious by Ollie Pope! Tim Southee goes full again searching for the swing and bowls it outside off, Ollie Pope leans forward and drives it along the ground through the covers region. Devon Conway performs the chase and puts in a valiant effort but the ball beats him to the fence.
Full and swinging in on leg, Ben Duckett works this one towards fine leg and takes a single.
Full and slanting away outside off, Ben Duckett defends this one solidly on the off side.
Strays on the pads and bowls it full in length, Ben Duckett flicks this one towards deep backward leg for a couple of runs.
FOUR! Pitches this one full and swinging into the batter, Ben Duckett accounts for the swing and rolls his wrists. Clips it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Fuller and angling away outside off from over the wicket, Ben Duckett watchfully blocks this one out.
On a good length and outside off, Ollie Pope shuffles across early and flicks this one to the left of deep square leg. Kane Williamson runs around and keeps it to two.
Fuller and around off, Ollie Pope works this one to mid-wicket for a dot.
Back of a length and around off, the ball nips back in after pitching, Ollie Pope hangs back and goes for the pull but does not connect.
Bowls it on a good length outside off, Ollie Pope gets his bat out of the way at the last moment and leaves the ball alone.
Back of a length and angling into the batter from 'round the wicket, Ben Duckett swivels in his crease to pull but gets it off his gloves towards backward square leg for a single.
Starts with a wayward delivery, full but down the leg side, Ben Duckett looks to help it fine but fails to get any bat on it.
The debutant Blair Tickner is introduced into the attack.
Good-length delivery outside off, Ollie Pope gets behind the line and defends it on the off side.
FOUR! Nicely played! Full and angling in on off by Tim Southee, Ollie Pope uses his feet to negate the swing and clips it through mid-wicket. Gets off the mark with a boundary.
Full and outside off, Ollie Pope shuffles across and clips this one straight to mid on.
Fuller and outside off, Ollie Pope takes a big stride forward and defends this one to cover.
Bowls it on a good length and shaping away outside off, Ollie Pope shoulders arms and lets the ball go through to the keeper.
Keeps it full and outside off, Ollie Pope watchfully defends this one towards cover.
Full and down the leg side, Ben Duckett leaves the ball alone this time.
On a length on off, Ben Duckett punches this one towards cover.

NO BALL! FOUR! Sloppy from Neil Wagner! Third no ball in only his second over! Bowls this one full and at the stumps. Ben Duckett presents a full face of the bat and drives it back past the bowler. Gets it to the right of mid on and collects a boundary.
Full and swinging away outside off, Ben Duckett leans forward and blocks it out on the off side.
On a good length outside off, Ben Duckett defends this one with soft hands towards gully.
Full and around off by Neil Wagner, Ben Duckett drives this one back to the bowler.
Fullish delivery at the stumps, Ben Duckett watchfully digs this one out back to the bowler.
On a good length and angling in on off, Ollie Pope covers the off stump and shoulders arms to the delivery.
Ollie Pope walks in at number 3 for England.

OUT! CAUGHT! Tim Southee finally gets his man! Bowls this one on a good length and outside off, Zak Crawley uses his feet to counter the swing and looks to drive this one with a straight bat. Goes with hard hands and gets an outside edge that carries to third slip. Michael Bracewell gets down low to his left and takes a good catch. Zak Crawley did not look comfortable during his short stay.
Commentary.Howout: c Michael Bracewell b Tim Southee

Commentary.Commentary: On a good length and going away from the batter, Zak Crawley goes for a drive away from his body but misses.
Another fuller delivery outside off, Zak Crawley accounts for the away swing and lets it go through to the keeper.
Full and swinging away in the channel outside off, Zak Crawley shoulders arms and leaves the ball alone.
Full and straying at the pads, Ben Duckett clips this one towards fine leg and takes a single.
Full and angling in on leg, Zak Crawley clips it firmly but fails to get it past square leg.
Full and swinging into the batter, Zak Crawley defends this one down the wicket.
NO BALL! Back of a length but angling down the leg side, Zak Crawley looks to flick but misses. Neil Wagner has overstepped for the second time in the over.
On a length outside off, Ben Duckett crouches and punches it through covers and collects three runs.
FOUR! Back-to-back boundaries for Ben Duckett! Fuller in length and outside off, Ben Duckett gets into the position early and drives it through covers for yet another boundary.

FOUR! Ben Duckett is up and running! Neil Wagner bowls it full and at the pads, Ben Duckett does not miss out as he clips it along the ground on the leg side. Gets it through square leg and opens his account with a boundary.
Full and outside off, Zak Crawley frees his arms and goes for the drive but gets an inside edge that rolls towards square leg for a single.

NO BALL! Oh no, Neil Wagner has castled Zak Crawley but guess what? He has overstepped. Starts with a full delivery and swinging into the batter on middle and leg, Zak Crawley gets forward to defend but does not account for the swing and sees his woodwork disturbed. Luckily for him, it was a no ball.
Neil Wagner will share the attack from the other end.
Keeps it full and wide outside off, Ben Duckett shoulders arms and leaves the ball alone.
Full and at the stumps by Tim Southee, Zak Crawley shuffles across and drives it to the left of mid on for a single.
Beaten! On a good length and shaping away outside off, Zak Crawley steps out and goes for the drive but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Fuller in the channel outside off, Zak Crawley does not reach out to the delivery and lets it go through to the keeper.

Was that a chance? Tim Southee goes full and lets the ball swing away outside off, Zak Crawley uses his feet to counter the swing and goes for the drive. Gets a thickish outside edge that travels low to the right of Michael Bracewell at third slip. He fails to react quickly and a chance goes begging. The batters run two in the process.
Southee starts with a full delivery, swinging away outside off, Zak Crawley shoulders arms and leaves the ball alone.

Right then, we are done with the national anthems. The umpires and players make their way out in the middle. Ben Duckett and Zak Crawley will open the innings for England. Tim Southee will start the proceedings with the ball for New Zealand. Let's play...
England (Playing XI) - Ben Duckett, Zak Crawley, Ollie Pope, Joe Root, Harry Brook, Ben Stokes (C), Ben Foakes (WK), Ollie Robinson, Stuart Broad, Jack Leach, James Anderson.

New Zealand (Playing XI) - Tom Latham, Devon Conway, Kane Williamson, Henry Nicholls, Daryl Mitchell, Tom Blundell (WK), Michael Bracewell, Scott Kuggeleijn (On debut), Tim Southee (C), Neil Wagner, Blair Tickner (On debut).
TOSS - New Zealand have won the toss and they will BOWL first.

England on the other hand have been on fire in Test cricket in the last year or so apart from a couple of times that 'Bazball' has worked against them. Their bowlers were already performing but with the batting lineup getting the freedom to play as they do, it is just a treat to watch when things do come off. Ben Stokes returns to New Zealand, the country in which he was born and he will look to continue pouring more misery onto the Kiwi which he has been doing since the 2019 World Cup final. It is a day-night game and the toss will be crucial. Which side will make early inroads on Day 1? We shall find out. Toss and team news in a bit.

New Zealand have a more or less settled batting unit but it is their bowling unit that has taken a bit of a hit with Kyle Jamieson being ruled out of his comeback series and Matt Henry not available for the first Test. In all likeliness, Blair Tickner is set to make his Test debut for the Black Caps and he will be looking to make a name for himself. Kiwi skipper Tim Southee will hope that the Kiwi batters are able to muster up runs against a pretty solid English bowling attack.

Hello and welcome everyone to Day 1 of the first Test match between New Zealand and England at the Bay Oval in Mount Maunganui. Just a few days after cyclone Gabrielle hit North Island, these two teams come together for some cricketing action with Mount Maunganui not being too badly affected. The sides also met less than a year ago in England and on that occasion, the 'Bazball' tactics just proved to be too strong for the Kiwis and they will be looking for a turnaround in the result at home.
... MATCH DAY ,,,

We are ready for England's second innings. They have a slender lead of 19 runs and would want to fend off the new ball. The umpires and the Kiwi players are back in the middle and can be seen in a huddle. Zak Crawley and Ben Duckett are the openers for England. Skipper Tim Southee has the new ball in hand and is raring to go. Let's play...
... THIRD INNINGS ...

England will be wondering what happened and where exactly they lost the plot. Having the opposition pegged back at 83/5 in the first session on Day 2 to ending up conceding 306 runs in total isn't what they had in mind. The visitors were completely taken aback by the hard-hitting display by Tom Blundell and even Scott Kuggeleijn took their bowlers to the cleaners. Ollie Robinson did bowl well and picked up a well-deserved four-fer but they were made to toil. James Anderson did pick up the final wicket with the new ball but the English openers now have to come out and face the new ball under lights which we saw on the previous day was a difficult thing to do. Will England be up for the challenge? Find out soon as the English second innings is up next.

Wow, what a colossal effort from Tom Blundell and New Zealand as they have gone from conceding a triple-digit first-innings lead to just finishing 19 runs short of England's total. New Zealand went into the Dinner break being 238/8 and lost Tim Southee soon after the resumption. With the score being 247/9, Blair Tickner walked in and displayed great heart to just stick around. Blundell then just laid into the English bowlers and got to a scintillating century before pouring more misery onto the visitors. In the end, he got out playing one-too many big shots but finished with his best-ever Test score and has given the hosts heaps of confidence going back onto the field.

OUT! CAUGHT! New Zealand have been bowled out for 306! Back of a length on middle by James Anderson, Tom Blundell shimmies down the track and looks to slap this one down the ground. Skies this one high in the air and only as far as James Anderson who settles under it and does the rest. End of a brilliant knock by Tom Blundell but it is England with a slender lead of 19 runs.
Commentary.Howout: c & b James Anderson

Commentary.Commentary: On a good length outside off, Tom Blundell shoulders arms and leaves the ball alone.
FOUR! More frustration for England! Bowls this one on a length and drifting at the pads, Tom Blundell helps this one fine towards the fine leg region for a boundary.
Fuller in length around off, Tom Blundell takes a stride forward and blocks this one out on the off side.
On a length on middle, Tom Blundell defends this one on the leg side.
Full and at the stumps, Blair Tickner gets behind the line and keeps this one out.

Full and outside off by Stuart Broad, Blair Tickner pushes at the delivery away from his body but gets beaten on the outside edge. Ben Foakes goes up in appeal thinking Tickner has edged it. The umpire shakes his head and Ben Stokes isn't convinced enough to go upstairs. Would you believe it? The UltraEdge show a spike as the ball was next to he bat. A huge reprieve for Blair Tickner.
Full and swinging in on middle and leg, Blair Tickner accounts for the swing and clips it through mid-wicket for a couple of runs.
Fuller in length and a bit too wide outside off, Blair Tickner leaves the ball alone.
On a good length and angling into the batter, Blair Tickner keeps this one out off the back foot.
Full and swinging in outside off, Blair Tickner shoulders arms and lets it go.
Stuart Broad (16-2-70-1) to share the second new ball with James Anderson.

FOUR! James Anderson goes back of a length and swinging away outside off, Tom Blundell steps out and frees his arms. Slogs across the line but gets a top edge that goes over the third man fielder for a boundary.
Back of a length at the batter by James Anderson, Tom Blundell works this one off the back foot to mid-wicket.
Back of a length at the batter by James Anderson, Tom Blundell works this one off the back foot to mid-wicket.
Goes full and on off, Tom Blundell takes a stride forward and defends it on the off side.

Full and a hint of away movement on middle, Tom Blundell tries to turn this one on the leg side but ends up chipping this one towards mid on. Luckily for him, the ball falls short of the diving Stuart Broad at mid on.
Starts with a length delivery swinging away outside off, Tom Blundell shimmies down the track and tries to go down the ground but connects with thin air.
The second new ball is now due! Ben Stokes has a word with his bowlers as he does take the second new ball right away. James Anderson (15-5-28-2) to have the first bite at the new pink cherry.
On a good length around off, Blair Tickner shuffles a bit and keeps this one out.
Short and angling down the leg side, Tom Blundell helps this one towards fine leg and takes the single.
FOUR! Pace on this time by Ben Stokes and bowls it on middle, Tom Blundell gets on his toes and flat bats this one through the vacant mid on region for yet another boundary.
FOUR! Slower and short at the batter, Tom Blundell does not miss out this time as he pulls this one to the right of deep square leg for a boundary.
Cutter on a length on middle, Tom Blundell clears his front leg and goes for a mighty heave across the line. Gets it from the inner part of the bat towards deep square leg and denies the single.
Slower and tad short on leg, Tom Blundell waits for it and pulls it towards fine leg. No single taken.
Short of a length on middle and leg, Blair Tickner gets behind the line and solidly keeps this one out.
Short and at the batter, Tom Blundell pulls this one towards Ben Duckett at deep backward square leg and takes the singe this time.
Slower and into the wicket outside off, Tom Blundell looks to drag this one on the leg side but does not connect.
Shortish delivery again and on middle, Tom Blundell pulls this one to deep square leg and refuses the single.
Short and on off, Tom Blundell pulls this one hard but fails to get it past Stuart Broad at mid-wicket.
Fullish and on off by Ollie Robinson, Tom Blundell gets across and scoops this one wide of fine leg. Jack Leach there makes a good diving stop and saves a couple of runs for his side.

Slower and full outside off, Tom Blundell gets down and swings hard at the delivery. Gets a thickish outside edge that flies to the right of the keeper. Ben Foakes flings himself to his right but fails to hang onto it. The batters cross for a single.
FOUR! Short again and on middle, Tom Blundell does not miss out as he swivels in his crease and pulls it hard towards deep square leg for a boundary. These are important runs for New Zealand.
Short of a length on leg, Blair Tickner takes his one hand off the bat and fends it off his gloves towards square leg for a single.
Short and aimed at the batter, Blair Tickner fends this one awkwardly towards gully.
Another back-of-a-length delivery at the batter, Blair Tickner stays leg side of the ball and lets it go.
Back of a length at the stumps by Ben Stokes, Blair Tickner sways away and leaves the ball alone.

FOUR! Streaky but they all count! Slower and fuller outside off, Tom Blundell clears his front leg to thump this one down the ground but gets into his shot early. Gets an outside edge that goes over Joe Root at first slip and the ball trickles to the boundary.
Looks to go for the yorker but bowls a full toss at the batter, Tom Blundell advances but gets cramped for room and can only push it to mid on.
Fuller and on off by Ollie Robinson, Tom Blundell takes a stride forward and keeps this one out.
Slower delivery again, on a length around off, Tom Blundell gets behind the line and blocks this one out.
On a length on middle, Tom Blundell works this one towards deep mid-wicket and decides not to take the single.
Touch slower and on a length on off, Tom Blundell hangs back and defends it on the off side.
Short and flatter at the stumps, Blair Tickner gets behind the line of the ball and defends it down the wicket.
Flighted, full on middle, Blair Tickner gets forward and blocks this one out.
Short and angling in on leg, Blair Tickner stays back and defends it on the leg side.
Tossed up, full around off, Blair Tickner presses forward and blocks it out on the off side.
Keeps it short and on off, Blair Tickner keeps this one out.

Short and on off, Blair Tickner dabs this one towards cover-point and sets off for a single. But gets sent back by Tom Blundell. The fielder fires a throw at the striker's end which Ben Foakes fails to collect. Blair Tickner gets back in the nick of the time.
Full and drifting at the pads, Tom Blundell misses the clip and gets hit on the front pad. It will be Blair Tickner on strike for the next over.
FOUR! Cracking shot by Tom Blundell! Back of a length on middle by Ollie Robinson, Tom Blundell backs away and frees his arms. Slaps this one back over the bowler's head for a boundary.
FOUR! Smart batting by Tom Blundell! Ollie Robinson bowls a fullish delivery on off, Tom Blundell gets across and scoops this one towards the fine leg region for a boundary.
Length delivery on middle, Tom Blundell hangs back and works it to mid-wicket.
Fuller and angling in around off, Tom Blundell takes a stride forward and leaves it alone.
On a length at the stumps, Tom Blundell steps out and frees his arms to go through the off side but gets an under edge that rolls behind the wicket.
Tossed up, full on off, Tom Blundell gets down and goes for the slog sweep. Does not get it from the middle part of the bat but gets it in the gap and crosses for a single.
Short and quicker on off, Tom Blundell makes room to cut this one but fails to connect.
Short and on middle, Tom Blundell goes on the back foot and works it on the leg side for a dot.

HUNDRED for Tom Blundell! What an innings this has been the wicketkeeper batter! Jack Leach bowls this one slower and short at the stumps, Tom Blundell gets into the position early and paddles this one towards the vacant fine leg region. Gets enough bat on it to come back for the second to bring up a well-deserved hundred.
Short and flatter at the stumps, Tom Blundell goes back in his crease and pushes it back to the bowler.

In the air but safe and Tom Blundell inches closer and closer to his ton. Jack Leach shortens the length and bowls it around off stump. Blundell skips down the track and looks for the big hoick across the line but is a bit undone in flight. The ball takes the top edge and loops up over the slip fielder and they get back for two.

As close as it gets and the crowd is fixed in on this game. Ollie Robinson goes full and straight and gets it in the blockhole. Blair Tickner with a nervy defense but somehow he manages to get a bit of bat on it and keeps it out.
Good length around the top of off, Tickner with another solid block off the front foot. Can he now survive one more delivery and allow Tom Blundell to have a shot at his century?
Goes full now and looks to target the toes but just slides it down the leg side.
Good length in that channel around off and just holding its line. Tickner watches it all the way through and leaves it alone.
Good length, angling into middle, Tickner blocks it out.
Pitched up on off stump, Blair Tickner with a solid front-foot defense and the crowd cheers it as well.

FOUR! Just over! This is dragged down by Jack Leach around off, a real 'hit-me' delivery. Tom Blundell rocks back and has to wait for it before he pulls it hard and flat just over the mid-wicket fielder for a boundary.

FOUR! Excellent shot again from Tom Blundell and he moves into the 90s! Flighted delivery, drifting into middle and leg, Blundell shimmies down the track and lofts it inside out one-bounce over the cover fence.
Nagging length outside off, Tom Blundell hangs back and dabs it late toward short third man.

SIX! Well then, Tom Blundell has decided to take matters into his own hands. Drifted onto the leg stump, Blundell steps down the track and clubs it over the wide long on fence for a maximum. The 250 is now up for New Zealand.
Slower through the air and fuller around off, Tom Blundell looks for the paddle sweep but fails to get it away.
Shorter and on off, Tom Blundell goes on the back foot to keep it out.
Blair Tickner is the last man in for New Zealand.

OUT! TAKEN! Tim Southee cannot believe his luck! A low full toss from Ollie Robinson at the stumps, Southee walks across and gets inside the line of the ball before lapping it hard and flat over backward square leg. Unluckily for Southee, Ben Duckett stationed over there is well inside the ropes and does well to pick the ball out of the sun rays as he leaps up and pouches it safely. England are now one wicket away from bundling New Zealand out and they still lead by 78 runs.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Duckett b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: Here comes the bumper now, around the off stump and angling in, Southee ducks under it.
FOUR! Glorious from the skipper! Overpitched and on middle, Tim Southee stays leg side of the ball and hammers it right back past the bowler for a lovely boundary.
On a hard length outside off, Blundell stays back and dabs it down through backward point for one more.
Pitches it a bit further up and angles it into middle and leg, Tom Blundell looks to block off the front foot but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Back of a length around off, Tim Southee with a back-foot punch to get the ball through covers for a run.
Ollie Robinson will operate from the other end.
Flatter one, a tad bit short and close to the off pole. Tim Southee cuts it off the outer half of the bat toward short third man for a single.
Nicely tossed up on middle, Southee backs away and hits it straight to the bowler.
Drifted onto the pads, Tom Blundell nudges it 'round the corner and gets across to the other end.
Drifted onto leg stump, Tim Southee advances and pushes it toward deepish mid off for an easy single.
Tossed up around off, Southee blocks it toward cover.
Starts off with a flighted delivery, full and on middle, Tim Southee eases it onto the off side.

We are back for the third and final session on Day 2! The England players make their way out in the middle and so do, the two New Zealand batters. Tom Blundell ​​​​and Tim Southee will resume their innings for New Zealand. Jack Leach will start the proceedings with the ball in this session. Let's play...
... DAY 2, SESSION 3 ...

England came out after the tea break with a clear plan of bowling short deliveries with Ben Stokes leading the way for them. He was rewarded for his efforts with the big wicket of Devon Conway. Jack Leach then got onto the wickets column dismissing Michael Bracewell cheaply. After that wicket, the visitors were frustrated by the pair of Tom Blundell and Scott Kuggeleijn who kept the scoreboard ticking. Ollie Robinson was brought back into the attack and he handed them a much-needed breakthrough removing Scott Kuggeleijn in the final over before the dinner break. The visitors will now be hoping to wrap the innings quickly in the third session and by doing so, get a sizable first-innings lead. It promises to be another exciting session of cricket after the dinner break. Do join us back at 11.30 am IST (6.00 am GMT) for the third and final session of Day 2.

Session Summary - 23 overs, 100 runs and 3 wickets. Another intriguing session comes to an end at the end of which, it will be England who will be the slightly happier side going into the dinner break. New Zealand were rocked early after the tea break losing Devon Conway as the southpaw fell 23 runs short of his hundred. Michael Bracewell looked to be positive but perished in his quest to up the ante. The debutant Scott Kuggeleijn got together with Tom Blundell and forged a solid recovery to help New Zealand reduce the lead to under 100 runs. However, the dismissal of Scott Kuggeleijn just before the dinner break has pegged the hosts back again. The onus is now on Tom Blundell to bat with the tail and get his side close to England's first-innings total.
This is pitched up on off stump, Tim Southee pushes it straight back toward the left of mid on for a single. That will be the end of the second session on Day 2!
This is dug in short and over the stumps, Tim Southee ducks under it well.
Full and wide, Southee caresses it through extra cover for a couple of runs.
Shorter in length and over off, Tim Southee hops and keeps it down.

OUT! TIMBER! A peach of a delivery from Ollie Robinson and the resistance from Scott Kuggeleijn comes to an end! Robinson bowls this fuller on off and angles it in but not quite full to drive. Kuggeleijn is drawn forward and he looks to play the on drive. In the end, Kuggeleijn ends up playing all around a straight ball and the ball goes crashing into the stumps as well. New Zealand are 8 down now. Also, Tim Southee walks out to bat now.
Commentary.Howout: b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: Good length on the fifth stump line, left alone by Kuggeleijn.
A bit shorter and outside off, Kuggeleijn steers it down through backward point for a single.
Full and angled into middle, nudged away leg side.
Pitched up on off stump, tucked away to short mid-wicket.
Good length around off, blocked out by Kuggeleijn.
Good length, angling into the pads, Blundell looks to work it leg side but misses. The ball rolls off the pads onto the off side and they get a leg bye.
Length ball around off, Tom Blundell puts a stride across and bunts it out.
Swish and a miss! This is dug in short and outside off, Scott Kuggeleijn looks to rock ball and pull but is well beaten.
Nagging length, in that channel around off, Kuggeleijn goes on the back foot to keep it out.
Goes wider of the crease and angles it into the stumps, Kuggeleijn works it away to square leg.

Halt! The umpires are unhappy with the shape of this ball and they have called for a replacement. The fourth umpire makes his way out with the box of balls for the on-field umpires to choose from. The ball has been handed over to Ollie Robinson and the play will resume now.
Length ball onto the pads, tucked away 'round the corner for a single.
Pitches this one up around off stump, Blundell drives it to the right of mid off and picks up a couple of runs. The 50-run stand is up between these two as well.
Inside-edge! Good length angling into middle and leg, Tom Blundell looks to tuck it away but gets a big inside edge back onto the pads.
Ollie Robinson (12-1-27-2) is back into the attack.
Full and straight, blocked out by Kuggeleijn.
Back of a length outside off, Blundell stays on the back foot and guides it through backward point for one.
Bowls it a bit fuller and on middle, Blundell flicks it uppishly toward mid-wicket.
Full and around off, pushed away onto the off side.
Good length around middle, Blundell flicks it away in front of mid-wicket for a couple of runs.

EDGED AND GONE! Or is it? Tom Blundell has reviewed it straight away! James Anderson bowls this on a good length around off and the ball nips back in sharply off the deck. Blundell gets cut in half as the ball beats the bat but might have taken an inside edge. UltraEDge though shows that it is missing the bat and hitting the pads rather. Ball Tracking is checked for lbw as well but the ball is missing the wickets and it is an excellent review by Blundell. Not Out!
Good length on off stump, blocked out by Kuggeleijn.
A length ball around off, Kuggeleijn defends it out.
Goes full now and bowls it on off stump, Kuggeleijn keeps it out.
A tad shorter and around off, Blundell hops back and nudges it down toward backward point for one.
On a hard length around off, Tom Blundell dabs it down in front of cover-point.
Back of a length around off, Kuggeleijn pushes it off the back foot to the left of mid off for a quick single.
Good length around the top of off, Blundell blocks it off the front foot.
Length ball on off, blocked out.
Goes full and straight now, Blundell punches it straight back to the bowler.

FOUR! Good length around off, Tom Blundell dabs it down with soft hands and runs it down to third man for a boundary. New Zealand now trail by exactly a 100 runs and these are frustrating runs now for England.

A huge appeal this time for lbw but it is turned down yet again! James Anderson bowls it on a length around middle and angles it into the pads. Tom Blundell gets caught on the crease and the ball goes past the inside edge and Blundell is rapped on the pads. This time Ben Stokes does review it. Nothing on UltraEdge and Ball Tracking shows that the ball is missing leg stump.
Half an appeal for caught behind but the umpire isn't interested. Fuller in length and angling down leg, Tom Blundell looks to flick but misses and the ball flicks the pad on its way to the keeper.
Fuller and attacking the off stump, kept out.
This is pitched up on the fifth stump line, Kuggeleijn leaves it alone.
On a length and angled into middle and leg, Blundell works it away through square leg for one.
Broad angles this one into the pads, Blundell gets on the front foot and flicks it straight to mid-wicket.
Fullish length on off, kept out.
FOUR! Skillful from Tom Blundell! Just a fraction short and outside off, Blundell stays back and knocks the ball down as it goes past him through the gully region and into the fence.
Fuller and outside off, Kuggeleijn reaches out and pushes it toward cover.
A touch fuller and angling it into the stumps, Kuggeleijn keeps it out.
Excellent running! Good length around off and swinging back in, Tom Blundell blocks it off the front foot and sets off for the run straightaway.
Back of a length at the stumps, Tom Blundell works this from the crease towards mid-wicket.
