On a length on off, Tom Blundell hangs back and defends this one to mid-wicket.
Starts with a good-length delivery around off, a hint of inward movement, Tom Blundell takes a stride forward to defend but gets an inside edge back onto his pads.
James Anderson (11-5-19-2) comes back on.
Short and on the body, pulled straight to backward square leg.
A yorker now around middle and leg, Tom Blundell stays deep in his crease and jams it out toward short fine leg for a quick single.
Fractionally short and over the stumps, Tom Blundell hangs back and rolls his wrists over the ball before pulling it down to deep backward square leg for a brace. New Zealand now trail by 111!
Banged in short and over middle, Tom Blundell mistimes the pull shot through wide mid on and picks up a couple of runs.
Shorter and on the body, Kuggeleijn gets inside the line and jabs it toward short fine leg for a quick run.
This is banged in short and over off, this is pulled down to mid-wicket.

FOUR! Up and over! Flighted delivery on middle, Tom Blundell dances down the track and forces the lofted shot well over mid on for a boundary. New Zealand now eating away into the English quickly here.

Poor cricket all around! Around off stump, Tom Blundell pushes it out in front of cover and looks for a single but he is sent back. Ben Duckett there picks up the ball and fires in a low throw wide of the keeper and there's no one backing up. The ball rolls away into the fence and that will be the easiest four Blundell has scored in this game.
Flatter and around middle, nudged away onto the leg side.
Tosses it up now on off stump, Tom Blundell uses his feet well but drills it straight to mid on.
Floated up around off, Blundell backs away a bit and pushes it onto the off side.
Nagging length, angled into the leg stump, Blundell goes on the back foot and keeps it out.
And again but this it is hit straight to the man. Banged in short and around off, Kuggeleijn pulls it toward mid-wicket.
FOUR! Hammered away! Fractionally short and around off, Kuggeleijn stays on the back foot and pulls it hard and through wide mid on for a boundary. The 200 is now up for New Zealand.
Comes from around the wicket now and digs it in halfway down the track over leg stump. Scott Kuggeleijn ducks under it well.
Banged in short and over middle, Scott Kuggeleijn pulls it well and in front of square on the leg side for a couple of runs.
Goes full and bowls it on off stump, Scott Kuggeleijn is late on the block and the ball almost sneaks through but luckily for him, it takes the inside edge and goes past the stumps.
This is dragged down the leg side, Tom Blundell just pulls it down to fine leg and gets across for a single. And, that will be FIFTY for Blundell, it has been a fighting knock from him.
Short and at the stumps, Scott Kuggeleijn works this one on the leg side for a dot.
Goes short and on off, Scott Kuggeleijn stays on the back foot and defends it on the off side.
FOUR! Another delivery tossed up, full around off, Scott Kuggeleijn steps out and drills it back past the bowler. Beats the mid off fielder as well and collects a boundary.

SIX! Scott Kuggeleijn goes huge! Jack Leach floats this one full on middle, Scott Kuggeleijn gets down on one knee and executes the slog sweep to perfection. Clears the mid-wicket fence with ease and collects a maximum.
Full and angling in on middle, Scott Kuggeleijn blocks it out.
Flighted, full around off, Scott Kuggeleijn gets on the front foot and defends.
Another bumper at the batter by Stuart Broad, Tom Blundell gets inside the line to pull this one but fails to connect.
Back of a length down the leg side, Tom Blundell looks to tuck this one fine on the leg side but misses.
Short again and on middle, Tom Blundell rides on top of the bounce and pulls it along the ground but fails to get it past square leg.
Short and on leg by Stuart Broad, Scott Kuggeleijn is late on the pull and gets it off his gloves towards fine leg for a single. Also, Scott Kuggeleijn is off the mark in Test cricket.
Short of a length on leg, Tom Blundell pulls it along the ground to backward square leg. A slight fumble there by Joe Root allows the batters to cross for a single.
Starts with a shortish delivery at the batter, Tom Blundell swivels and pulls only to find square leg.
Stuart Broad (11-2-48-1) is back into the attack.
Short and quicker just outside off, Scott Kuggeleijn stays on the back foot and punches it straight to cover.
Flighted, full on middle, Scott Kuggeleijn presses forward and defends it on the leg side.
Full and flatter on off, Scott Kuggeleijn keeps this one out.
Scott Kuggeleijn is the new man in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Another soft dismissal and this time it is Michael Bracewell! Jack Leach floats this one full at the stumps, Michael Bracewell gets tempted by the flight and steps out to go down the ground, Does not get the elevation and he hits it straight to Ben Stokes at mid on. Jack Leach has his first wicket of the game and New Zealand are now 7 down with still 143 runs behind.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Stokes b Jack Leach

Commentary.Commentary: Short and on off, Michael Bracewell pushes this one off the back foot to cover.
Slower and short, turning into the batter, Michael Bracewell stays back and keeps it out.

Michael Bracewell has been hit flush on the helmet but luckily, he seems to be fine. There will be a mandatory concussion check carried out though by the physio. The physio asks Bracewell a bunch of questions and calls for a replacement helmet in accordance with the protocols. The umpires use this prolonged halt to call for drinks as well. It has been an even session thus far after the break but England will certainly be the happier of the two sides as their skipper got rid of Devon Conway as he persisted with some short stuff. After that, Tom Blundell and Michael Bracewell have done well to just tick along.

Leg bye! Ouch, that is a tough blow! Banged into the wicket at the batter by Ben Stokes, Michael Bracewell ducks to evade the delivery but the ball does not bounce and hits him flush on the helmet. The ball rolls towards off side and batters cross for a single.
Switches to 'round the wicket, bowls it short and on leg, Tom Blundell works this one off his hips to deep backward square leg for a single.
Persists with short length but down the leg side, Tom Blundell leaves the ball alone.
Shorter and on off, Michael Bracewell hangs back and drops this one on the off side. Tom Blundell calls him for a quick single and he obliges.
Short and on middle and leg, Tom Blundell gets on top of the bounce and pulls it towards deep backward square leg for a single.
Starts with a short delivery aimed at the batter, Tom Blundell gets inside the line and leaves it alone.
Short and on leg, Michael Bracewell stays back and works it to short leg.
Short and turning into the batter, Michael Bracewell smothers the ball on the leg side.
Short and flatter on off, Tom Blundell cuts this one to deep point for a single.
FOUR! Flighted, full around off, Tom Blundell shimmies down the track and slices this one over Ben Stokes at mid off for a boundary.
Tossed up, full on middle, Tom Blundell uses his feet and works it to mid on.
Tossed up, full on middle, Tom Blundell presses forward and defends.
Short and on leg, Michael Bracewell ducks underneath the delivery and lets it go.
Sharp bouncer! Ben Stokes goes short again and bowls it at the batter, Michael Bracewell rises to defend but gets rapped on the gloves. The ball drops safely on the off side.
Banged in short on off, Michael Bracewell ducks under it and lets it go.
Slower and a touch fuller but down the leg side, Michael Bracewell leaves the ball alone.
Slower and into the wicket on leg, Tom Blundell gets into the shot early as he tried to pull. Gets a top edge but it falls in no man's land behind square on the leg side for a single.

NO BALL AND FOUR! Short and punished! Goes short again and at the batter, Tom Blundell gets into the positon early and pulls it hard on the leg side. Gets it through square leg for a boundary. Ben Stokes has overstepped again, his third no ball in two overs.
Short and outside off, Tom Blundell does not reach out to the delivery and leaves it alone.
Tossed up, full at the stumps, Michael Bracewell advances and goes for a hoick across the line. Gets it over mid-wicket for a couple of runs.

FOUR! Just wide! Flighted, fuller around off by Jack Leach, Michael Bracewell uses his feet and plays this one with the turn. Drives it uppishly but gets it just wide of the diving Ollie Robinson at mid on for a boundary.
Short and turning in on off, Michael Bracewell gets behind the line and defends it back to the bowler.
Short and fraction outside off, Tom Blundell picks the length early and rocks back in his crease. Cuts it late and gets it past backward point for three runs.
Short and around off, Tom Blundell punches it off the back foot but cannot beat Ben Duckett at extra cover.
Full and quicker on off, Tom Blundell drives this one to mid on for a dot.

OUT! CAUGHT! The short ball ploy does the trick for England! Ben Stokes goes short again and bowls it outside off, Devon Conway does not get on top of the bounce but still tries to drag this one on the leg side. Ends up pulling this one straight to Ollie Pope at square leg who makes no mistake. England are delighted and so they should be. New Zealand have been pegged back once again and they are now 6 wickets down.
Commentary.Howout: c Ollie Pope b Ben Stokes

Commentary.Commentary: Michael Bracewell walks out to bat now.
NO BALL! Short but angling down the leg side, Tom Blundell pulls this one towards fine leg and rotates the strike. Stokes has overstepped again.
Short of a length on middle, Devon Conway rides on top of the bounce and pulls it to deep backward square leg for a single.
Bumper outside off, Devon Conway does not reach out to the delivery and leaves it alone.
Back of a length angling down the leg side, Tom Blundell gets inside the line and tucks it to the left of fine leg for a single.
NO BALL! Short and at the batter, Devon Conway pulls it along the ground to fine leg for a single. Ben Stokes has overstepped and it is signalled as a no ball.
Banged in short again and on off, Devon Conway goes for the pull but does not manage to execute the shot this time. Mishits it to mid-wicket.
Continues to go short and bowls it on off, Devon Conway gets on top of the bounce and pulls it towards deep mid-wicket.
Flatter and quicker at the stumps, Tom Blundell keeps this one out.
Short and on off, Tom Blundell goes on the back foot and punches it straight to cover.
Fuller on off, Tom Blundell drives this one straight to mid off.
Flighted, full at the stumps, Tom Blundell presses forward and blocks it out.

Leach floats this one full and on off, Tom Blundell steps out but does not get to the pitch of the delivery but still goes through with the shot. Slices this one over mid off and collects a couple of runs. Ollie Robinson back tracked but it was out of his reach.
Tossed up, full on middle and leg, Tom Blundell shimmies down the track and goes down the ground but cannot beat James Anderson at mid on.
Another short delivery on leg, Tom Blundell rises and works it to fine leg for a single. 150 comes up for New Zealand.
Shortish delivery at the batter, Devon Conway pulls it along the ground to fine leg and rotates the strike.
Short again and outside off, Devon Conway tries to drag this one towards leg side but hits it a bit uppishly. Gets it between square leg and mid-wicket.
Continues with short stuff and bowls it on leg, Tom Blundell gets inside the line of the delivery and helps it to deep backward square leg for a single.
Short of a length on leg by Ben Stokes, Devon Conway swivels in the crease and pulls it to fine leg for a single.
Short and around off, Devon Conway gets on top of the bounce and pulls it on the bounce towards square leg.
Full on middle, Tom Blundell gets forward and keeps it out.
Floated, full on middle, Tom Blundell pushes it back to the bowler. Jack Leach collects and fires a throw back at the striker's end.
FOUR! Nicely played! Fraction short and on off by Jack Leach, Tom Blundell rocks back in his crease and punches it on the off side. Pierces the gap in the covers region and collects a boundary.
Fuller around off, Tom Blundell presses forward and defends it to cover.
Tossed up, full at the stumps, Tom Blundell steps out and drills it back past the bowler but fails to get it past the substitute fielder Matthew Potts at mid on.
Starts with a flighted delivery, full around off, Tom Blundell gets forward and pushes it to extra cover.
Jack Leach (7-1-24-0) to operate from the other end.
Back of a length on middle, Tom Blundell tucks this one off his hips to deep backward square leg. Retains the strike with a single.
Keeps it short and on off, Tom Blundell gets on top of the bounce and works it to mid-wicket.
Slower and into the wicket outside off, Devon Conway plays a controlled pull shot to deep square leg for a single.
Short of a length on leg, Tom Blundell gets on his toes and works it behind square on the leg side for a single.
Persists with short length at the batter, Tom Blundell rises to fend this one but gets hit on the gloves. Luckily for him, the ball does not lob up.
Goes short again but a bit down the leg side, Tom Blundell gets inside the line of the delivery and leaves it alone.
WIDE! Banged in short and around off, Tom Blundell sways away and lets it go. The ball sails over the batter's head and it is signalled as a wide.

We are back for the post-Tea session on Day 2! The umpires are back out in the middle and so are the players of England. Tom Blundell and Devon Conway are all set to resume their innings as well. And, it will be the English skipper Ben Stokes to start proceedings with the ball here. It's the first time we will see Stokes bowl in this game. No slips in play and people are stationed in the deep on the leg side so a lot of short stuff is to be expected. Let's play...
... DAY 2, SESSION 2 ...

England failed to start well with the ball as they were a bit off with their lines and lengths. Neil Wagner did trouble them but Stuart Broad foxed him with a slower delivery to hand his side a much-needed breakthrough. It was then Ollie Robinson who struck after being brought on as the first change. The visitors brought on Jack Leach and Joe Root in search of wickets but the duo have not extracted any purchase from the surface and have failed to trouble the opposition batters. The visitors are still in a strong position and will look to assess their game plans during the tea break. Do join us back at 8.50 am IST (3.20 am GMT) for the second session on Day 2.

Session Summary - 28 overs, 101 runs and 2 wickets. As the first session on Day 2 comes to an end, both teams will be pleased with their efforts in the first session. Neil Wagner and Devon Conway resumed their innings for New Zealand and were positive in their approach. Wagner in particular took charge before being dismissed for 27 runs. Daryl Mitchell followed him back into the hut after failing to trouble the scorers. Despite losing wickets at the other hand, Devon Conway has looked in complete control and is 28 runs short of the three-figure mark. Tom Blundell took his time initially but grew in confidence later in his innings. However, the job is far from over yet and this Kiwi pair need to carry on and get New Zealand close to parity in the sessions to follow.
Floated up around off, Devon Conway gets on the front foot and presents a dead bat at it. That will be the end of the first session on Day 2 as New Zealand still trail by 187 runs.
Short again and outside off, Blundell latches onto the width and taps it toward cover for a quick single.
Nagging length, around off and just turning away a touch, Blundell goes back and across to push it onto the off side.
Just fractionally short and around off, this is eased out toward cover.
Drifted onto middle, Blundell makes another easy block.
Shorter and on off, Blundell goes on the back foot and pushes it back to the bowler.
Flatter one outside off, Devon Conway lets it through to the keeper. A maiden!
Pulls the length back and tries to attack the off stump, Conway gets a good stride forward and blocks it out.
Tosses it up full and outside off, left alone by Conway.
Around off, kept out.
Gives it a lot of air and bowls it well wide of the off stump, tempting the batter but Conway leaves it alone.
Tossed up around middle, Conway drives it inside out to short cover.
This is fuller and drifted onto middle, Blundell keeps it out.
Flighted delivery on the stumps, blocked out.
FOUR! Top shot! Tossed up on middle and leg, Tom Blundell uses hi feet and drives it straight back past mid on and into the fence.
Shortens the length now and angles it onto the pads, Blundell pushes it out to mid on.
Tossed up around leg stump, Blundell uses his feet and flicks it straight to mid-wicket.
Flighted delivery, drifted onto middle, Blundeel blocks it off the front foot.
Floated up full and on off, Conway defends it out with soft hands.
This is around the pads, Conway goes back in his crease and works it away in front of square leg for a couple of runs. The 50 partnership is up between these, a crucial stand this for New Zealand.
Flighted delivery on the stumps, kept out.
FOUR! Fast hands from Devon Conway. Short and wide, Conway hops on the back foot and pounces on the loose ball as he cuts it hard and behind point for a boundary.
Very slow through the air and shorter in length as well, Conway waits for it and makes the block.
Shorter in length around off, punched away toward cover.
Spin from both ends as Joe Root returns to the attack.
Good fielding and that will be a maiden for Jack Leach. Tossed up on the pads, Blundell steps out and flicks it to the right of mid-wicket where Harry Brook makes a sharp stop.
Can't pierce the gap! Short again, Tom Blundell rocks back and punches it straight to cover.
Slower and shorter on off stump, pushed out onto the off side off the back foot.
Full and drifting onto middle and on off, Blundell keeps it out.
A tad shorter and around off, Blundell goes on the back foot and punches it out toward cover.
Floated up, very full and on middle, Blundell blocks it out.
Jack Leach (4-0-19-0) comes back into the attack.
This is on a perfect length and angled onto middle, Conway defends it out.
Pitches it up around the off stump, Conway makes a solid block off the front foot.
A touch fuller and angled into the legs, Blundell tucks it 'round the corner for a single.
Hard length around off, seaming away a touch, Blundell shoulders arms.

Full and around middle, Devon Conway flicks it away with nice timing in front of mid-wicket. James Anderson from mid-wicket hares toward the ball and manages to pull it back in. Three runs are taken and New Zealand have successfully avoided the follow-on.
Comes from around the wicket to the left-hander and angles one in around the top of off middle. Devon Conway blocks it out but gets a little blow on the gloves as well.
Tossed up around off, Devon Conway steps out and works it to deepish mid off for an easy single.
Root sees Conway advancing and shortens the length. Conway ends up pushing it off the inside edge onto the leg side.
Flighted delivery on off stump, Conway defends it off the front foot.
A bit flatter and shorter at the stumps, Conway makes the block.
Floated up around off, Conway blocks it out.
Excellent stop! Tossed up around off, Devon Conway steps out and creams the cover drive but Ollie Pope makes a sharp stop at short extra cover.
Pitched up in that channel around off and zipping through. Blundell leaves it alone.
The call is for two straightaway and they get it with ease. Shortish delivery on the pads, Blundell stays back and tucks it away in front of mid-wicket for a brace.
Goes full and bowls it on off stump, Blundell pushes it back to the bowler.
Pitched up around the off pole, Tom Blundell caresses it straight to the cover fielder.
On a length outside off, Blundell gets on the front foot and taps it in front of cover.
Full and on the fifth stump line, Tom Blundell looks to drive away from the body but gets a big inside edge back onto the pads.
Full and around off, Devon Conway gets the cover drive through the gap and picks up a couple of runs.
Gives it a nice bit of loop and floats it around off stump, Conway blocks it out.

SIX! Looks like Devon Conway has had enough of Joe Root and decides to take him on. This is tossed up on off stump, Conway comes down the pitch and smokes it well over the long off fence for a biggie.
Flatter one around off, kept out.

Straight as an arrow! Tossed up full and on middle, Devon Conway steps out and drills it onto the stumps at the bowler's end. Joe Root might have got a boot on it and the umpires have gone upstairs to check for the run-out. The replays show that Root did stick out his left foot but the ball might have just under his foot and UltraEdge shows a flat line as well. There's no conclusive evidence of the ball flicking the boot and hence it will be Not Out.
Floated up around off stump, Conway prods forward and defends it out.

Excellent delivery to end the over and its back-to-back maidens for England. On a good length, in that channel around off and this one nips back in sharply off the deck. Tom Blundell gets caught on the crease and gets a blow high on the pads.
Pitches it right up in that corridor of uncertainty, Blundell stays solid in defense though.
Good length around the top of off, blocked out.
Bowls it a bit fuller and pushes it wider of the off stump, Blundell leaves it alone.
Probing line from Robinson, in and around that fourth stump line, Blundell gets on the front foot and keeps it out.
On a length outside the off stump and staying a touch low as well. Tom Blundell lets it through to the keeper.
Change of ends for Ollie Robinson.
Maiden! Excellent first over from Joe Root. Flighted delivery around off, very full as well, Conway bunts it straight to short cover.
Almost a chance! Floats it up does Joe Root around the off stump and induces the false drive from Devon Conway who almost ends up chipping it straight to covers.
Tossed up around off, Conway keeps it out.
Nicely bowled! This is bowled right in the blockhole around off, Devon Conway looks to drive but the ball sneaks under the willow.
Around off, pushed out toward cover.
Starts off with a friendly full toss around middle, Devon Conway misses out as he pushes it along the ground to mid on.
Joe Root comes on to bowl, replacing Ollie Robinson.
Around the pads, this is nudged away down to leg gully.
Short again and outside off, Blundell hops on the back foot and cuts it well in front of cover-point for a couple of runs.
Tossed up around off, Tom Blundell uses his feet well and pushes it straight to mid off.
Quicker one, a bit fuller and around middle, Blundell looks to use his feet but has to adjust and blocks it out.
Drifted onto the leg stump, Blundell keeps it out.
FOUR! Nicely done! Short and outside off, Tom Blundell goes back and across to just cut it past the diving point fielder for a boundary.
Pitched up on off stump, this is driven straight down the ground but the fielder from mid off gets across and cuts it off.
On a length around off and slanting across the left-hander, Conway leaves it alone.
A bit of a floater on the pads, Tom Blundell tickles it down to fine leg and rotates the strike.
This is banged in short and over middle, Conway gets on top of the bounce and pulls it down through mid-wicket for one.
Pitches it a bit further up and in that channel around off, Conway shoulders arms.
On a good length from around the wicket and close to the off pole, Devon Conway blocks it from inside his crease.
Use of the feet from Tom Blundell! Flighted delivery around middle and leg, Blundell comes forward and hits it on the full toward mid on.
Floated up on a nagging length and on off stump, Blundell blocks it out.
Nicely drifted onto middle, Blundell defends it off the front foot.
Pushed through quicker and fuller on middle and leg, Tom Blundell keeps it out.
A tad shorter and on the pads, Conway uses the depth of the crease to work it 'round the corner for one.
Tossed up, full and turning in on off, Devon Conway pushes this one towards mid-wicket.
Fuller and on off by Ollie Robinson, Tom Blundell keeps this one out on the off side.
On a length outside off, Tom Blundell shoulders arms and leaves the ball alone.
Back of a length and on middle, Tom Blundell stays back and clips it through mid-wicket for a couple of runs.

FIFTY for Devon Conway! Ollie Robinson goes full and just outside off, Devon Conway gets on the front foot and drives it along the ground through the vacant covers region. Collects three runs to bring up his fifty. This has been a fine knock by the southpaw but the job is far from over yet.
On a good length and angling into the batter, Devon Conway fends this one on the leg side.
Fuller and outside off by Ollie Robinson, Devon Conway keeps this one out.
Full and on middle, Tom Blundell gets forward and defends it down the wicket.
FOUR! Cut away by Tom Blundell! Fraction short and quicker around off, Tom Blundell goes back in his crease and cuts it late. Gets it through short third man and opens his account with a boundary.
Floated, full on off, Tom Blundell gets on the front foot and defends it on the off side.
Flighted, full and turning in on off, Devon Conway picks the length early and drives it through covers. Does not time it too well and has to settle for three runs.
Fraction short and turning in on leg, Devon Conway looks to work it on the leg side but does not connect.
FOUR! Nicely played! Tossed up, full and outside off by Jack Leach, Devon Conway does not miss out as he frees his arms and drives it through covers for a boundary.

DRINKS! Devon Conway ​​​​and Neil Wagner began the day for New Zealand and it was the latter who put on a show before being dismissed. Daryl Mitchell followed him back into the hut and that put New Zealand in big trouble. They need a partnership here to get them close to England's first innings score. On the other hand, England bowlers have been on the money since the start of the day and they will be looking to get into the Kiwi tail as soon as possible.
Full and on off by Ollie Robinson, Tom Blundell solidly keeps this one out.

Switches to 'round the wicket and bowls it full at the stumps, Devon Conway looks to work it on the leg side but gets an inside edge back onto his pads. The ball goes to the left of Ollie Pope at short leg and Conway takes a single.
On a good length in the channel outside off, Devon Conway defends this one from the inner part of the bat towards mid on.
Fuller and outside off by Ollie Robinson, Devon Conway pushes this one towards mid off.
Angled away fuller outside off, Devon Conway shoulders arms and leaves the ball alone.
On a length drifting at the pads, Devon Conway tucks this one to the left of fine leg and collects a couple of runs.
Short and quicker at the stumps, Tom Blundell blocks this one out off the back foot.
Tossed up, full on off, Tom Blundell goes on the front foot and defends it to short cover.
Short and turning away on off, Tom Blundell goes back in his crease to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Shortens his length and bowls it at the batter, Devon Conway swivels in his crease and pulls it to deep square leg for a single.
Fuller and on off by Jack Leach, Devon Conway gets behind the line of the delivery and keeps it out.
Starts with a flighted delivery, full outside off, Devon Conway gets on the front foot and defends it on the off side.
Spin for the first time on Day 2 as Jack Leach comes on to bowl.
Angling in on off by Ollie Robinson, Tom Blundell gets on the front foot to defend but gets it from the inner part of the bat towards square leg.
Keeps it full and at the stumps, Tom Blundell watchfully blocks this one out.
Fuller and swinging at the stumps, Tom Blundell gets on the front foot and defends it back to the bowler.
Tom Blundell is the new man in.

OUT! LBW! Ollie Robinson strikes in his first over of the day and removes Daryl Mitchell. Bowls this one full and around off, the ball nips back a bit after pitching, Daryl Mitchell takes a big stride forward and looks to leave the delivery. The ball catches him on the front pad and the umpire raises the dreaded finger. Daryl Mitchell has a word with Devon Conway but he decides not to review. New Zealand have lost half their side with still trailing by 242 runs.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: Fuller and at the stumps, Daryl Mitchell pushes this one a bit uppishly but to the right of Ollie Robinson.
Starts with a short delivery on off, Devon Conway pulls it along the ground to deep square leg for a single.
Ollie Robinson is introduced into the attack.
Full and on off, Daryl Mitchell takes a stride forward and pushes it with a straight bat. James Anderson at mid on dives to his left and makes a good stop.
Fuller outside off by Stuart Broad, Daryl Mitchell gets forward and blocks this one out towards point.
Length delivery at the stumps, Daryl Mitchell shuffles across and clips it towards mid-wicket. The fielder there fumbles but batters decide not to take a single.
On a good length, a hint of away movement, Daryl Mitchell advances and shoulders arms to the delivery.
Goes full again on middle and leg, Daryl Mitchell drives but finds James Anderson at mid on.
Full and outside off by Stuart Broad, Daryl Mitchell steps out and drives it firmly down the ground but fails to get it past mid on.
On a good length on off by James Anderson, Devon Conway takes a stride forward and defends this one on the off side.
Fuller and angling at the pads, Devon Conway turns this one straight to square leg.
Pitches it full and around off, Devon Conway gets behind the line and pushes it back to the bowler.
Switches to 'round the wicket, Devon Conway gets forward and keeps this one out on the leg side.
Back of a length on off, Devon Conway hangs back and defends this one on the off side.
Full and on off by James Anderson, Devon Conway blocks this one solidly off the front foot.

Keeps it on a good length just outside off, Daryl Mitchell takes a big stride forward to defend but gets rapped on the front pad. England go up in appeal but the umpire shakes his head. It looked like the impact was outside the off stump.
On a good length around off by Stuart Broad, Daryl Mitchell gets on the front foot and defends it on the leg side.
Daryl Mitchell walks in at number 6.

OUT! CAUGHT! Neil Wagner's show is finally over! Stuart Broad bowls it slow and touch fuller on middle from 'round the wicket, Neil Wagner gets deceived by the pace of the delivery and ends up chipping it towards mid on. Ollie Robinson there runs to his left and completes an easy catch. First breakthrough on Day 2 for England and Stuart Broad.
Commentary.Howout: c Ollie Robinson b Stuart Broad

Commentary.Commentary: SIX! Neil Wagner is putting on a show here! Stuart Broad goes short again and at the stumps, Neil Wagner swivels his crease and decides to take on the short ball. Goes for the pull but gets a top edge that flies over fine leg for a maximum.
SIX! Banged in short at the batter, Neil Wagner stays on the back foot and pulls this one towards the vacant deep backward square leg region for a maximum.

FOUR! Easy pickings for Neil Wagner! Back of a length and on leg, Neil Wagner gets inside the line of the ball and uses the pace of the delivery. Gets it wide of Ben Foakes behind the wicket and collects a boundary.
Fuller and just outside off, Devon Conway pushes this one off the front foot to mid off.
Keeps it on a length on leg, Devon Conway uses his feet and goes for the flick but misses and gets hit high on the pad.
Length delivery at the stumps, Devon Conway solidly blocks this one out down the wicket.
On a good length around off, Devon Conway defends this one on the leg side.

FOUR! Goes full this time on off, Devon Conway gets into the position early and drives it back past the bowler. Does not time this one well but the ball has enough legs on it to reach the boundary towards long off.
Fuller and angling away outside off, Devon Conway lets it go.
Banged in short at the batter, Neil Wagner goes for the pull but misses and gets hit on the body.
On a length at the stumps, Neil Wagner watchfully blocks this one out.

NO BALL! Goes short this time and at the batter, Neil Wagner swivels in his crease and helps this one towards fine leg. The ball travels to Jack Leach at fine leg who completes the catch after multiple juggling attempts. However, the umpire signals a no ball and Neil Wagner survives.
Straying at the pads and on a fuller length, Devon Conway rolls his wrists and clips it to deep square leg for a single.
Fuller in length and at the stumps, Devon Conway gets behind the line and defends it back to the bowler.
On a length just outside off, Devon Conway shoulders arms and leaves the ball alone.
Full and on middle by Stuart Broad, Devon Conway picks the length early and clips this one through the vacant mid-wicket region for a couple of runs.
Back of a length and angling away outside off, Neil Wagner hangs back to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge by the sharp bounce.

Good stop! Switches to over the wicket, full and at the stumps, Devon Conway pushes this one towards mid on where Stuart Broad dives to his left and keeps it to one. Looks like Broad has injured himself in the process but will continue for now.
Full and outside off, Devon Conway uses his feet and drives it down the ground but fails to get it past Stuart Broad at mid on.
Fuller in length on off by James Anderson, Devon Conway takes a big stride forward and watchfully defends it on the off side.
Keeps it on a good length in the channel outside off, Devon Conway guides this one towards gully for a dot.
On a length around off from 'round the wicket, Devon Conway stays on the back foot and dabs it towards point.
Beaten! Goes full and outside off, the ball moves away after pitching, Neil Wagner looks to drive it on the up but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Angled in around off on a good length by Stuart Broad, Neil Wagner solidly blocks this one out on the off side.
On a good length and shaping away outside off, Neil Wagner shoulders arms and lets it go.
Keeps it full and at the pads, Neil Wagner this time goes along the ground and clips it through mid-wicket for another brace.
Full and swinging in on leg by Stuart Broad, Neil Wagner allows the ball to swing and flick this one in the air but wide of Ollie Robinson at deep square leg. A couple of runs taken.
Back of a length and angling in at the batter from 'round the wicket, Neil Wagner looks to turn this one on the leg side but misses and gets hit on the thigh pad.
Back of a length at the batter, Devon Conway stays back and defends it on the leg side.
Switches to 'round the wicket and bowls it on a good length around off, Devon Conway keeps this one out from the crease.
Back of a length and shaping away outside off, Neil Wagner stays on the back foot to push it on the off side but gets it from the inner part of the bat tos square leg for a single.
Fuller at the stumps, Neil Wagner defends this one down the wicket towards mid off.
On a length on off and swinging away, Neil Wagner accounts for the swing and pushes it to mid-wicket.

Keeps it on a good length on leg, Neil Wagner goes for the clip without much foot movement and gets caught right in front of the stumps. England go up in unison but it is turned down by the umpire. The visitors send it upstairs after a deliberation. The UltraEdge shows no bat but it is pitching outside leg on Ball Tracking. The onfield decision will stand and England lose their review.

James Anderson starts with a no ball. Bowls this one on a good length around off, Neil Wagner hangs back and looks to punch this one on the leg side but gets an inside edge that rolls to fine leg for a couple of runs.
James Anderson will bowl from the other end.

FOUR! Glorious by Devon Conway! Stuart Broad goes full and on off, Devon Conway gets himself into a great position and gets well behind the line. Presents a straight bat and drives it down the wicket. Hits it to the right of mid on and collects yet another boundary. An expensive first over by Stuart Broad.
Fuller on middle by Stuart Broad, Devon Conway blocks this one out towards square leg.

FOUR! On a length and on leg, Devon Conway tries to work this one on the leg side, gets it from the inner part of the bat and the outfield does the rest. Jack Leach fails to get there in time to stop the boundary.
Back of a length and slanting in on middle, cuts Devon Conway in half as he goes on the back foot to defend.
Full and around off, Devon Conway gets on the front foot and defends this one on the off side.

FOUR! What a way to start Day 2! Stuart Broad bowls this one full and angling at the pads from 'round the wicket, Devon Conway uses his feet and helps this one towards fine leg. Gets it just wide of Jack Leach there and collects a boundary on the first ball.

We are all set for the play to commence on Day 2. The umpires and players make their way out in the middle. Neil Wagner and Devon Conway will resume the innings for New Zealand. Stuart Broad will start the proceedings with the ball for England. Let's play...

New Zealand are currently reeling with the bat and need a big stand from somewhere to cut into the deficit and they will have a chance to do so as there were scoring opportunities on offer in the first session on Day 1. Devon Conway will be key for them as he has faced enough deliveries to muster up a few important runs here. England do have James Anderson firing on all cylinders at the moment and if he can make the ball talk early on Day 2, then the visitors can really inflict more misery onto the hosts. Will the Kiwis be able to turn things around and get back on level terms on Day 2? Or will England continue to dominate proceedings? We shall find out soon.

Hello and a very warm welcome to Day 2 of the first Test match between New Zealand and England at the Bay Oval in Mount Manganui. Day 1 was filled with a lot of action but it was the visitors who put their foot on the accelerator and made things happen, be it with the bat or with the ball in hand. England will now look to simply extend their advantage.

Right then, a total of 362 runs were scored in 76.2 overs on the first day and 12 wickets fell as well. England continued to play aggressively with the bat and notched up 325 runs in less than two and a half sessions. The decision to then declare was a welcome one and they have got the hosts firmly pushed back on the ropes. Will New Zealand fight their way back into the contest early on Day 2? We shall find out. Day 2 will begin on Friday at 6.30 am IST (1 am GMT) and it sure looks to be an exciting one. You can though join us a lot earlier for the build-up as well. Cheers!

New Zealand will be a bit disappointed with their efforts on the whole as they gave away far too many easy runs with the ball and then, they weren't positive enough with the bat late in the day. Tom Latham got out early playing a poor shot and then Devon Conway and Kane Williamson tried to build a stand. Neither of them ever looked in control and soon after, Williamson fell. Henry Nicholls came in and got out early as well, leaving Conway stranded on one end with the night watchman. Neil Wagner though has done well enough not to get out but the hosts will look to try and better their efforts on Day 2.

Ben Stokes declared with plenty of time remaining in the final session and this decision proved to be a masterstroke as the new pink ball under lights did help the English pacers. It was Ollie Robinson who was brought on as first change in the fifth over who got the first breakthrough and after a bit of resistance from the Kiwis, James Anderson came back for his second spell and picked up a couple of vital wickets. The visitors will now look to press home the advantage early on Day 2 and try and get a sizeable first innings lead.

What an entertaining day of cricket we have witnessed here and it is just Day 1! The game ebbed and flowed but certainly, at the end of Day 1, it will be England who will be the happier of the two sides going into Day 2 as they have simply pinged New Zealand on the back foot via their aggressive approach. The hosts still trail by 288 runs and have 7 wickets in hand.
Back of a length around off by James Anderson, Neil Wagner stays on the back foot and dabs this one towards gully. That will be STUMPS on Day 1!
Full and angling in at the stumps, Neil Wagner blocks this one out on the leg side.
Bowls it on a length outside off from 'round the wicket, the ball nips away after pitching and beats Neil Wagner on the outside edge.
Short of a length on leg, Neil Wagner fends this one wide of short leg for a dot.
Fuller around off by James Anderson, Neil Wagner gets behind the line and blocks this one out towards mid off. There was a single on offer but the batters decide not to run.
Length delivery angling into the pads from over the wicket, Neil Wagner goes for the flick but misses and gets hit on the thigh pad.

Full and angling at the stumps from 'round the wicket, Devon Conway gets behind the line and defends this one towards mid on. First maiden over of the game for Stuart Broad. Last over of the day coming up.
Fullish delivery at the stumps, Devon Conway shuffles across and squeezes this one to mid on.
Pitches this one full and on leg, Devon Conway looks to turn this one on the leg side but miscues it to mid on.
Back of a length around off by Stuart Broad, Devon Conway hangs back and lets it go through to the keeper.
Full and going away outside off, Devon Conway shoulders arms and leaves the ball alone.
Full and angling in on off from 'round the wicket, Devon Conway leans forward and keeps this one out.
On a length at the stumps, Devon Conway works this one towards mid-wicket and retains the strike with a single.
Beautiful bowling from James Anderson! Bowls it full and swinging around off, Devon Conway gets forward to defend but luckily for him, the ball does not catch the outside edge.
Switches to round the wicket and bowls it on a length outside off, Devon Conway does not reach out to the delivery and lets it go.
Goes full this time searching for swing, bowls it on off, Neil Wagner drives this one back past the bowler. Gets it to the left of mid on and collects three runs.
On a good length, going across on off, Neil Wagner shoulders arms and leaves the ball alone.
Peach of a delivery! James Anderson angles this one on a length in the channel outside off, Neil Wagner stays leg side of the ball and tries to defend but misses.
This is pitched up around middle, Devon Conway blocks it out.
On the pads yet again, Neil Wagner deflects it down to the fine leg region and gets off the mark with a single.
On the bounce! Full and down leg, Devon Conway flicks it uppishly but the ball lands well in front of Jack Leach at deepish backward square leg. They pick up a single.
Full and straight, Conway drives it off the inner half of the bat toward short mid on.
Good length around the pads, Devon Conway keeps it down in front of a deepish short leg.
Comes from around the wicket and angles one in from outside the off stump, Devon Conway leaves it alone.
Stuart Broad (4-0-10-0) returns to the attack.
A wicket-maiden! Pitches this one up in and around the off stump and angles it across. Neil Wagner looks to block but is beaten on the outside edge once again. Top-drawer stuff from James Anderson!
A bit fuller and on off, pushed away toward mid on.
Well bowled! Back of a length around off stump, Neil Wagner tries to get behind the line of the ball but it zips past the outside edge.
Neil Wagner is the next batter in.

OUT! EDGED AND GONE! Quality bowling this from the senior pacer. James Anderson stays over the wicket and bowls it on a good length on off stump with the natural angle taking it away from the left hander. Henry Nicholls doesn't move his feet and gets caught on the crease and is forced to play at it. The ball takes the outside edge and Zak Crawley redeems himself at second slip as he takes a good low catch down to his right. New Zealand in a spot of bother now.
Commentary.Howout: c Zak Crawley b James Anderson

Commentary.Commentary: Around the top of off and angling across, Nicholls shoulders arms.
A length ball, swinging down the leg side, Henry Nicholls looks to tickle it fine but misses.
Pitched up around the fifth stump line, left alone by Conway.
Pitched up on off stump, Devon Conway looks to push at it but gets an inside edge back onto the pads.
Fullish length angling it across the left-hander, left alone by Conway.
Comes from over the wicket now and bowls it full, trying to slide one across the off stump. Conway looks to defend off the front foot but gets an inside edge.
Pulls the length back and bowls it around the top of off, Conway leaves it alone.
FOUR! Crisp hit from Devon Conway! Overpitched and around off, Conway gets on the front foot and strokes it away through extra cover for a boundary.
Around the top of off again and it is just kept down on the off side by Nicholls.
Good length around the top of off stump, Henry Nicholls looks to get behind the line but gets beaten and gets hit high on the pads.
And again! Full and on the pads, tucked away behind square leg for two more.
On a length and angling onto the pads, Henry Nicholls works it away behind square on the leg side for a couple of runs to get off the mark.

OUT! LBW! A brilliant review from England and they have got the big fish. James Anderson bowls this one a touch fuller and angles it in from around the off stump. Kane Williamson looks to block with a straight bat but ends up getting beaten on the inside edge. The ball goes on to rap hi on the pads and there is a loud appeal. Anderson cannot believe it and Ben Stokes immediately reviews. Nothing on UltraEdge and Ball Tracking comes up with three reds. Williamson departs for a low score and England right on top of proceedings here.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b James Anderson

Commentary.Commentary: Henry Nicholls walks in at number 4.
On a length and outside the off stump, Williamson leaves it alone.
Full and straight, punched right back at the bowler.
Good length around the top of off stump, Conway blocks it off the inside edge back onto the deck.

Excellent take by the keeper Ben Foakes. Ollie Robinson bowls this one full and on leg stump and the ball just keeps on swinging down the leg side. Foakes springs to his right and pouches it with one hand.
Good length in that channel around off and Conway makes a leave.
Full and on off stump, Devon Conway with a gentle push right back past the bowler. Ben Stokes from mid off chases it down and keeps it down to a couple of runs.
Good length wide of the off stump, left alone by Conway.
A tad shorter and over middle, Williamson keeps it down on the on-side.
On a length and on off stump, kept out by Williamson.
Leg bye! This one is angling down the leg side, Devon Conway misses the flick and gets it off his pads toward backward square leg. The get a leg bye.

DROPPED! Zak Crawley at second slip has put down a sitter! James Anderson bowls it on a good length around off, angling it in. The ball just straightens a touch off the deck and Devon Conway gets an outside edge pushing at it. The ball goes straight into the bread basket and pops out. A huge chanced missed this by Crawley and England.
Keeps the length a bit fuller and the line tight around off stump. Conway gets a solid stride forward and defends it on the off side.
Pitches it up around the off stump, Conway pushes it out to the right of the bowler.
Change of ends for James Anderson.

Half a shout for lbw but it is turned down. On a good length around off stump and angled in. Kane Williamson looks to block but gets beaten on the inside edge and gets hit high on the back leg. Ollie Robinson has a chat with Ben Stokes and they decide against the review. The replays show that it was going over the stumps, so a good decision not to review.
Very full around the fifth stump line, left alone by Williamson.
Full and straight, this is worked away in front of mid-wicket for a run.
Excellent leave! Ollie Robinson bowls it on a good length outside off and angles it in a long way. Devon Conway makes the leave and the ball goes over the top of the stumps.
Pitched up right on off stump, Conway makes a solid block off the front foot.
Nice and full in that corridor of uncertainty, Devon Conway decides to leave it alone.
Good length around middle, defended out with soft hands.
Pitches it up well outside off and this one straightens after pitching. Williamson shoulders arms to it.
Goes a bit wider of the crease and tries to angle it in a long way from outside off. Williamson solidly keeps it out.
Back of a length around off and nipping back in off the deck. Williamson looks to block but misses and wears it on the thigh pad.
A tad short and outside off, tapped away past the point fielder for a single.

Just short! Pitched up around middle, Devon Conway looks to flick and does so uppishly to the right of the man at short mid-wicket. Ollie Robinson dives well to his right but pouches the ball on the bounce.

A probing delivery to end yet another probing over from Ollie Robinson. Serves it on a good length around off and angles it into the off stump. Kane Williamson tries to get behind the line of the ball but the ball seams away off the deck and beats the outside edge.
Pitches it up now outside off and Williamson leaves it alone.
Good length around off and this one nips back in off the deck. Williamson makes an assured leave.

Lovely bowling! Ollie Robinson comes from over the wicket now and serves a scrambled-seam delivery, full and around off. The ball angles in but leaves the batter and Williamson ends up playing inside the line of the ball.
Goes full now and angles it down leg, Conway flicks it away down to fine leg for a single.
Pitches it up a bit in that channel around off, Devon Conway pushes it out on the off side.
Length again around off, Williamson blocks it off the front foot.
FOUR! Soft hands! Fullish length outside off, Kane Williamson plays it late under his eye-line and knocks it down past the slip cordon for a boundary.
Good length around off and this one seams back in sharply, Kane Williamson looks to block but misses and gets hit on the pads.

A peach of a delivery from Stuart Broad! Angles this one in on a length from wider of the crease and into the off pole. The ball straightens beautifully off the deck and just beats the outside edge of Williamson's bat.
Bowls it a bit fuller and around middle, Conway works it away in front of square leg and turns the strike over.
Broad bowls this one around the top of off stump, Devon Conway solidly blocks it out.
Bowls it full and a bit wide outside off, Kane Williamson shoulders arms and leaves the ball alone.

A loud appeal but turned down! Bowls it full and angling back into the batter, Kane Williamson looks to defend but gets beaten by the sharp inward movement. England go up in appeal as the ball catches Williamson on the pads. The umpire shakes his head and England decide not to review.
Full and swinging away outside off by Ollie Robinson, Kane Williamson gets on the front foot and drives it through covers for a couple of runs.
Kane Williamson walks in at number 3.

OUT! CAUGHT! Ollie Robinson strikes in his first over and removes Tom Latham! Bowls it on a length at the batter, Tom Latham looks to turn this one on the leg side but gets an inside edge onto his pad. The ball lobs off the thigh pad in front of short leg. Ollie Pope there reacts quickly and dives forward to complete the catch. This was a clever field placing by Ben Stokes and he has been rewarded with a wicket.
Commentary.Howout: c Ollie Pope b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: Full and swinging in on off, Tom Latham takes a stride forward and defends it down the wicket.
Starts with a full delivery outside off from 'round the wicket, Tom Latham leaves the ball alone.
Ollie Robinson comes in early as first change.
Goes full and on off, Devon Conway gets behind the line and solidly blocks this one out to mid on.
Keeps it on a good length on off, the ball nips back in sharply after pitching, Devon Conway accounts for the movement and shoulders arms.
Good-length delivery outside off, Devon Conway does not reach out to the delivery and lets it go through to the keeper.
Brave leave! Bowls this one full and slanting in just outside off stump, Devon Conway shoulders arms and leaves the ball alone.
Fuller and on off, Devon Conway gets on the front foot and defends this one out.
Full and angling in around off, Devon Conway drives this one a bit uppishly but wide of cover for a couple of runs.
Back of a length on off, Tom Latham dabs this one towards backward point.
Length delivery on middle, Tom Latham works this one straight to mid-wicket.
Goes full and angles it around off from 'round the wicket, Tom Latham gets on the front foot to defend but the ball straightens after pitching and beats him on the outside edge.
Back of a length on off, Devon Conway taps this one on the off side and takes a quick single.

FOUR BYES! Back of a length and angling down the leg side, Devon Conway shuffles across to help this one fine but misses. Ben Foakes behind the wicket misses as well as the ball swings away from him and it goes for a boundary.
Length delivery around off, Tom Latham takes a stride forward and defends it to cover. Opens his account with a single.
Devon Conway and ​​​​New Zealand are finally underway! Stuart Broad pitches this one full but on leg, Devon Conway gets inside the line and works it wide of fine leg for a couple of runs.
On a length outside off, Devon Conway guides this one towards gully.
A stifled appeal but turned down! Full and slanting in on off by Stuart Broad, Devon Conway defends with a straight bat but gets an inside edge back onto his pads.
Fuller and around off by Devon Conway watchfully keeps this one out.
Beauty! Angled in on a length outside off, the ball nips away after pitching, Devon Conway tries to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Bowls this one full and at the stumps from 'round the wicket, Devon Conway gets forward and defends it back to the bowler.
Stuart Broad to operate from the other end.
Length delivery at the stumps, Tom Latham gets behind the line and defends this one out. James Anderson starts with a maiden over.
Angling in on a length outside off, a hint of away movement after pitching, Tom Latham lets it go through to the keeper.
Back of a length and angling in on leg, Tom Latham stays on the back foot and clips it to mid-wicket.
Bowls it on a good length in the channel outside off, Tom Latham shoulders arms and leaves the ball alone.
On a good length around off, Tom Latham gets forward and defends this one on the off side.
Starts with a full delivery angling in on leg from 'round the wicket, Tom Latham gets behind the line and pushes it to mid-wicket.

We are back for the run-chase! The umpires are back out in the middle as the English players take their positions on the field. It will be Tom Latham and Devon Conway to open the batting for New Zealand. And as usual, it will be James Anderson to start off proceedings with the new ball. Let's play...
... FOURTH INNINGS ...

Right then, New Zealand's highest-ever successful run chase in Test cricket came way back in 1994 in Christchurch where they scored 324 runs to win against Pakistan. At the moment, they not only have to get to that score but better it by a big margin as well. England will feel that they have done enough with the bat with useful contributions from the lower middle-order and they are bowled out just as the lights start to take full effect at the Bay Oval. Will the Kiwis be able to ride the early storm under lights and give themselves a chance of a favorable result on Day 4? Or will England get those early breakthroughs and end the day firmly in front? Let's find out as the Kiwi chase is up next.

There it is, New Zealand have finally managed to bundle out England! But, it has required a big effort in the field and the visitors will certainly be happy with what they have on the board. They lead by 393 and the hosts will require a record-breaking score of 394 runs if they are to win this game. England went into the Dinner break with the score on 349/8 and the tailenders have managed to add on crucial 25 runs to that which could make a huge difference. As for New Zealand, Blair Tickner and Michael Bracewell ended up with three wickets each but in all, it was a sub-par effort on their side albeit on a bit of a dead track.

OUT! STUMPED! Michael Bracewell gets his third wicket and brings an end to England's innings! Tossed up nicely, slower and full around off, Jack Leach advances down the track and looks to go down the ground. Gets beaten in the flight and the ball spins past his outside edge. He is in no position to get back in the crease and Tom Blundell behind the wicket does the rest. England end up with a lead of 393 runs.
Commentary.Howout: st Tom Blundell b Michael Bracewell

Commentary.Commentary: Fired in quicker on leg, James Anderson gets into an awkward position but still manages to flick this one through mid-wicket for three runs.
Short and on middle, James Anderson works this one off the back foot to mid-wicket.
Short and on leg, Jack Leach goes back in his crease and pushes it towards square leg for a single.
Flighted, full and drifting at the pads, James Anderson works this one to short fine leg and rotates the strike.
Short of a length angled in off, Jack Leach gets on the back foot and pushes it to the left of Henry Nicholls at silly-point.
Short and on middle by Scott Kuggeleijn, Jack Leach ducks under it.

FOUR! Cracking shot! Persists with the short stuff and bowls it on off, Jack Leach backs away and slaps this one hard towards the vacant deep backward point region for another boundary. England now lead by 388 runs.
A well-directed bumper from 'round the wicket, Jack Leach looks to get on top of the bounce but the ball keeps rising. Fends this one uppishly but wide of short leg.
Banged in short and at the batter, Jack Leach ducks under it and lets it go.
Short of a length angling in on leg, Jack Leach gets inside the line and tucks this one off his hips towards deep backward square leg. Collects a couple of runs more.
Goes short and on off, James Anderson punches it nicely off the back foot but does not manage to beat Kane Williamson at extra cover.
Tossed up, full and around off, James Anderson goes for the conventional sweep this time but misses again.
Touch fuller and turning away outside off, James Anderson goes for the reverse sweep but misses.
Short and quicker around off, James Anderson tries to cut this one late but misses.
Short and around off, James Anderson goes back in his crease and punches it past extra cover and gets off the mark with a couple of runs.
Short and at the stumps, Jack Leach stays on the back foot and clips it through mid-wicket. Henry Nicholls performs the chase and saves a run for his side.
Short of a length on leg, James Anderson moves across and fails to get any bat on the flick.
Switches to over the wicket and directs a short ball at the batter, James Anderson ducks under it and lets it go.
Shorter in length and angled into the batter, James Anderson looks to help this one fine on the leg side but misses. The ball catches him on the thigh pad.
Back of a length on off by Scott Kuggeleijn, James Anderson hangs back and defends it on the off side.
James Anderson is the last man in for England.

OUT! CAUGHT! Scott Kuggeleijn finally gets his man! Goes short again and follows the batter, Ollie Robinson shuffles across to access the leg side but the ball gets big on him. Gets this one off his gloves and the ball lobs towards gully. Henry Nicholls dives in front and completes the catch.
Commentary.Howout: c Henry Nicholls b Scott Kuggeleijn

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Dispatched by Ollie Robinson! Scott Kuggeleijn bangs it in short on middle, Ollie Robinson backs away and flat bats this one through the vacant mid on region for a boundary.
Scott Kuggeleijn to bowl from the other end.
Short and quicker at the stumps, Ollie Robinson goes on the back foot and flicks it to deep square leg for a single.
Short and on off, Ollie Robinson hangs back and pushes it to cover.
Floated, full outside off, Ollie Robinson steps out and shapes to slog but gets deceived by the flight. Can only defend this one down the wicket.
FOUR! Full and outside off by Michael Bracewell, Ollie Robinson gets inside and paddles this one towards fine leg. The ball trickles to the ropes for a boundary.
Tossed up, full around off, Ollie Robinson presses forward to defend but gets it off his front pad. The ball lobs towards leg slip.
Starts with a short delivery, turning in on off, Ollie Robinson gets behind the line and defends it off the back foot.

We are back for the final session on Day 3! The umpires and the Kiwi players are back out in the middle. Ollie Robinson and Jack Leach are set to resume their stay on the crease. Michael Bracewell will continue bowling his off-breaks after the break. Let's play...
... DAY 3, SESSION 3 ...

New Zealand had their tails up after dismissing Joe Root in the final over before the tea break. However, they were unable to get any early breakthrough but did manage to keep runs in check. Michael Bracewell was rewarded for his efforts as he foxed Ben Stokes with a good delivery. Ben Foakes did trouble them but Blair Tickner got rid of him much to the relief of the hosts. However, since that wicket, they have been unable to break this stand between Jack Leach and Ollie Robinson. They will look to reassess their plans during the dinner break and come back to bundle out the visitors. It is all nicely poised in this first Test, so don't go anywhere and join us back at 11.30 am IST (6.00 am GMT) for the third and final session of Day 3.

Session Summary - 27.5 overs, 112 runs and 2 wickets. As both teams head into the dinner break on Day 3, it will be England the happier of the two sides as they have stretched their lead to 368 runs. After tea, Ben Stokes joined Ben Foakes out in the middle, the England skipper took his time initially but started scoring freely once he got his eye in. However, he perished in his quest to up the ante but it was Ben Foakes holding one end for visitors. He was dismissed soon after reaching his fourth fifty of his Test career. Ollie Robinson has shown a lot of composure at the crease and has received able support from Jack Leach at the other end. England have a healthy total on the board but there is still a lot of time left in the game and the visitors will look to bat for as long as possible.

Safely negotiated and that will be the end of the second session on Day 3! Neil Wagner bowls it short on off stump and angles it in. Jack Leach does well to get behind the line and keep it down onto the deck.
Another short one around off and zipping off the deck, Leach leaves it alone.
Short one on the body, Leach looks to work it away but misses and wears it on the body.
On a hard length and angled in from around off, Jack Leach gets right behind it and keeps it out.
Back of a length and around off, Robinson steers it down past backward point for one.
FOUR! Slapped away! Banged in short and around off, Ollie Robinson backs away and flat-bats it through mid off for a boundary.
Tossed up around off, pushed away to cover.
Peach of a delivery! Just a bit quicker and on a nagging length on off stump, this one grips and turns away sharply, Jack Leach gets pushed on the back foot but manages to keep it down.
Leg bye! Shorter and turning onto the pads, Ollie Robinson looks to flick but misses and the ball goes off the pads behind square leg. They get a leg bye.
Slows it up and bowls it a bit shorter on off, blocked out.
Faltter one, around off, kept out by Robinson.
On a length and turning into the stumps, Ollie Robinson blocks it out.
Banged in short and over the stumps, Leach ducks under it.

In the air...just out of reach! Neil Wagner gets this short ball right on the money as he bowls it over off stump. Jack Leach hops on the back foot but gets into an awkward position as he sticks out his bat. The ball takes the shoulder of the bat and goes off Leach's shoulder as well before looping up square of the stumps. Tim Southee from silly point scampers to get to it but isn't able to.
Bowled on a hard length and over off, Jack Leach hops and keeps it down.
Another bumper angled down leg, Leach ducks under it but the ball stay really low and dies on its way to the keeper.
Banged in short and Leach moves out of the way.
Back of a length and around the hops, tucked away 'round the corner for a single.
Neil Wagner (11-0-104-2) comes back on.
Flighted delivery, full on off, Jack Leach presses forward to defend but gets it from the upper part of the bat.
Short and flatter on off, Jack Leach stays on the back foot and defends it onto the off side.
Flights it up now on the stumps, Leach makes another block.
Flatter one on the pads, Leach works it off the back foot onto the leg side.
Loops it up now around off, blocked out.

Oh, my! What happened here? Michael Bracewell looks to toss it up but serves a friendly full toss on leg stump. Ollie Robinson doesn't pick it up and just looks to work it away, ends up getting a top edge. Luckily, for him the ball loops over the head of Kane Williamson at short mid-wicket and they get a single.
Excellent short ball, dug in short at over 140 clicks and over middle as well. Jack Leach does well to duck under it.
Bowled from around the wicket and bowled fuller on the pads, Jack Leach clips it to the left of the man at short leg for a couple of runs. Leach is finally underway.
Good length angled onto the pads, this is tucked away down to fine leg for a single.
Pitches it up now around the off stump, Robinson keeps it out.
Another solid bumper over middle and leg, Robinson ducks under it well.
A short ball around off and shooting off the deck, Robinson sways his head out of the way.
Tosses it up now around off, Leach keeps it out.
Fuller and on off, pushed away toward mid on.
Flighted delivery, on a length and around off, Jack Leach attempts the reverse sweep but misses and gets hit on the pads.
Flatter one around off, tapped away in front of cover-point.
Nicely looped up outside off and turning away, Jack Leach makes a watchful leave.
Slower and shorter around off, Ollie Robinson waits on the back foot and wrists it away behind square on the leg side for one.
Blair Tickner bends his back a bit more and digs in a short one over leg stump, Leach ducks under it well.
Very full and angled across the off stump, Jack Leach eases it toward cover-point.
Short of a length and over off stump, Leach keeps it down on the deck.
Short one, around the leg stump and Jack Leach makes an awkward leave.
Good length outside off, played down with soft hands toward third man for a single.
Hits the length hard and bowls it on off stump, Ollie Robinson backs away and looks to slap it away but misses.
Loops it up now, nice and full outside off, teasing the batter but Leach leaves it alone.
Oh, thats a brave shot from Leach! Tossed up full and on off stump, Leach turns around for the reverse sweep and goes hard at it but gets it nowhere.
On a nagging length and on off stump, Jack Leach goes deep in his crease to block it out.
Turning it onto the pads, Robinson sits down and slogs it away behind square on the leg side for a single.
Flighted delivery, on a length and turning in from outside off, Robinson stays solid in defense.
Ollie Robinson early and Michael Bracewell pulls the length back considerably. Bracewell blocks it out.
Comes from around the wicket and bangs on in around the rib cage, Jack Leach hosp and keeps it down on the leg side.
Jack Leach comes out to bat.

OUT! CAUGHT! FIFTY AND OUT for Ben Foakes! This is a gem of a delivery from Blair Tickner though and he deserves that wicket. Tickner bowls this one on a hard length and on a tight line around off, angling it in. The ball just straightens off the deck and catches the outside edge as Foakes looks to make the block. Tom Blundell behind the sticks make no mistake and England are now eight down with a lead of 354 runs.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Blundell b Blair Tickner

Commentary.Commentary: Pulled away and that will be Tes match half-century number 4 for Ben Foakes, an impressive knock from him. This is banged in short and over middle, Foakes gets on top of the bounce and pulls it in front of the man at deep square leg for a couple.

Halt! Ollie Robinson is experiencing some discomfort in his left knee and requires medical attention. The umpires are unhappy with the ball and have called for a replacement as Robinson continues to receive treatment. He is back on his feet and play will resume now.
On a hard length and over the stumps, Foakes keeps it out off the back foot.
Goes a bit wider of the crease and bowls it full and into middle and leg. Foakes keeps it out.
Back of a length around off, Ben Foakes hops back and works it away through the mid-wicket region for a couple of runs. Foakes moves to 49 now.
Blair Tickner (9-0-47-2) comes back into the attack.
Flatter delivery on off stump, Ollie Robinson keeps it out.
Short again around off and turning in a bit sharply as well, Foakes gets on the back foot and forces it through mid on for one more. England stretch their lead to 350 now.
A fraction shorter and around off, nudged out by Foakes.
Tossed up around off, Robinson gets down on one knee and plays the conventional sweep this time through square leg for a run.
FOUR! Played to perfection! Full again and around middle, Ollie Robinson gets into position early and reverse sweeps it past the man at first slip for a boundary.
This is bowled full and on off, Foakes steps down the track and plays it through mid on for one.
Angles this one on a length and around the pads, Foakes works it away past square leg for a single.
Pitches it a bit further up and on off stump, Foakes hangs back and defends it out.
Good length again, around middle and leg, blocked out.

Good length over off stump, Ben Foakes with a punch right back past the bowler and the fielders from mid off and mid on chase it down. Scott Kuggeleijn from mid on cuts it off and keeps it down to a couple.
Short again over off stump, Ollie Robinson pulls it in front of his face and controls it down to deep mid-wicket for one more.
This is banged in short and over leg stump, Foakes keeps the pull shot down and gets it to fine leg for a run.
On off stump, kept out by Robinson.
Fullish length around off, Ollie Robinson pushes at it and edges it down toward point.
Floated up on off stump, Foakes steps out and flicks it through wide mid on for one.
Shorter one around off, turning into the right-hander. Ben Foakes stays back and dabs it down toward square leg.
On off stump and sliding on, Foakes plays it off the front foot and just wide of short leg.
Tossed up full and around off, Foakes eases it toward mid on.
Good length around the top of off, Robinson stays solid in defense.
Back of a length and over middle, this one climbs on the batter but Robinson manages to keep it down onto the deck.
Full and straight, punched off the front foot to mid on.
Length again around off, stroked through the cover region for a single.
Pitched up around off, Foakes gets on the front foot and blocks it out.
Short and angled well down leg, Ben Foakes looks to pull it away but misses.
Nagging length around off and turning in, Ollie Robinson blocks it out from inside his crease.
A tad short and wide, Robinson backs away and misses out on the cut as he gets an inside edge that goes past the off stump.
Nagging length, pushed through a bit quicker and around off, Ollie Robinson gets on the back foot to defend.
A bit flatter and around middle, kept out by Robinson.
FOUR! NIcely done! Shorter and turning in from around off, Ollie Robinson shuffles across and whips it behind square leg for a boundary.
Nicely tossed up on a shorter length and outside off, turning in, Ollie Robinson keeps it down in front of short leg.
Goes full on off and tries to swing it away, Foakes defends it back to the bowler.
A length ball on leg stump, Ollie Robinson tucks it away in front of square on the leg side for a single.
Fuller in length and around off, Foakes pushes it toward wide mid off and scampers across for the single.
Pitched up just a bit wider of the off stump, Foakes gets forward and punches it out to cover.
Fullish length in that channel around off and this is kept out off the front foot.
Tim Southee comes back into the attack and starts with a pitched-up delivery on off stump, Ben Foakes pushes it straight back to mid off.

Michael Bracewell bowls this one full and on middle, Ollie Robinson presses forward to defend but gets beaten on the inside edge and gets rapped on the front pad. A loud shout but it is turned down by the umpire. New Zealand go upstairs for a review but the UltraEdge shows a spike as the ball is next to the bat. The on-field decision stands and New Zealand lose their review.
Short and quicker at the stumps, Ollie Robinson goes back and pushes it to mid on.
Slower and full, turning into the batter, Ollie Robinson gets behind the line and keeps this one out.
Tossed up, full on off, Ben Foakes steps out and flicks it towards mid on for a single.
Flighted, full around off, Ollie Robinson goes for the reverse sweep again and gets this one past first slip. Three runs taken.
FOUR! Michael Bracewell misses his length and fires in a low full toss at the stumps, Ollie Robinson pulls out the reverse sweep and gets it through backward point for a boundary.

FOUR! Easy pickings! Scott Kuggeleijn bowls this one short of a length but down the leg side, Ben Foakes gets inside the line and uses the angle to his advantage. Helps it to the right of the fine leg fielder and picks up a boundary.

Drinks break! Ben Foakes has been dealt with a blow on the forearm and is in some pain. The physio comes out to have a look and the umpires also call for drinks. England have managed to stretch the lead to 318 runs but are 7 wickets down and with plenty of time still remaining in the game, they will look to bat the whole of the second session on Day 3 and then some. New Zealand on the other hand will look to clean up the tail and come out to bat while the sun is still shining. An interesting phase of play awaits.
Short and aimed at the batter, Ben Foakes gets across to pull it on the leg side but gets rapped on the gloves. Takes his glove off and calls for the physio.
Back of a length around off by Scott Kuggeleijn, Ollie Robinson hangs back and pushes it to cover for a single.
Goes short this time at the batter, Ben Foakes swivels and pulls it to deep backward square leg for a single.

FOUR! Nicely played! Scott Kuggeleijn bowls this one slower and full on middle and leg, Ben Foakes waits for it and drives this one along the ground. Gets it wide of mid on and the ball races away for a boundary.
Full but down the leg side from 'round the wicket, Ben Foakes goes for the flick but misses.
Ollie Robinson is the new man in.

OUT! STUMPED! A huge wicket for New Zealand! Michael Bracewell floats this one nicely, fuller and outside off, Ben Stokes gets tempted by the flight and advances down the track to go down the ground. Swings his bat but gets beaten in the flight and the ball spins past his outside edge. Tom Blundell behind the wicket collects it cleanly and does the rest. Michael Bracewell is delighted and so he should be.
Commentary.Howout: st Tom Blundell b Michael Bracewell

Commentary.Commentary: Short and flatter on leg, Ben Foakes works it off the back foot to backward square leg for a single.
Short and at the stumps, Ben Foakes works it straight to short leg where Tom Latham makes a good stop.
Short and on off, Ben Stokes punches it wide of long off for a single.
Tossed up, slower and full around off, Ben Stokes presses forward and smothers the ball on the off side.
FOUR! Michael Bracewell bowls this one a bit too full on off, Ben Stokes steps out and gets to the ball in flash. Uses his bottom hand and drills it past mid off for a boundary.
Back of a length and angling on leg, Ben Foakes stays on the back foot and works it straight to short fine leg.
Shortens his length and bowls it on off, Ben Stokes hangs back and dabs it past backward point for a single. 50-run stand comes up Ben Stokes and Ben Foakes.

Good running! Scott Kuggeleijn bowls a full toss outside off, Ben Stokes shimmies down the track and reaches out to the delivery. Drives it wide of deep point which allows him to come back for the second with relative ease.

The New Zealand players feel that the ball has taken a bit too much hammering and want it changed. The umpire puts it through the gauge test and gives it back to Tim Southee to get the play restarted.
WIDE! Persists with the short stuff but this time goes too short and the ball sails over the head of Ben Stokes.
Short and again down the leg side, Ben Foakes rises and pulls it down to fine leg for a single.
FOUR! Short of a length on leg, Ben Foakes gets on top of the bounce and pulls it well wide of fine leg and the fast outfield does the rest. The lead goes past 300 now.
Banged in short at the batter from 'round the wicket, Ben Foakes rolls his wrists and pulls this one but fails to get it past Kane Williamson at backward square leg.

A huge appeal for lbw but it is turned down! This is bowled flatter from around the stumps and angling it in from outside off. Stokes gets a big stride across as he looks to sweep it fine but seems to have missed it and gets hit on the pads. No review was taken by New Zealand and the replays show that there might have been an inside edge.
Floated up around off, Ben Stokes defends it off the front foot.
Flighted delivery around off, Foakes advances and pushes it to the left of mid on for a quick single.
FOUR! Good shot! Tossed up outside off and turning in, Ben Foakes uses his feet and whips it over the mid-wicket region for a boundary.
Bowls it shorter and turns it in from outside off, Foakes defends it down the pitch.
Tossed up on a length and turning into middle, Ben Foakes pushes it uppishly but well in front of short leg.
A good bouncer now bowled from over the stumps and angled across the batter. Stokes looks to upper cut it but misses.
Short and around off, dabbed down to the right of backward point.

SIX! Oh, no! Neil Wagner has made a mess of that one. Banged in short and over leg stump, Ben Stokes goes for the pull but hits it straight around the face of Wagner who is stationed right on the fine leg fence. Wagner grabs it with both hands but fails to keep his balance and falls over the ropes, resulting in another maximum.

SIX! All the way! Short again and angling down leg, but just not short enough. Ben Stokes pulls it over the fine leg fence and there's a huge roar from the crowd as Stokes becomes the player to hit the most number os maximums in Test matches. Phenomenal achievement! And guess who he overtakes? Former Kiwi batter and now England's coach Brendon McCullum.
A bumper now around leg stump and angling further down, Ben Stokes just walks across the off stump and leaves it alone.
Bowled short from around the wicket and around leg stump, Foakes gets inside the line and pulls it down to fine leg for one.
