Full and outside off, Ben Stokes accounts for the away turn and leaves the ball alone.
Flighted, full and turning away outside off, Ben Stokes gets down to slog sweep but does not connect.
Short and angling in at the pads, Ben Foakes flicks it to mid-wicket for a single.
Fuller on middle, Ben Foakes defends it down the wicket.
Short and at the stumps, Ben Stokes stays on the back foot and knocks it down to long on for a single.
Short and quicker around off, Ben Stokes goes back in his crease to cut but misses.
Goes full and on middle, Ben Foakes pushes it back to the bowler for a dot.
WIDE! Banged in short by Scott Kuggeleijn, Ben Foakes ducks under it and lets it go. The ball sails over the batter's head and it is signalled as wide.

FOUR! A wayward delivery by Scott Kuggeleijn, low full toss at the pads, Ben Foakes tries to help this one fine on the leg side. Tries to work it fine but it comes off his back leg and it races away to the ropes for a boundary. However, the umpire thinks it has come off Ben Foakes' bat.
Goes full and straight at the stumps, Ben Foakes gets behind the line and defends it back to the bowler.
Good bumper! Scott Kuggeleijn bangs this one short and at the batter, Ben Foakes gets inside the line and ducks under the delivery.
Scott Kuggeleijn misses his line and length and bowls a low full toss down the leg side, Ben Foakes goes for the flick but misses.
Back of a length on off from 'round the wicket, Ben Stokes hangs back and taps it towards cover for a single.
Short and turning in on middle, Ben Foakes gets across and works it to short leg.
Full and drifting in on middle, Ben Stokes uses his feet and pushes it to mid off for a quick single.
Short and outside off, Ben Foakes pushes this one off the back foot to point for a single.
Short and flatter outside off, the ball keeps a bit low but Ben Foakes manages to keep this one out.
Full and darted on off, Ben Foakes takes a stride forward and defends it to cover.
Full and quicker outside off, Ben Foakes gets forward and smothers the ball on the off side.

FOUR! Back-to-back boundaries for Ben Stokes! Scott Kuggeleijn bowls this one on a length on middle, Ben Stokes shimmies down the track and opens the bat face to guide it past backward point for yet another boundary.

FOUR! Nicely played! Short and aimed at the batter by Scott Kuggeleijn, Ben Stokes swivels in his crease and plays a controlled pull shot. Gets it towards deep backward square leg and opens his account with a boundary.
Fuller and slanting away outside off, Ben Stokes shoulders arms and lets it go.
On a length angling across on off, Ben Stokes hangs back and defends it on the off side.
Banged in short and outside off, Ben Foakes gets on top of the bounce and pulls it along the ground to deep square leg for a single.
Full and around off by Scott Kuggeleijn, Ben Foakes gets behind the line and defends it down the wicket.
Floated, full on middle, Ben Stokes takes a stride forward and defends this one back to the bowler.
Goes full and on middle, Ben Stokes presses forward and blocks this one out.
Short and flatter on middle, Ben Stokes goes back in his crease and defends it on the off side.
Full and drifting in on middle, Ben Stokes can only push this one to extra cover.
Flighted, full and turning in on leg, Ben Foakes steps out and helps this one towards fine leg for three runs.
Tossed up, full at the pads, Ben Foakes works this one to mid-wicket.
Length delivery angling across outside off, Ben Stokes dabs this one from the crease to backward point.
Slower and full on leg, Ben Foakes waits for it and clips it to deep square leg for a single.
On a good length around off, Ben Foakes gets behind the line and defends it down the wicket.
Back of a length on middle, Ben Foakes hangs back and whips this one to mid-wicket.
Banged in short and outside off by Scott Kuggeleijn, Ben Foakes sways away and leaves the ball alone.
Goes full and at the stumps, Ben Foakes drives this one to mid on.
Scott Kuggeleijn will bowl from the other end.
Full and around off, Ben Stokes gets forward and smothers the ball on the off side.
Short and outside off, Ben Stokes goes back and punches it to cover.
Full and turning away outside off, Ben Stokes leaves the ball alone.
Full again around off, Ben Stokes gets forward and defends it on the off side.
Full and at the stumps, Ben Stokes keeps it out.
We are back for the post-tea session on Day 3. Ben Stokes and Ben Foakes make their way out in the middle. Michael Bracewell will resume his over in the second session. Here we go...
... DAY 3, SESSION 2 ...

New Zealand came out with a clear game plan and went straightaway with the short ball tactic. Neil Wagner led the way for them and was rewarded with the wicket of Stuart Broad in his second over. He was taken for 36 in his four overs after that wicket but a change of ends paid dividends for him. He dismissed Ollie Pope to hand New Zealand a much-needed breakthrough. It was then Blair Tickner who struck to remove Harry Brook who was threatening to take the game away from them. In the last over before tea, Michael Bracewell got rid of Joe Root to put New Zealand right back in the game. The game hangs in the balance at the moment and it promises to be another intriguing session of cricket. Do join us back at 8.50 am IST (3.20 am GMT) for the second session of Day 3.

Session Summary - 25.1 overs, 158 runs and 3 wickets. What an entertaining first session we have had here. One would feel that the wicket of Joe Root in the final over has titled the balance in New Zealand's favour. England began the day with the lead of 98 runs and were dealt an early blow losing Stuart Broad in the third over of the day. Joe Root had a nervy start to his innings but grew in confidence as he progressed. He and Ollie Pope took their chances against the short ball barrage by New Zealand and it came off. Ollie Pope fell one short of the fifty-run mark but Joe Root and Harry Brook got together notching up their respective fifties. The latter perished shortly after completing his fifty and the dismissal of Joe Root just before Tea has pegged England back a bit.

OUT! CAUGHT! Joe Root is gone in the final over before tea! Michael Bracewell bowls this one full and outside off, Joe Root pulls out the reverse sweep but gets a glove on it. The ball takes the glove of Tom Blundell behind the wicket and lobs to Daryl Mitchell at first slip who does the rest. Joe Root is distraught as he was looking so good out in the middle. That will be Tea on Day 3!
Commentary.Howout: c Daryl Mitchell b Michael Bracewell

Commentary.Commentary: Banged in short at the batter by Blair Tickner, Ben Foakes ducks under it and lets it go through to the keeper.
Fuller in length outside off, Joe Root presses forward and guides it towards backward point for a single.
Full and on middle and leg, Joe Root gets into the positon early and clips it off his toes. Gets it wide of deep square leg which allows him to complete the second run with ease.
Full and angling down the leg side, Ben Foakes gets inside the line and works it to fine leg for a run.
Back of a length in the channel outside off, Ben Foakes hangs back and dabs it to point.
Short and outside off, Joe Root swivels in his crease and drags this one to deep square leg for a single.
Floated, full outside off by Michael Bracewell, Ben Foakes drives it along the ground to mid on.
Full and quicker on middle, Ben Foakes gets behind the line and turns this one to mid-wicket.
Short and at the stumps, Ben Foakes stays back and works it to mid-wicket.
Tossed up, full outside off, Ben Foakes gets across and pushes it to mid-wicket.
Full on off, Ben Foakes gets forward and smothers the ball on the off side.
Flighted, full outside off, Ben Foakes steps out and flicks this one uppishly towards deep square leg for a couple of runs.
Back of a length and angling in on middle, Joe Root stays on the back foot and defends it on the off side.
Full and on middle and leg, Ben Foakes clips this one wide of Kane Williamson at mid on and takes a single.
Short and aimed at the batter, Ben Foakes ducks under the delivery and leaves the ball alone.
Goes full this time and at the stumps, Ben Foakes gets behind the line and pushes it back to the bowler.
Fraction short and outside off, Joe Root hangs back and dabs it to deep backward point for a single.
On a good length outside off, Joe Root takes a stride forward to defend but gets it from the outer part of the bat towards gully.
Full around off by Michael Bracewell, Ben Foakes gets forward and keeps it out.
Floated, full on off, Joe Root gets down and sweeps it to deep backward square leg for a single.
Short and quicker at the stumps, Ben Foakes works this one off his hips to deep backward square leg. Opens his account with a single.
Flighted delivery, full outside off, Ben Foakes takes a big stride forward to defend but gets rapped on the front pad.
Short and turning into the batter, Joe Root goes back and turns it towards backward square leg for a single.
Slower and short, turning in on off, Joe Root smothers the ball down the wicket.
On a length around off, Ben Foakes solidly defends on the off side.
Blair Tickner welcomes Ben Foakes with a bumper! Bowls it short and at the batter, Ben Foakes ducks under it and lets it go through to the keeper.
Who comes next?

OUT! CAUGHT! Blair Tickner finally gets his man and removes Harry Brook! Bowls this one on a good length in the channel outside off, Harry Brook is neither forward nor back and pokes at the delivery. The ball catches the outside edge and it travels first slip. Daryl Mitchell reacts quickly and gets low to his left. Takes a sharp catch to bring an end to a fine knock by Harry Brook. This is a much-needed breakthrough for New Zealand.
Commentary.Howout: c Daryl Mitchell b Blair Tickner

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Short and just outside off, Harry Brook hangs back and cuts this one late. Gets it past gully and the ball races away to the fence.
Full and slanting into the batter, Harry Brook drives it along the ground to mid on.
Short of a length on off, Harry Brook dabs this one off the back foot towards gully.

FIFTY for Harry Brook! Short and turning into the batter, Harry Brook goes on the back foot and pushes it down to long on. Takes a single to bring up his fifty. This has been fearless batting by the right-handed batter.
Floated, full on off, Harry Brook pushes it back to the bowler.

FIFTY for Joe Root! Bracewell misses his length and bowls a low full toss on off, Joe Root reverse paddles this one towards third man. Kane Williamson runs around and saves a run for his side. This has been a resilient fifty by Joe Root and these are ominous signs for New Zealand.
Full and at the stumps, Harry Brook knocks it down to long on for a single.
Short and on off by Michael Bracewell, Harry Brook goes back in his crease and punches it wide of cover for a couple of runs.
Michael Bracewell starts with a flighted delivery, fuller around off, Harry Brook steps out to go through the off side but mishits it to mid-wicket.
Michael Bracewell is introduced into the attack.
Strays on the pads, fuller in length, Harry Brook clips it off his toes and flicks it to fine leg for a single.
Short of a length on off, Harry Brook steers this one on the bounce towards gully.
Goes into the wicket again and on middle, Harry Brook gets on top of the bounce and defends it on the leg side.
Short of a length angling into the batter, Joe Root nudges this one to backward square leg for a single.
Shorter in length on middle, Joe Root hangs back and keeps this one out.

Blair Tickner bowls this one on a good length but angling on leg, Joe Root gets across to flick this one on the leg side but misses and gets hit on the front pad. New Zealand go up in unison but the umpire shakes his head. After a deliberation, Tim Southee sends it upstairs for a review. The UltraEdge shows no bat but it is missing the stumps on Ball Tracking. The onfield decision stands and New Zealand lose their review.
Short but down the leg side, Harry Brook lets it go through to the keeper.

SIX! Neil Wagner persists with short length and on middle and leg, Harry Brook backs away and flat bats this one towards long on. Gets it from the middle part of the ball and clears the ropes for a maximum.
FOUR! Make that three in a row! Neil Wagner goes short and at the batter, Harry Brook moves to the leg side again and drills this one in tennis style wide of mid off or a boundary.

FOUR! Short again on middle by Neil Wagner, Harry Brook does not get on top of the bounce and pulls this one high in the air towards deep square leg. Devon Conway stationed there goes for the catch and puts in the dive. The ball falls just short of him and it trickles into the fence.
FOUR! Keeps it short and at the batter, Harry Brook backs away and flat bats this one through the vacant mid off region for a boundary.
Ouch, that must have hurt! Neil Wagner bowls it short and at the batter, Harry Brook gets into his shot early as he tried to pull. Fails to connect and the ball catches him near the ribs.
Full on off, Joe Root gets on the front foot and drives it to mid off.

FOUR! Streaky but they all count! Blair Tickner bowls it on a length around off, Joe Root tries to work it on the off side but gets an inside edge that rolls past the keeper for a boundary. 50-run stand comes up between Joe Root and Harry Brook.
Keeps it full and around off, Joe Root presses forward and drives it nicely but fails to get it past Michael Bracewell at short cover.
Goes short again and outside off, Joe Root does not reach out to the delivery and leaves the ball alone.
FOUR! Short and wide outside off by Blair Tickner, Joe Root stands tall and cuts this one through point. Gets it well wide of deep backward point and the fast outfield does the rest.
Starts with a short-of-a-length delivery around off, Joe Root gets on his toes and guides it towards gully.
Blair Tickner comes on to bowl, replacing Scott Kuggeleijn.
Short and on middle by Neil Wagner, Harry Brook pulls it hard but straight to square leg.
Sees the batter shuffle and bowls it on a length at him, Harry Brook moves out of the line and leaves the ball alone.
Short again on leg, Joe Root gets inside the line and pulls it wide of short fine leg for a single.
Short and angling across on off, Joe Root sways away and lets it go through to the keeper.
Short and aimed at the batter, Joe Root gets into a good position and pulls it to the right of deep square leg for a brace.
Short but down the leg side from over the wicket, Joe Root pulls it along the ground but fails to get it past short fine leg.
Full and at the stumps, Harry Brook blocks this one out off the front foot.
Bowls this one short and on off, Harry Brook rides on top of the bounce towards deep mid-wicket and collects a couple of runs.
On a length on middle, Harry Brook gets behind the line and works it to mid-wicket.
FOUR! Beautiful shot! Scott Kuggeleijn goes full this time and bowls it outside off, Harry Brook picks the length early and leans into the drive. Gets it to the left of mid off for a boundary.
Short of a length at the batter by Scott Kuggeleijn, Joe Root works this one off the back foot to deep square leg for a single.
FOUR! Short and angling in on leg, Joe Root gets on top of the bounce and rolls his wrists. Pulls this one towards fine leg for a boundary. The runs keep coming for England.

FOUR! Neil Wagner persists with short length and on middle, Harry Brook moves to the leg side and has all the time in the world to get into a position. Flat bats this one through the vacant mid on region for a boundary.
Short and down the leg side, Joe Root gets inside the line and helps it to fine leg for a single.
Short and around the left shoulder of the batter, Harry Brook does not control his pull shot and hits it uppishly but wide of backward square leg for a single.
SIX! Short and dispatched by Harry Brook! Goes short again and on middle, Harry Brook backs away and flat bats this one towards the long on fence. Gets enough bat on it and collects a maximum.
Short and at the batter, Harry Brook swivels in his crease and pulls it straight to backward square leg.
FOUR! Neil Wagner looks to go short again but the ball does not rise, Harry Brook gets into the position early and pulls it towards deep backward square leg for a boundary.

DRINKS! Despite losing two wickets in the first hour, England's lead has raced to 175 runs. They are going along at a crisp pace and this pair needs to carry on. On the other hand, New Zealand will be relieved to see the back of Ollie Pope but need to look for wickets and at the same time, keep the runs in check.
Short of a length outside off, Harry Brook dabs this one off the back foot to backward point.
Keeps it on a good length around off, Joe Root stays back and taps it to cover for a quick single.
Back of a length on middle and leg, Harry Brook hangs back and turns this one to square leg for a single.
Length delivery on off by Scott Kuggeleijn, Joe Root presses forward and defends it to cover for a single.
On a good length outside off, Joe Root goes back in his crease to defend but gets it from the outer part of the bat towards gully.
Good-length delivery around off, Harry Brook pushes this one wide of mid on and takes a single.
Banged in short at the batter by Neil Wagner, Joe Root shapes to take it on but lets it go through to the keeper.

Not far away! Short of a length over middle and leg, Harry Brook nails the pull shot but hits it flat and just over the leaping fielder at square leg for a single. Tom Blundell there reacted quickly and flew to his left but couldn't get a hand on it.
Short of a length around leg stump, Harry Brook gets on top of the bounce and pulls it to the right of the man at deep square leg for a couple of runs.
Another slower bumper over leg stump and this one sticks in the surface a bit. Joe Root goes for the pull but mistimes it a bit uppishly down to fine leg for one more.
BYE! A slower short ball this angled well across the right-hander and the ball just keeps on angling away, beating the diving keeper and going toward third man. They pick up a bye.
Shorter and around the hips, Root pulls it down to fine leg for a single.
Back of a length around off, Brook blocks it out.

This is excellent bowling from Scott Kuggeleijn and Harry Brook is lucky not to have edged that. Good length on the fifth stump line and angled in. This one leaves the batter a bit after pitching and Brook has a little nibble at it but gets beaten just past the outside edge.
Scott Kuggeleijn grunts and bangs in another bumper over the stumps, Brook is able to duck under it though.
Pitches it further up now around off and at 141 clicks. Harry Brook is caught on the back foot as he looks to drive and gets an outside edge that lands just in front of the gully fielder.
Scott Kuggeleijn bowls a solid bumper now at almost 140 clicks and over off stump. This one flies off the deck and Harry Brook ducks under it.
Short of a length around leg stump and at 141.5 clicks. Root plays a controlled pull shot down to deep backward square leg for one.
Banged in short and over leg stump, Harry Brook pulls it hard but straight to the man at deepish square leg.
Harry Brook is the new man in.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Neil Wagner has the last laugh here and seems to have gotten rid of Ollie Pope but the umpires have gone upstairs to check for a fair catch and the soft signal is out. The third umpire checks it a couple of times and is satisfied with the catch. Coming to the delivery, Wagner bangs it in short and over leg stump but it is a bit slower. Pope looks to shuffle a bit and pull it behind square but only manages to get a glove on it. The ball loops up a bit and goes to the right of the keeper. Tom Blundell dives forward to that side and pouches it safely. Wagner is ecstatic and Pope departs on 49.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Blundell b Neil Wagner

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Ollie Pope is in overdrive here. This is dug in even shorter by Wagner and over off stump. Pope gives himself a bit of room and slaps it tennis-style over mid on for a boundary.
FOUR! That has been spanked away! Short and outside off, sitting up nicely for the batter, Ollie Pope backs away and hits it hard well in front of square on the off side for a boundary.
Slower and shorter over leg stump, Joe Root plays a controlled pull shot down to deep backward square leg for one.
This is short and at the body, jabbed away down to deep square leg for a single.
Change of ends for Neil Wagner.
Back of a length outside off, Root hops on the back foot and dabs it down towards the gully region.
Short again and there's width on offer, Ollie Pope salps it off the back foot and in front of point for yet another single.
Short and outside off, tapped away off the back foot through the point region for one more.
On middle, Pope comes forward and flicks it leg side for a single. The 50-run stand between these two is up as well.
Top delivery! On a hard length, angled in from wider of the crease and into off stump. Ollie Pope looks to block but the ball straightens and zips past the outside edge.
Scott Kuggeleijn comes back into the attack and starts off with a back-of-a-length delivery on the body. This is tucked away 'round the corner for one and the lead is now worth 150 runs.
This is full and outside off, Pope leaves it alone.
Pitched up around off, Joe Root punches it to the right of the diving man at short extra cover for a quick single.
Full and around off, shaping away, Root drives it straight to the man at short extra cover.
Good length around off and just angling in a bit, Root gets on the front foot and blocks it out.
Fuller and at the stumps, Pope advances and whips it away through mid-wicket for a single.
On a good length outside off and shaping away a touch, left alone for the keeper to collect.
Back to over the wicket now and dug in over leg stump, Pope pulls it to deep mid-wicket for one.

SIX! All the way again and England are quickly extending their lead here. Wagner comes from 'round the wicket and bangs it in shorter just over head height as well. Ollie Pope still takes it on and pulls it over the fine leg fence yet again for a maximum.
Slower one, around the hips, this is nudged down to fine leg for one.

SIX! A third maximum in the same region and this time it's off the bat of Joe Root. Neil Wagner bangs in a bumper across middle and Root is able to get across the stumps and pull it over the man at fine leg for a biggie.
Back of a length and outside off, tapped away off the back foot and to deep point for an easy single.
Shorter in length and over middle and leg, Joe Root pulls it along the ground past square leg for a run.
Good length outside off and shooting of the deck a bit. Ollie Pope advances but leaves it alone.
Shorter and outside off, Root plays it late and dabs it down wide of the gully fielder who gets a hand on it. They pick up a single.
FOUR! Pitched up around off stump, Joe Root shimmies across the wicket and works it sweetly through wide mid on and the ball runs away into the fence.
Southee keeps the length a bit full and swings it away from the fourth stump line, Joe Root makes yet another leave.
And again! Bowled wide of the off stump and swinging it away from the right-hander, Root shoulders arms.
On a length on the fifth stump line and shaping away, Root leaves it alone for the keeper to collect.
Keeps it short and around leg, Root pulls it down behind square leg for a run.
Uppish but in the gap! Banged in over leg stump, Pope takes it on and pulls it a bit uppishly in front of the diving man at mid-wicket for a single.
SIX! WOW! Short ball over middle and leg and angling across. Ollie Pope shuffles across and gets inside the line once again before pulling it onto the grass banks over the fine leg fence.
Around the hips, this is pulled down to fine leg for one more.
This is banged in even shorter and outside off, Ollie Pope backs away and upper cuts it wide of the man at third man for a single.
SIX! Aggressive shot from Ollie Pope! Banged in around the leg stump, Pope gets inside the line of the ball and muscles it away over the fine leg fence for a maximum.
Beaten! Tim Southee bowls this a bit wider of the off stump and brings the ball back into the right-hander. Joe Root looks to drive away from the body but is beaten on the inside edge.
Pitches up outside off and swinging away, Root leaves it alone.
Bowls it a touch fuller and on off, Root looks to defend off the front foot but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Good length again around off, Root blocks it out.
FOUR! Close but not close enough! Good length around the top of off, Joe Root pushes at it and gets an inside edge that goes past the stumps and runs away into the fine leg fence. A lucky boundary!
FOUR LEG BYES! This is fuller and on the pads, looking to swing it away but this one slides right on. Joe Root looks to flick but the ball just tickles the pads and runs away into the fine leg fence.
Shorter and on the body, pulled down toward fine leg for a single.
Oh, Joe Root has completely mistimed that! Banged in short and around leg stump, cramping Root for room as he tries to pull and almost miscues it straight toward square leg.
Short and on leg stump, pulled away toward square leg.

Now a loose shot from Joe Root. Shortish length, down the leg side yet again, Root looks to pull it fine but the ball just sneaks under the bat. There is half an appeal for caught behind but nothing doing.
A bit of a loosener as Wagner bowls this short and well down the leg side. Joe Root leaves it alone.
Joe Root comes in at number 5.

OUT! CAUGHT! That's what Neil Wagner does best! Wagner comes from over the wicket and bangs in a nasty bouncer over middle and leg. The ball shoots off the deck and comes in at an awkward height and Stuart Broad gets all cramped up. Broad hops back and turns his head away as he tries to fend it away. The ball takes the handle of the bat and lobs up around the gully region where Henry Nicholls takes a simple catch. The 'Nighthawk' is gone and New Zealand have an early breakthrough on Day 3.
Commentary.Howout: c Henry Nicholls b Neil Wagner

Commentary.Commentary: Tim Southee starts the day with a maiden! Good length on the fifth stump line, Pope comes forward but ends up just leaving the delivery.
Full and outside off, shaping away, Ollie Pope shimmies down the pitch looking to cover drive but mistimes it completely toward mid off.
On a length and outside off, Ollie Pope shoulders arms at it.
Keeps the length a bit fuller and angles it into middle, Pope defends it out.
Pitches it up now and brings the ball much closer to the off pole, Pope makes a solid block off the front foot.
This is full and wide of the off stump, just a hint of away movement there. Pope leaves it alone.
It will be Tim Southee to operate from the other end.
Keeps the length short and bowls it around the hips, pulled down to fine leg for a run.
Good bouncer this, over middle and leg and zipping through. Ollie Pope ducks under it well.
This is short around leg stump and coming in at an awkward height. Pope looks to pull it behind square but mistimes it to the right of the man at backward square leg.
A bumper now, spilled down the leg side and Ollie Pope ducks under it with ease.
Wagner bangs this one in around off stump, Broad gets pushed onto the back foot and edges it down to third man for a single. England now lead by 100 runs!
Short again and aimed at the body, Broad gets on the back foot and keeps it down on the on-side.
Starts off with a no ball! Neil Wagner steams in and serves it shorter over off stump. Stuart Broad hopes and keeps it down on the off side and the umpire signals a no ball as Wagner has overstepped.

We are all set for the play to commence on Day 3! The New Zealand players make their way out in the middle and so do, the two England batters. Ollie Pope and Stuart Broad will resume the innings for England. Neil Wagner will start the proceedings with the ball for New Zealand. Let's play...

Day 2 proved to be quite an interesting day as a pegged-back New Zealand side fought really hard with the bat and almost dusted off the entire deficit. This however wasn't quite backed up by their bowlers and England ended Day 2 with a lead of 98 runs and now have a chance to bat long and in good batting conditions as well. The hosts will need to put on a spirited performance with the ball if they are to keep the final English lead to a minimum. A crucial first session awaits.

Hello and warm welcome to one and all. It is Day 3 of the first Test match between New Zealand and England at the Bay Oval and it is set up to be yet another exciting day of cricketing action as both teams look to make a push for a favorable result. England do have the lead and look likely to put the home side under serious pressure here and it will be interesting to see how the Kiwis respond.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1...

Right then, England lead by 98 runs and there's still plenty of time left in the Test match. Day 3 is known as the moving day but every day so far has been a moving day in this game and we will hope that the game continues to move at a good pace. The visitors have their noses well in front and would want to stretch this lead at least beyond the 300-run mark. New Zealand on the other hand will look to keep the lead to a minimum as batting will definitely get a bit tougher late on Day 3 and on the remaining days as well. Do join us for the action at 6.30 am IST (1 am GMT) on Saturday. You can also catch the build-up for the day a lot earlier. Cheers!

New Zealand did extremely well to claw their way back into the game but when they had the chance to bowl with the new ball under lights, they didn't make full use of it. The lack of a second new-ball bowler cost them a bit but Blair Tickner came on as the first change and after a bit of perseverance, he got the breakthrough. After this Tim Southee bowled some probing lines but didn't get any reward. Scott Kuggeleijn came on to bowl late on in the day and picked up a wicket in his very first over and this could have been doubled if not for a miscommunication between the bowler and keeper. In the end, the Kiwis would have wanted to have picked up a couple of more wickets but the way they batted should prove to be a confidence booster for them on Day 3.

England were made to toil a bit more in the field at the start of the final session but they did get the job done and ended with a small lead of 19 runs. Under lights, Zak Crawley and Ben Duckett didn't hesitate one bit and started playing shots and sent the bad balls to the fence. The pair put on 52 runs before Duckett got out and then Crawley too followed suit by playing a lazy shot. Ollie Pope was joined by the nightwatchman Stuart Broad and the pair managed to see their team through to Day 3 without losing another scalp. They will now look to make the most use of the batting-friendly conditions early on Day 3.

End of yet another fascinating day of Test cricket here at the Bay Oval! Two days have now just breezed past in this Test match and everyone watching inside the stadium and elsewhere have had their money's worth up until now. Both New Zealand and England have gone toe-to-toe on Day 2 but in the end, the visitors will be happier of the two teams going into the moving day as they lead by 98 runs with 8 wickets in hand and better batting conditions to come early on Day 3.

Leg bye! Short of a length on leg by Scott Kuggeleijn, Stuart Broad looks to tuck this one on the leg side but fails to get any bat on it. The ball comes off his body and rolls to fine leg for a single. That will be Stumps on Day 2!
Keeps it back of a length around off, Stuart Broad stays leg side of the ball and dabs this one past gully. The ball rolls to third man but Broad refuses a single.
Back of a length on middle by Scott Kuggeleijn, Stuart Broad gets on his toes to defend this one but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Sharp bumper! Scott Kuggeleijn follows the batter and bowls it short at him, Stuart Broad gets into an awkward position and fends this one towards backward square leg. No single taken.
Back of a length but angling down the leg side, Stuart Broad tries to help it fine behind the wicket but misses.
Banged in short and at the batter from 'round the wicket, Stuart Broad ducks under it in time and lets it go through to the keeper.

Dangerous leave from Ollie Pope but he does manage to get far enough outside the crease to avoid being given out. This is on a good length around off and just angling in. Ollie Pope comes forward and then shoulders arms expecting an outswinger but the ball flicks the pad and there is an appeal from the hosts. It is quickly turned down though.
Shorter and around leg stump, Broad works it off his hips past square leg for a single.
FOUR! Slapped away! Good length outside off, Stuart Broad sees the width and goes after it. Broad thumps it over the vacant cover region for a boundary.
Another short ball, aimed at the body, Broad hops and is able to keep it down on the off side.

Halt! Stuart Broad has been rattled on the helmet and the physio comes out for the mandatory concussion assessment. He isn't happy with the new helmet and wants another one to be brought on. Thumbs up from Broad and the play will resume now.

Right on the money! Tim Southee goes for the bumper now and gets it spot on as he bowls it over middle and off and the ball just climbs up at an awkward height. Stuart Broad hops and tries to fend it away butn instead he takes a blow on the helmet. Hope he is fine.

FOUR BYES! Tim Southee comes from around the wicket and tries to angle in a full one at the toes but spills it well down the leg side. Tom Blundell puts in a big dive to his right but fails to get to it and the ball rolls away into the fence.

Oh my, that is a huge blunder from the Kiwis! Scott Kuggeleijn bangs it in short and over the stumps, Stuart Broad advances and takes on the pull shot. Broad only manages to sky it around the silly point region and the bowler and keeper both run toward it. In the end, both Kuggeleijn and Tom Blundell stop in their tracks and are left watching each other as the ball lands in the middle. A huge reprieve for Broad and he also gets a single.
Banged in short and around leg stump, Stuart Broad looks to come forward and take it on but has to adjust and takes a blow on the body.
Stuart Broad walks out to bat as the night watchman.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! A bit of a nothing shot and Zak Crawley has thrown away a good start here. Scott Kuggeleijn just bangs this one on a hard length over the off stump and the ball keeps a shade low. Crawley stays on the back foot and there's no foot movement at all. Crawley plays a lazy pull shot and gets a faint toe-end of the bat. Tom Blundell takes an easy catch behind the sticks and Kuggeleijn strikes in his first over. England now lead by 87 runs.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Blundell b Scott Kuggeleijn

Commentary.Commentary: Fuller and around middle, Pope steps out and works it leg side for a single.
Kuggeleijn sees Ollie Pope coming forward early and bangs it in short over the stumps. Pope is able to duck under it.
Starts from a bit wider of the crease and bowls it on a good length around off. Ollie Pope watchfully blocks it out.
Scott Kuggeleijn is introduced into the attack.
Maiden! This is around off and Crawley defends it out.
Full and around off, swinging away, a bit too full though to draw the batter forward.

Just a bit too high probably! Tim Southee bowls this on a length and around the pads, looking for the magic ball. Southee does get it to swing away and Zak Crawley gets wrapped high on the pads as he looks to flick. There is a loud appeal for lbw but the umpire shakes his head.
Fullish length around off, pushed away to cover.
Lovely outswinger by Tim Southee. This is pitched up around the fourth stump line and drawing the batter forward. Crawley looks to play at it but is undone completely by the swing.
Good length around the top of off, Zak Crawley blocks it out.
On a hard length and around off, Pope taps it onto the off side.
FOUR! Exquisite timing from Ollie Pope! Overpitched and outside off, Pope gets on the front foot and drives it through the big gap at cover for yet another boundary.
Fuller in length and around off, kept out by Pope.
FOUR! Nice use of the feet by Ollie Pope. Length again on middle and leg, Pope comes forward and just pushes it wide of mid on to pick up a boundary.
Good length on the pads, this is worked away behind square leg for a single. Also, Blair Tickner has overstepped and a no ball is called.
Sliding down leg! Bowls it a touch fuller and around middle, angling it in. Zak Crawley falls over a bit as he looks to flick and gets hit on the pads.
On a good length around off, Zak Crawley pats it away onto the off side.
Length ball on off stump, Ollie Pope blocks it out. A good over of Test cricket comes to an end with the batter and bowler both trading blows.

Just keeping the batter honest here. Ollie Pope is already looking to get outside the crease and Tim Southee just bowls a scrambled-seam delivery on a good length around off. Pope shoulders arms but the ball nips back in late and goes past the off stump.

FOUR! Much better from Ollie Pope and that's a brilliant shot. Fullish length outside off,m trying to swing it away, Pope advances and drives it square of the wicket through cover-point for a boundary.

Play and a miss! Perfect length from Tim Southee and bowls it outside off, Ollie Pope looks to cream the cover drive but is beaten past the outside edge as the ball seams away beautifully off the deck.
Southee keeps the ball full but brings it closer to the off stump, swinging it away. Pope makes another leave and the ball just keeps really low.
This is pitched up on the fifth stump line and swinging away. Ollie Pope leaves it alone.
Just a fraction shorter and on leg stump, Ollie Pope comes forward and works it 'round the corner for a single.
Good length around the off stump, kept out by Pope.
Good length at the stumps, Ollie Pope decides to walk down the track but ends up just blocking it back to the bowler.
Full and outside off, Ollie Pope stays watchful and leaves it alone.
Ollie Pope walks in at number 3 for England.

OUT! CAUGHT! New Zealand have their first wicket and Blair Tickner is absolutely elated! Tickner bowls it on a good length, angling it across the left-hander and keeps the line tight on off stump. Ben Duckett stays rooted to his crease and pushes at it with hard hands only to get an outside edge on it. The ball goes straight into the bread basket of Tom Latham at second slip and he holds on with both hands while tumbling over. Tickner gets the better of Duckett for the second time in this game.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Latham b Blair Tickner

Commentary.Commentary: Full and wide outside off, Ben Duckett extends his arms and slashes it away behind backward point. Kane Williamson from deep point runs around and fumbles a bit, allowing the batters to get back for the second.
Pitches it up outside off, and Zak Crawley just lets it through to the keeper.
Bowls it fuller and outside off, Crawley looks to drive but gets a leading edge onto the off side.
Another quick run and the 50 is up for England! Back of a length around off, tapped away straight to point for one.
Good length, on a tight line around off stump. Ben Duckett just has a feel for it and gets beaten on the outside edge.

Risky single! A length ball around off, Zak Crawley hits it firmly to the right of cover where Kane Williamson makes a half-stop and they go for the run. Neil Wagner then picks up the ball and has a shy at the bowler's end. He misses and the replays show that Crawley was well home anyway.
Slightly shorter and outside off, Ben Duckett cuts it toward deep point for a single.

FOUR! This time on the other side of the wicket. Back of a length around middle, Zak Crawley short-arm jabs it well in front of square on the on-side and picks up back-to-back boundaries. England are off to a flier once again.
FOUR! Hit on the up! Pitched up around off, Zak Crawley punches it in between extra cover and mid off and finds the fence. Excellent timing on that.
Goes full and straight now, Crawley drives it straight to short mid on.
Just a fraction fuller and on off stump, Crawley blocks it out.
On a good length just over off stump, Zak Crawley gets pushed onto the back foot and ends up edging it down to the slip cordon with soft hands.
Good length around the pads, Duckett tucks it away in front of square leg for an easy single.
Full and wide again, Duckett throws his hands at it and slashes it toward deep point for a single.
Nicely bowled! Immaculate length, close to the off stump and straightening a touch as well. Duckett has a little nibble at it but the ball zips past the outside edge.

EDGED AND FOUR! Nagging length, brings the ball close to the off stump and draws the batter forward. Ben Duckett leans forward to drive but gets a thick outside edge that flies wide of the man at second slip and rolls into the fence.

A bit of a loose shot from Duckett this time around. Tim Southee pushes this one well outside the off stump and keeps the length full. Duckett looks for the expansive drive away from the body but is beaten.
Full and around off, driven firmly to short cover.
FOUR! That's impressive from Ben Duckett. A good-length ball, angling in a long way from well outside off. Duckett stays back and plays it very late as he just taps it behind point for a boundary.
Goes full now and bowls it around off, Crawley drives it straight to cover.
Good length around the top of off, tentatively kept out by Crawley.

FOUR! New Zealand continue to just keep on conceding boundaries. This is short and over off, Zak Crawley gets in a great position and muscles it well in front of square on the leg side for a boundary.
Bangs it in a bit and bowls it just outside off, Zak Crawley looks to hop and cut it over point but is beaten by the extra bounce.
Back of a length around off, this is kept down on the off side.
Starts off with a good-length delivery over off stump, Zak Crawley goes on the back foot and eases it toward cover.
Blair Tickner comes into the attack now.
Back of a length on off, Ben Duckett punches this one off the back foot but fails to beat Michael Bracewell at cover-point.
Length delivery on middle, Ben Duckett gets behind and pushes it to mid on.
On a length on off by Tim Southee, Ben Duckett hangs back and defends. The ball drops at his feet and he keeps it out from rolling onto the stumps. .
Switches to 'round the wicket and goes full around off, Ben Duckett gets forward to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge.
FOUR! Cut away by Ben Duckett! A fraction short and outside off, Ben Duckett uses the angle to his advantage and cuts it past backward point for a boundary.
Full and outside off, Ben Duckett drives it off the front foot to mid off.
Full and angling away on off, Zak Crawley takes a stride forward and defends it on the off side.
FOUR MORE! Short again and outside off, Zak Crawley frees his arms and cuts it late this time. Gets it past backward point for yet another boundary.

FOUR! Short and punished by Zak Crawley! Neil Wagner goes a bit short this time and outside off, it sits up nicely for the batter. Zak Crawley stays on the back foot and cuts it through covers for a boundary.
On a length and outside off, Zak Crawley shapes to cut this one but shoulders his arms at the last moment.
Fuller and outside off from over the wicket,, Zak Crawley shoulders arms and leaves the ball alone.
FOUR! Full and going across outside off, Zak Crawley frees his arms and slices this one past backward point for his first boundary.
Full and slanting at the pads, Zak Crawley clips this one along the ground to deep square leg and retains the strike with a single.
Full and outside off, Zak Crawley goes for the drive without much foot movement and gets beaten on the outside edge.
Goes full again and in the channel outside off, Zak Crawley solidly blocks this one out down the wicket.
Full and around off by Tim Southee, Zak Crawley takes a stride forward and defends it to cover.
Length delivery angling at the pads, Zak Crawley turns this one to mid-wicket.
On a good length and swinging away outside off, a loose shot by Zak Crawley as he drives away from the body. He is lucky to not get an edge there.
FOUR! Keeps it full and just outside off, Ben Duckett gets the width he needs and pounces on it. Drives this one to the left of mid off and collects a boundary.
Goes full again and allows the ball to swing away on off, Ben Duckett drives it with a straight bat to mid on.
Full and going away on off, Ben Duckett gets forward and solidly blocks this one out.
Length delivery on off, Ben Duckett stays back and defends it on the leg side.
On a length and outside off, Ben Duckett pushes this one towards cover but fails to find the gap.
Full and swinging away on off by Neil Wagner, Ben Duckett gets behind the line and defends it back to the bowler.
Neil Wagner to bowl from the other end.
Beauty! On a length and just outside off, the ball straightens after pitching, Zak Crawley looks to defend this one but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Full and going across outside off, Ben Duckett drives this one a bit uppishly but wide of mid off. Scott Kuggeleijn performs the chase and puts in a dive to save a run for his side.
Goes full this time and shaping in on middle, Ben Duckett gets across and works it to mid-wicket.
Length delivery swinging into the batter on middle, Ben Duckett gets behind the line and defends it down the wicket.
Strays at the pads on a length, Zak Crawley tucks this one to square leg and opens his account with a single.
Starts with a back-of-a-length delivery in the channel outside off, a hint of away movement, Zak Crawley shoulders arms and leaves the ball alone.

Right then, that's all from this game. It is England who have drawn first blood in the series, winning the first Test by 267 runs and will now be eying a 2-0 whitewash. On the other hand, New Zealand will look to put up a better show in the second Test and draw level in the series. The second and final Test of this series begins on Friday, 24th February at the Basin Reserve in Wellington. The first ball will be at 3.30 am IST (10.00 pm GMT). As always, you can join us in advance for the build-up. Until then, take care and goodbye!

Ben Stokes, the skipper of England, says that they were clinical in both departments. Adds that they executed their plans with the pink ball under the lights and it was always going to be tough for anyone against Stuart Broad and James Anderson. Feels that they managed to react well to whatever was thrown at them by New Zealand. Also says that it was an entertaining game and it was what everyone wanted. Ends by saying that Harry Brook is a fantastic talent and he is going to be a global superstar.

Tim Southee, the skipper of New Zealand, says that it is disappointing and credits England for the way they played. Adds that the decision to bowl first was right but the way England batted was brilliant. Feels that they needed to stem the flow of runs and create chances. Also mentions that Stuart Broad bowled exceptionally well last night. Ends by saying that it will be a different challenge at the Basin Reserve and his team are looking forward to that game.

Harry Brook is the Player of the Match for scoring fifties in both innings. He says that there was no standout performer in this game and everyone contributed equally well. Adds that bowlers in particular bowled extremely well on this docile pitch. Feels that it did help with New Zealand bowling short balls. Shares that he stuck to his strengths and took on the bowlers. Ends by saying that he is excited to bat every time and he is happy that he is carrying on from his form in Pakistan.
Time for the Presentations...

England though impressed with the bat yet again and set New Zealand a target of close to 400 with three of their batters scoring 50s. Their bowlers then were ruthless as they ran riot in the last session of Day 3. Broad was at his best then. Day 4 though belonged to James Anderson and Jack Leach who made quick work of the lower order to complete a comprehensive win.

To be honest, New Zealand were just outplayed. Things just did not go their way, whereas, for England, every move they made worked. First, after being inserted, they managed to score 325 with Harry Brook impressing yet again. Also, they weren't bowled out but declared on the last session of Day 1. That decision proved to be a good one as they managed to bag three wickets before Stumps. They had New Zealand staring down the barrel at 83 for 5. Had it not been for Tom Blundell who scored a brilliant ton, England would have gotten a big lead. Courtesy of that superb knock, the lead was just a slender one.
A thumping win for the visitors and England's impressive form in the longer format continues. They needed five wickets heading into Day 4 to win this game and they wrapped it up quite quickly.
OUT! TIMBER! That is it. It is Anderson who finishes it off. Goes length again and on off, Tickner plays down the wrong line and misses. It hit the top of off. England win by 267 runs.
Commentary.Howout: b James Anderson

Commentary.Commentary: Goes Fuller this time and on middle, Tickner was ready for it as he defends.
Bangs it short and on the body. Blair defends.
Bangs this short and on middle, this is pulled but to square leg. Mitchell fails to take the one.
Halt! The umpires are unhappy with the seam of this ball and have called for a replacement. All good to go now.
Fuller and on off, it is driven back to the bowler. One ball to go in the over.
Bangs it short, this is pulled to mid-wicket.
FOUR! Another lovely shot from Mitchell. Fuller and around off, this is driven through covers for a boundary.
Another pull shot towards deep square leg. No run taken.
Angled into the pads, this is worked down to fine leg for one.
A harmless nut to end! Down the leg side. Left alone.
Another short one on middle, Blair Tickner backs away and defends.
That surely must have hurt! A short one, it does not rise a lot. Blair Tickner takes his eyes off the ball as he tries to fend at it. It hits the arm and lobs to leg gully.
A rib-tickler this time, Blair looks to flick but misses.
Another short one around off, Tickner lets it go to the keeper.
A short one on the body, Tickner ducks under it.
James Anderson (9-2-18-3) returns to the attack.
A full toss to end, Daryl Mitchell pushes it to mid on.
FOUR! Hammered away! Fifty for Mitchell. His impressive start to his Test career continues. He has fought a lone battle here. Gets there by pulling this nicely through square leg for a boundary.
Another short one and on middle, Mitchell pulls again but towards deep square leg.
Back of a length and on off, blocked.
Another short one on middle, Daryl Mitchell pulls again but on runs taken.
Bangs it short and on the body, this is pulled down to fine leg.
On middle, blocked.
Flatter and on off, Tickner guides it through point but no run taken.
Gives it air and lands it on off, nicely defended.
Pushes it through on middle, blocked.
Tossed up this time on off, Tickner defends it off the front foot.
Flatter and on middle, defended.
Finds the fielder! Fuller and around off, Mitchell shows the full face of the bat and strokes it to covers. A good shot but for no runs. Fails to retain strike.
FOUR! That is a superb pull shot. So very controlled and Mitchell is one short of a half ton. Shorter and on middle, this is pulled through mid-wicket and it races away to the fence.
Shorter and on middle, Mitchell pulls it down to long on for two more.
Shorter and on the body, this is pulled towards fine leg. No run taken.
Two more! A low full toss, Broad goes for another yorker but Mitchell walks down and makes it into a full toss, he pushes it down towards long on for two.
A yorker on middle, Mitchell jams it back to the bowler.
Flatter and outside off, left alone.
On middle, pushed through, this is pushed to cover.
On the stumps, kept out.
On off, defended.
On off, defended.
On off, this is pushed to cover.
Goes full around off, Daryl Mitchell solidly blocks this one out.
FOUR! Angled in on a length on leg, Daryl Mitchell stays in the crease and helps it past short fine leg. The ball was in the air for a bit but well wide of that fielder.
Fullish delivery on off by Stuart Broad, Daryl Mitchell digs this one out back to the bowler.
Shortens his length and bowls it on off, Daryl Mitchell gets behind the line and keeps it out.
Goes full and at the pads, Daryl Mitchell works it to fine leg and refuses a single.
Bowls it back of a length on off, Daryl Mitchell hangs back and defends it down the wicket.

Drinks! England are one wicket away from winning this first Test and taking a 1-0 lead in the series. They have taken four wickets in this first hour with James Anderson accounting for three of those. On the other hand, New Zealand would have wanted to put up a fight at the start of the day but they have failed to do so. Daryl Mitchell has been the lone survivor and he is 13 runs away from his fifty.
Bowls it short and just outside off, Blair Tickner goes back and keeps this one out.
Tossed up, full outside off, Daryl Mitchell paddles this one towards short fine leg and takes a single.
Full and turning away outside off, Daryl Mitchell pushes this one towards point.
Short and on middle, Daryl Mitchell stays on the back foot and defends.
SIX! Good shot! Jack Leach floats this one full and outside off, Daryl Mitchell uses his feet and lofts this one over long off for a maximum.
Short and slower outside off, Daryl Mitchell shoulders arms and leaves the ball alone.
FOUR! Stuart Broad bowls it full and around off, Blair Tickner stays leg side of the ball and leans into the drive. Gets it to the right of mid off and the ball trickles to the fence.
Back of a length on off, Blair Tickner hangs back and keeps this one out.
FOUR! Edgy! On a good length and outside off, Blair Tickner throws his hands at the ball and pushes away from the body. Gets a thickish outside edge that goes past gully for a boundary.
Short of a length and wide outside off, Blair Tickner is in no mood to play those and lets it go.
Goes short again and on middle, Blair Tickner drops his hands and lets the ball go through to the keeper.
Starts with a shorter delivery outside off, Blair Tickner sways away and leaves the ball alone.
Stuart Broad (10-5-21-4) comes back on.
Keeps it full and on off, Daryl Mitchell gets behind the line and blocks this one out. It will be Blair Tickner on strike for the next over.
Fired in full and on off, Daryl Mitchell plants his front foot forward and defends.
Flighted, full on off, Daryl Mitchell gets on the front foot and keeps it out.
Full and around off, Daryl Mitchell steers this one towards point.
Tossed up, full on off, Daryl Mitchell gets forward and defends it down the wicket.
Bowls it short and outside off, Daryl Mitchell goes back in the crease and pushes it to deep cover. Denies a single.
Full and swinging in on middle, Blair Tickner stays leg side of the ball and keeps this one out.
Blair Tickner is the last man in for New Zealand.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Another one bites the dust! James Anderson bowls this one on a good length outside off from over the wicket, Neil Wagner goes for a drive away from his body and without any foot movement. Gets an outside edge that is pouched safely by Ben Foakes behind the wicket. James Anderson gets his third wicket and the end is now near for New Zealand.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Foakes b James Anderson

Commentary.Commentary: Slower and into the wicket, Neil Wagner waits for it and steers this one to backward point.
Length delivery around off, Daryl Mitchell taps this one towards cover and takes a single.
On a good length around off, the ball straightens after pitching, Daryl Mitchell looks to defend but gets an outside edge that rolls towards the slip cordon.
Back of a length on off by James Anderson, Neil Wagner stays on the back foot and dabs it towards backward point for a quick single.
Goes full again on off, Daryl Mitchell gets on the front foot and defends it down the wicket.
Floated, full outside off, Daryl Mitchell takes a stride forward and keeps this one out.
Flighted, full on off, Daryl Mitchell gets forward and pushes it to cover.
Fullish delivery on off, Daryl Mitchell squeezes this one out towards cover.
Full around off, Daryl Mitchell smothers the ball on the off side.
SIX! Jack Leach tosses this one full on off, Daryl Mitchell steps out and frees his arms. Lofts this one over mid on and it goes all the way for a maximum.
On a good length  and swinging in on middle, Neil Wagner tries to get behind the line and defend but gets an inside edge back onto his pads.
FOUR! Switches to over the wicket and angles this one short and outside off, Neil Wagner stands tall and punches this one past backward point. Collects his first boundary of the innings.
Back of a length on off by James Anderson, Neil Wagner hangs back and pushes it towards cover.
Bowls this one full and on off, Neil Wagner solidly keeps this one out.
Another well-directed bouncer by James Anderson, Neil Wagner ducks and lets it go through to the keeper.
Goes short and at the batter, Neil Wagner takes his eyes off the ball and wears the ball on his chest.
Full and slanting in on middle by Jack Leach, Daryl Mitchell defends it back to the bowler.
Full and drifting in on off, Daryl Mitchell defends it off the front foot.
Bowls it full and on off, Daryl Mitchell knocks it to mid off for a dot.
Short and flatter outside off, Daryl Mitchell shoulders arms and lets it go.
Full and on middle, Daryl Mitchell gets behind the line and pushes it to back to the bowler.
Full and drifting in on middle, Daryl Mitchell gets on the front foot and defends.
Goes full this time and swinging in outside off, Neil Wagner goes for the drive but gets an inside edge back onto his front pad.
Sharp bumper by James Anderson, Neil Wagner ducks under it and lets it go.
Goes length again and bowls it on off, Neil Wagner drives this one uppishly but to the left of James Anderson. Collects a couple of runs towards the mid on region.
Length delivery on middle, Neil Wagner gets behind the line and defends it down the wicket.
Switches to 'round the wicket and bangs it in short and at the batter, Neil Wagner goes for the hook but fails to connect.
On a good length on off, a hint of inward movement, Daryl Mitchell gets across and works it towards square leg for a single.
Floats this one full on off, Neil Wagner solidly blocks this one out on the off side.
Fullish delivery angling in on middle, Daryl Mitchell knocks it down to long on and rotates the strike.
Full and on off by Jack Leach, Daryl Mitchell pushes this one back to the bowler.
Persists with full length on off, Daryl Mitchell defends from the front foot.
Keeps it full and around off, Daryl Mitchell gets on the front foot and smothers the ball on the off side.
Full and drifting in on off, Daryl Mitchell presses forward and defends it back to the bowler.
On a good length angling outside off from 'round the wicket, Neil Wagner drives it on the up and through covers for a couple of runs.
Almost a yorker length around off, Neil Wagner goes for the drive but gets beaten on the inside edge.
Shortens his length and bowls it on off, Daryl Mitchell stays on the back foot and taps it towards the vacant cover region for a single.
Full and angling in on middle, Daryl Mitchell takes a stride forward and defends it on the leg side.
Goes full and at the stumps, Daryl Mitchell looks to get behind the line to defend but gets an outside edge that goes on the bounce towards the slip cordon.
Bowls back of a length and angling on middle and leg, Daryl Mitchell hangs back and taps it to mid-wicket.
Short and on middle, Neil Wagner goes back in the crease and keeps it out.
Sees the batter advance and bowls it slower and short at him, Neil Wagner plays with the turn and pushes it to short mid-wicket.
Floated, full outside off, Neil Wagner works it to short mid-wicket.
Pushed through full on middle, Neil Wagner gets on the front foot but gets an inside edge that goes wide of short leg.
Short and at the batter, Neil Wagner stays on the back foot and defends.
Goes a fraction short and turning away outside off, Daryl Mitchell stays on the back foot and punches it to deep cover for a single.
Neil Wagner walks out to the middle.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! Make that wicket number 251 in Tests overseas. Absolutely brilliant and New Zealand are now 8 down. This inswinger did the trick against Scott Kuggeleijn and the outswinger is too good for Southee. That though was a nothing stroke. It is on a length and outside off, Southee pokes at it tentatively and away from the body, it goes off the outside edge, low to Joe Root at first slip. He makes no mistake.
Commentary.Howout: c Joe Root b James Anderson

Commentary.Commentary: The New Zealand skipper Tim Southee comes out to bat.

HAVE ENGLAND GOT ANOTHER ONE? The umpire has raised his finger but Scott Kuggeleijn reviews. Looks out though. ULTRA EDGE CONFIRMS NO BAT! OUT! THREE REDS! England now three wickets away. Scott Kuggeleijn walks back and takes a review along. This is the fullest ball Anderson has bowled in this over. It starts on off and then tails back in a touch. Scott Kuggeleijn plants his front foot a little too across and looks to put bat on ball but misses to get hit on the pads. An appeal and the finger is raised. Anderson now has 250 wickets overseas. A true great.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b James Anderson

Commentary.Commentary: Back of a length and on off, Scott Kuggeleijn guides it through point. Stokes runs after it and then tries to flick it for the person running behind but ends up flicking it for himself. Two taken.
Good length and on off, a little bit of extra bounce. Defended.
Slightly shorter, this is pulled but to mid-wicket.
Slightly shorter and on the body, this is pulled towards deep square leg for one.

A good nut to end! Pushes it through this time, drags his length back a touch, this lands and spins away. Scott Kuggeleijn is beaten as he tries to defend. They did go upstairs to check for the stumping but Scott Kuggeleijn is in.
Slows it up, gives it air and lands it on off, this is pushed to mid off.
Scott Kuggeleijn is the new man in.

OUT! TAKEN! That is a soft, soft dismissal and the move to begin with Leach has worked. England only 4 wickets away now. This is tossed up outside off, it turns back in a touch. Michael Bracewell looks to flick, the ball holds in the surface and hence, Michael Bracewell is through the shot, in the end, he chips it to mid-wicket where it is taken by Brook.
Commentary.Howout: c Harry Brook b Jack Leach

Commentary.Commentary: Pushes this one through and lands it on off, Michael Bracewell stays back and blocks.
Slightly shorter and on middle, Michael Bracewell works it but it hits the fielder at short leg.
Slightly shorter and outside off, this is pushed through covers for one.
A maiden then to begin with by Anderson! On a length and around off, blocked.
Another dot! Angles it into the pads, this is worked to square leg.
A little bit of more zip this time, runs in and lands it on a length and outside off, left alone.
Another gentle length delivery on off, Michael Bracewell stays back and blocks.
A little bit of inward movement but the line is down the leg side. Michael Bracewell looks to flick but misses.
Angled into middle, Anderson bowls it from around the wicket, it is worked to mid-wicket.
James Anderson will bowl from the other end.
Full and drifting in on off, Daryl Mitchell presses forward and keeps it out.
Another full delivery on off, Daryl Mitchell gets on the front foot and smothers the ball on the off side.
Fullish delivery on middle, Daryl Mitchell squeezes this one out down the wicket.
Full and quicker at the stumps by Jack Leach, Daryl Mitchell gets forward and defends it back to the bowler.

FOUR! Daryl Mitchell and New Zealand are underway on Day 4! Loopy delivery, low full toss at the stumps, Daryl Mitchell does not miss out as drives this one with a straight bat. Gets it to the left of mid on for the first boundary of the day.
Starts with a flighted delivery, full on off, Daryl Mitchell gets behind the line and defends it off the front foot.

We are all set for the play to commence on Day 4! The umpires and players make their way out in the middle. Daryl Mitchell and Michael Bracewell will resume their innings for New Zealand. Jack Leach will start the proceedings with the ball for England. Here we go...

New Zealand had an off day on Day 3 and conceded way too many runs trying to bounce the English batters out and were a bit unlucky to have to face the new ball completely under lights. Stuart Broad wrecked havoc and the hosts found themselves with half the side back in the hut and a mountain and a half to climb. Can they put on a bit of fight and frustrate the visitors? Or will the English bowling attack tear through the remaining batters? We shall find out soon as the start of Day 4 isn't far away.

Hello and a warm welcome everyone to Day 4 of the first Test between New Zealand and England at the Bay Oval in Mount Manganui. The game flowed at quite a rapid pace on Day 3 as a total of 13 wickets fell and currently, the visitors are in pole position to go on and get the win on Day 4 itself.
... DAY 4, SESSION 1 ...

Right then, New Zealand still need 331 runs to win and have just five wickets in hand. It is more than just a tough ask and the game seems to be going in favor of England. But, one thing that is guaranteed is that there will be a fight shown by the Kiwis, how long it lasts is a different thing though. Can England clean up the hosts early on Day 4? Or will they face some stern resistance under the warm sun? Join us at 6.30 am IST (1 am GMT) on Sunday to find out. You can catch the build-up a lot earlier as well. Cheers!

England ended Day 1 in a commanding position and after a bit of a fight from the hosts on the second day, the visitors are now well and truly on the verge of victory. This is largely due to their solid batting effort and a scintillating spell by Stuart Broad under the lights. Broad bowled 10 overs on the trot but he did all the damage early on as he picked up four out of the five wickets. Broad got the ball to come into right and left-handers alike and ripped through the Kiwi top order. Ollie Robinson supported him well and now they will look to come out on Day 4 and wrap up the game in the first session or so.

New Zealand failed to bowl out England in the second session and whilst they did eventually get the job done, it was right around when the lights started to take full effect. Just like late on Day 1, the Kiwis lost wickets in heap late on Day 3 and were soon five down for just 28 runs. After that, Daryl Mitchell and Michael Bracewell weathered the storm and as the ball got a bit older, scoring became easy as well. The pair has done well but will need to at least bat the whole of the first session on Day 4 together to give their side an outside chance.

Three days have now gone by in the first Test between New Zealand and England and it has been blockbuster entertainment on all three days. Day 3 started with England leading by 98 runs and they managed to just keep scoring whilst losing wickets and ended up with a big lead of 393 runs. Currently, the hosts are reeling at 63 for 5 and would need more than a miracle to escape defeat with two full days of action remaining.
Bowls it full and on leg, Michael Bracewell solidly keeps this one out. That will be Stumps on Day 3!
Short and flatter around off, Michael Bracewell leaves the ball alone once again.
Flighted delivery, full outside off, Michael Bracewell shoulders arms and lets it go.
Fuller and outside off, Michael Bracewell is in no mood to play at those and lets it go.
Short and on off, Michael Bracewell accounts for the away turn and defends it on the off side.
Fired in full and quicker at the stumps, Michael Bracewell gets behind the line and defends.
Joe Root has now been thrown the ball for probably what will be the final over of the day.
Tossed up, full on middle, Michael Bracewell works this one towards square leg and retains the strike with a single.
Flighted, full on leg, Michael Bracewell smothers the ball on the leg side.
Short and at the stumps, Michael Bracewell stays on the back foot and keeps it out.

Was that a chance? Jack Leach keeps it short and turning in on leg, Michael Bracewell shapes to work this fine on the leg side. Gets it low and to the left of leg slip, Zak Crawley there fails to react quickly and a tough chance goes down.
Short and on middle and leg, Michael Bracewell turns this one to mid-wicket.

Short and turning in on leg, Michael Bracewell goes back in his crease and clips this one uppishly towards deep mid-wicket. Ben Duckett fires in a throw at the non-striker's end but does not hit. It would not have mattered anyway as Daryl Mitchell was safely in. Two runs taken.
Time for some spin right at the end of the day as Jack Leach comes on to bowl.
Good stop! Banged in short and at the batter, Michael Bracewell stands tall and pulls this one hard towards deep square leg. Ben Duckett stationed there dives to his left and keeps it to one.
Length delivery on off, Daryl Mitchell taps it towards point and takes a single.
Good-length delivery outside off, Daryl Mitchell pushes at the delivery away from his body but gets beaten on the outside edge.

Back of a length and seaming in on middle, Daryl Mitchell defends this one with an angled bat. Gets an inside edge that goes back onto his front pad. The ball lobs off his pad but in front of him and Ben Foakes cannot get there despite standing up to the stumps.
On a good length around off, Daryl Mitchell takes a stride forward to defend but gets it from the outer part of the bat towards backward point.

FOUR! Easy pickings! A rare loose delivery from Ollie Robinson, bowls this one back of a length angling down the leg side, Daryl Mitchell tucks this one off the back foot towards the fine leg region for a boundary.
Shorter and over middle, Daryl Mitchell works it toward square leg for one and brings up 1000 runs in Test cricket as well.
Good length around middle, blocked out.

Sharp reflexes from Ollie Pope. Fullish length, sliding onto middle and leg, Mitchell clip it to the left of short leg where Pope makes the stop and keeps the batter honest by throwing it right back to the keeper in a flash.
A fraction shorter and over middle and leg, Michael Bracewell dabs it on the leg side for a single.
A length ball on the pads, this is pushed away toward wide mid on for a run.
This is pitched up on off stump, Michael Bracewell gets on the front foot and firmly pushes it through mid off. Jack Leach chases it down and they come back for the third run with ease.
Another short ball over leg stump, this is pulled down to deep mid-wicket for a single.

FOUR! A bit of aggression shown for the first time by New Zealand. This is banged in short and over middle, Michael Bracewell takes it on and pulls it high and over wide mid-wicket. Stuart Broad gives the chase and puts in the dive as well but the ball just beats him into the fence.
Full and on the pads, this is nudged away through mid-wicket for a single.

Halt! Daryl Mitchell pulled up at the striker's end after completing the run and called for the physio immediately. After being treated for cramps on his right hamstring, Mitchell is up on his feet and we are good to go.
Good running! Good length around off, Michael Bracewell blocks it with soft hands in front of cover and scampers through for the single.
Good length again over middle, Bracewell blocks it out.
Good length, close to the off stump, Michael Bracewell gets an inside edge onto the pads as he looks to block.
A tad shorter and on the pads, Mitchell tucks it off bat and pad toward square leg.
Fullish length on off stump and nipping back in. Daryl Mitchell looks to flick but gets an inside edge onto the on-side.
Full and straight, nudged away onto the leg side.
Length ball around off, this is nudged down behind point.
On a good length and outside off, Mitchell looks to play at it but is beaten on the outside edge. The ball though dies on its way to the keeper.
A tad shorter and down leg, Daryl Mitchell clips it off the thigh pad and down toward leg gully.
Around the top of off, kept out.
Back to around the wicket and pitches it up on off stump, Michael Bracewell defends it out.
Full and on leg stump, this is wristed away toward mid-wicket.

FOUR! Lovely on drive from Michael Bracewell. Ollie Robinson comes from over the wicket and pitches it up on middle and leg, Bracewell simply punches it to the right of mid on and the ball rolls away into the fence.
Full, on middle and leg, flicked away straight to mid-wicket.
Just short of a good length and around off, angling in. Michael Bracewell looks to block but misses and gets hit on the thigh pad.
Another maiden! An unexpected full toss on middle, Daryl Mitchell manages to push it down in front of mid on.
Keeps the length fuller and tries to attack the pads, Mitchell blocks it off the front foot.
A bit fuller and angling into the pads, Mitchell looks to flick but ends up squeezing it onto the off side.
Back of a length and on the body, Mitchell keeps it down on the leg side.
Good length outside off, edged down with soft hands toward third slip.
On a length, angled in from outside off but straightens off the deck, Daryl Mitchell pushes at it but is beaten on the outside edge.
Good length over middle, this is nudged away toward mid-wicket for a quick run.
Full and wide of the off stump, sliced away to the left of point where the fielder makes a good stop.

Overthrows and four of them! Good length around off, Michael Bracewell bunts it out toward cover and sets off for the quick single. The fielder there picks up the ball and fires in a wayward throw at the bowler's end. Stuart Broad who is backing up fails to stop it and the ball trickles away into the fence.
Bowled from over the wicket and on middle and leg, Michael Bracewell flicks it leg side.
Good length around the top of off, Michael Bracewell keeps it out.
Full and outside off, strokes away toward covers for a quick single.
A wicket-maiden! Hard length around off stump, Michael Bracewell gets behind the line and makes the block.
Length again but a bit outside off and Bracewell leaves it alone.
Length again, angled in from around off, Michael Bracewell defends it off the front foot.
Stuart Broad steams in from around the wicket and angles in a good-length ball onto the off stump. Michael Bracewell keeps it out.
Michael Bracewell walks in at number 7.

OUT! CLEANED HIM UP! Stuart Broad sends the first-innings centurion back into the hut and picks up his fourth wicket. Broad pitches this one up around off and gets the ball to nip back in off the deck. Tom Blundell stands a bit out of his crease and just looks to defend it with a straight bat. The ball goes through the gap between the bat and pad and castles into the stumps. New Zealand have lost half their side now and are in serious danger of being bowled out before Day 3 even ends.
Commentary.Howout: b Stuart Broad

Commentary.Commentary: A bit fuller and angled onto middle, Blundell blocks it out.
Good leave! On a length and angling in a bit from outside off, Daryl Mitchell stands well outside his crease and leaves it alone.
Drop and run! Good length around off, Tom Blundell bunts it out in front of point and scampers through for the quick and gets off the mark as well.
A length ball outside off, Blundell pushes it out toward point.
Goes fuller now and attacks the stumps, Blundell keeps it out.

There's something happening on almost every delivery out there at the moment. Lovely delivery from Ollie Robinson as he bowls it on a good length around off. The ball seams back in a long way and as Tom Blundell looks to block, he gets beaten between bat and pad.
Pitched up, wider of the off stump and angled in. Tom Blundell shoulders arms.

Drinks! England are all over New Zealand at the moment and are 6 wickets away from taking a 1-0 lead in the series. Stuart Broad has been the wrecker-in-chief with 3 wickets and is bowling an exceptional spell here. On the other hand, New Zealand have failed to counter the movement on offer and have lost their top four batters. The onus is now on this pair to get them through till stumps without any more loss of wickets.
Maiden! Fuller in length, attacking middle stump, Daryl Mitchell punches it off the front foot toward mid on.
A touch fuller and outside off, left alone by Mitchell.
Good length, angling into middle and leg, kept out on the leg side.
A length ball on middle and leg, Mitchell pushes it with soft hands to short mid-wicket.
Slightly pitched up on off stump, Daryl Mitchell blocks it out.
On a good length but angled well down the leg side, this is left alone for the keeper to collect.
Good length around middle, Blundell presents a dead bat at it.
Goes wider and angles it into middle and leg, Tom Blundell pushes it to the left of silly mid on.
Pitches it up in and around off stump, Tom Blundell blocks it out.
The centurion of the first innings Tom Blundell comes out to bat.

OUT! EDGED AND GONE! England looking to wrap things up in a hurry here. Ollie Robinson stays over the wicket and bowls this one back of a length and close to the off stump. The ball deviates away off the deck and Henry Nicholls is caught on the back foot. Nicholls ends up just dabbing at it and the outside edge is taken. Ben Foakes dives to his left and takes a good catch. New Zealand are four down now with more than an hour of play left on Day 3.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Foakes b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: On a hard length and angled well across the off stump, Henry Nicholls shoulders arms.

A bit of a loosener from Ollie Robinson as he serves a low full toss wide of the off stump. Daryl Mitchell reaches out and just eases it through the cover-region. Stuart Broad gives chase and keeps it in play. Mitchell gets off the mark right away with a three.
Pitched up around middle and off, Henry Nicholls gets on the front foot and defends it out.
Beaten! On a length and angled in from around off, this one straightens off the angle and beats the outside edge of Nicholls' bat.
A bit fuller and outside off, going straight through and dying on its way to the keeper.
Keeps it on a good length but brings the line closer to the off pole, Nicholls makes the block.
Good length, angling in a bit from outside off and Nicholls shoulders arms to it.
This is full and on off stump, Henry Nicholls squeezes the drive through the cover region and picks up a couple of runs.
Switches to over the wicket for the final delivery and bowls it full on the pads. Henry Nicholls flicks it down to fine leg for one.
Good length, hitting the top of middle and Nicholls stays solid in defense.
Streaky but will do. Full and outside off, Henry Nicholls goes for the square drive but gets it off the outer half of the bat through cover-point. They come back for two.
Well left! Fuller and around off stump, going straight on, Nicholls leaves it alone.
Good length around middle, blocked with soft hands onto the on-side.
On a length close to the off stump and blocked out by Henry Nicholls.
Daryl Mitchell is the new man in.
